const RAW_MD_HISTORY = "## Single Correct (SCQ)\n\nQ1. Who among the following first proposed that certain groups of three chemically similar elements show the atomic mass of the middle element close to the arithmetic mean of the other two?\n\n(a) Dobereiner\n\n(b) Newlands\n\n(c) Mendeleev\n\n(d) Moseley\n\nQ2. The classical examples of Dobereiner's Law of Triads (alkali metals, alkaline earth metals, halogens, and chalcogens) illustrate that the law could be meaningfully applied to:\n\n(a) All 63 elements known in 1829\n\n(b) Only a small number of chemically similar triads such as alkali metals, alkaline earth metals and halogens\n\n(c) All elements of the third period\n\n(d) Only the noble gases\n\nQ3. Newlands' Law of Octaves is best described by which analogy to musical structure?\n\n(a) A continuous, non-repeating melody\n\n(b) A scale of twelve semitones\n\n(c) The repetition of an element's properties after every eighth element, similar to octaves in music\n\n(d) A triad chord\n\nQ4. Which of the following was NOT a recognized shortcoming of Newlands' Law of Octaves?\n\n(a) It assumed only 56 elements existed in nature\n\n(b) It broke down for elements heavier than calcium\n\n(c) Some dissimilar elements were forced into the same slot\n\n(d) It correctly predicted the existence and properties of germanium before its discovery\n\nQ5. Mendeleev's Periodic Law, as originally stated, asserts that the properties of elements are periodic functions of their:\n\n(a) Atomic mass\n\n(b) Atomic number\n\n(c) Number of valence electrons\n\n(d) Ionic radius\n\nQ6. Mendeleev predicted the properties of an undiscovered element he called \"eka-aluminium.\" The element later discovered and found to closely fit this prediction is:\n\n(a) Germanium\n\n(b) Gallium\n\n(c) Scandium\n\n(d) Technetium\n\nQ7. In Mendeleev's periodic table, tellurium (atomic mass approximately 127.60) was placed before iodine (atomic mass approximately 126.90), reversing the strict order of atomic mass. This exception was made because:\n\n(a) Iodine's atomic mass was measured incorrectly at the time\n\n(b) Mendeleev had not yet discovered iodine\n\n(c) Placing tellurium before iodine kept each element in a group with chemically similar elements\n\n(d) The atomic number of iodine was unknown\n\nQ8. The scientist who established that the characteristic X-ray frequency emitted by an element bombarded with high-energy electrons increases by a fixed, predictable amount from one element to the next in the periodic sequence was:\n\n(a) J.J. Thomson\n\n(b) Lothar Meyer\n\n(c) William Ramsay\n\n(d) Henry Moseley\n\nQ9. According to the Modern Periodic Law, the physical and chemical properties of elements are periodic functions of their:\n\n(a) Atomic number\n\n(b) Atomic mass\n\n(c) Atomic volume\n\n(d) Valency alone\n\nQ10. The long form of the periodic table, based on the electronic configuration of elements, contains how many periods and groups respectively?\n\n(a) 6 periods, 16 groups\n\n(b) 7 periods, 18 groups\n\n(c) 8 periods, 18 groups\n\n(d) 7 periods, 16 groups\n\nQ11. A key advantage of the Modern Periodic Law over Mendeleev's atomic-mass-based law is that it:\n\n(a) Removed the need for any periods or groups\n\n(b) Eliminated the s, p, d, f block classification\n\n(c) Correctly explains the position of isotopes, since all isotopes of an element share the same atomic number\n\n(d) Is based on atomic volume instead of atomic number\n\nQ12. Lothar Meyer's contribution to the development of the periodic table is best described by which of the following?\n\n(a) He proposed the law of octaves\n\n(b) He discovered the neutron\n\n(c) He established the modern group numbering from 1 to 18\n\n(d) He plotted atomic volume against atomic mass and observed periodic peaks and troughs, supporting periodicity independently of Mendeleev\n\n## Multiple Correct (MCQ)\n\n(One or more options may be correct.)\n\nQ13. Which of the following statements about Dobereiner's triads are correct?\n\n(a) Li, Na, K form a valid triad\n\n(b) Cl, Br, I form a valid triad\n\n(c) Fe, Co, Ni form a triad that perfectly obeys the mean atomic mass rule\n\n(d) O, N, F form a recognized Dobereiner triad\n\nQ14. Which of the following are genuine limitations of Mendeleev's Periodic Table?\n\n(a) It could not accommodate the noble gases at all, even after their discovery\n\n(b) No single unambiguous position could be assigned to hydrogen\n\n(c) The position of isotopes could not be explained, since the table was based on atomic mass\n\n(d) Some chemically dissimilar elements, such as the coinage metals Cu, Ag and Au, ended up in the same group as the alkali metals\n\nQ15. Which of the following pairs were placed out of strict increasing atomic-mass order in Mendeleev's periodic table to preserve chemical group similarity?\n\n(a) Ar and K\n\n(b) Co and Ni\n\n(c) Te and I\n\n(d) Na and Mg\n\nQ16. Which of the following statements about Moseley's work are correct?\n\n(a) His experiments measured the characteristic X-ray spectra emitted when elements were bombarded with high-energy electrons\n\n(b) He found that the square root of the X-ray frequency is a linear function of atomic number\n\n(c) His work confirmed atomic mass, rather than atomic number, as the true basis of periodicity\n\n(d) His findings resolved the Co-Ni and Ar-K ordering anomalies present in Mendeleev's table\n\nQ17. Which of the following statements correctly describe the modern long form periodic table?\n\n(a) It has 18 vertical columns called groups\n\n(b) Period 1 contains only two elements\n\n(c) The lanthanides and actinides are placed within the main body of the table, spanning groups 3 through 17\n\n(d) For representative (main-group) elements, the period number equals the highest principal quantum number occupied in the ground-state configuration\n\nQ18. Which of the following are true regarding John Newlands' Law of Octaves?\n\n(a) The law held well beyond calcium, up to the heaviest elements known at the time\n\n(b) Elements were arranged in increasing order of atomic mass\n\n(c) The eighth element from any given one was found to have properties similar to the first\n\n(d) It could not accommodate elements that were discovered later\n\n## Paragraph / Comprehension\n\nParagraph 1: In 1817, Johann Wolfgang Dobereiner observed that certain sets of three elements with similar chemical properties showed a curious numerical pattern: the atomic mass of the middle element was close to the arithmetic mean of the atomic masses of the outer two. He identified such triads among the alkali metals, the alkaline earth metals, and the halogens. Roughly fifty years later, in 1865, John Newlands arranged the elements then known in order of increasing atomic mass and noticed that every eighth element showed properties similar to the first, a pattern he likened to musical octaves. His law worked reasonably well for the lighter elements but broke down once elements heavier than calcium were included, and it could not accommodate elements discovered later.\n\nQ19. According to Dobereiner, which of the following sets qualifies as a valid triad based on the mean atomic mass rule?\n\n(a) Li (6.94), Na (22.99), Mg (24.31)\n\n(b) Ca (40.08), Sr (87.62), Ba (137.33)\n\n(c) F (19.00), Cl (35.45), Br (79.90)\n\n(d) O (16.00), S (32.07), Se (78.97)\n\nQ20. Which limitation of Newlands' Law of Octaves is described in the passage as the reason it was eventually abandoned once elements beyond calcium were considered?\n\n(a) It required a periodic table with 18 groups\n\n(b) It depended on atomic number rather than atomic mass\n\n(c) It was contradicted by Dobereiner's triads\n\n(d) Properties no longer repeated at the eighth element for heavier elements, and no room was left for newly discovered elements\n\nQ21. In Newlands' original arrangement (elements in strict increasing order of atomic mass, starting after hydrogen), which pair of elements was famously forced into the same slot, illustrating a flaw of the law?\n\n(a) Co and Ni\n\n(b) Fe and Co\n\n(c) Ar and K\n\n(d) Ce and La\n\nParagraph 2: By 1869, Dmitri Mendeleev had arranged the elements then known into a table of eight groups and several periods, ordered mainly by increasing atomic mass but adjusted in places to keep chemically similar elements together. He left blank spaces for elements he believed remained undiscovered, forecasting the atomic mass and properties of several of them in detail. Decades later, Henry Moseley, studying the characteristic X-ray spectra emitted by elements bombarded with high-energy electrons, found that the square root of the X-ray frequency increased linearly with a whole-number property of the atom, which he identified as the atomic number. This discovery placed the periodic table on a firmer footing and cleared up several ordering puzzles that had troubled Mendeleev's atomic-mass-based version.\n\nQ22. Mendeleev predicted an element he called eka-silicon; when it was discovered a few years later, it closely matched his predictions in atomic mass and density. This element is known today as:\n\n(a) Gallium\n\n(b) Scandium\n\n(c) Germanium\n\n(d) Selenium\n\nQ23. Moseley's work, as described in the passage, resolved which of the following ordering discrepancies present in Mendeleev's atomic-mass-based table?\n\n(a) The Te-I, Co-Ni and Ar-K pairs\n\n(b) Placement of hydrogen\n\n(c) The lanthanide contraction\n\n(d) The position of the noble gases\n\nQ24. The \"whole-number property of the atom\" that Moseley identified as governing the periodic law is best described as:\n\n(a) The number of neutrons in the nucleus\n\n(b) The number of valence electrons\n\n(c) The number of protons in the nucleus, i.e., the atomic number\n\n(d) The mass number\n\n## Integer Type\n\nQ25. How many elements were known to chemists at the time Mendeleev published his periodic table in 1869? (Report the integer.)\n\nQ26. What is the atomic number of the element Mendeleev called \"eka-silicon,\" now known as germanium?\n\nQ27. How many periods does the modern long form periodic table contain?\n\nQ28. How many elements are present in Period 6 of the modern periodic table?\n\nQ29. Consider the five candidate element triples below, listed with standard atomic masses. Using Dobereiner's mean atomic mass rule (the predicted mean of the outer two elements lies within about 2 percent of the middle element's actual atomic mass), how many of these five triples qualify as valid triads?\n\n(i) Li 6.94, Na 22.99, K 39.10\n\n(ii) Ca 40.08, Sr 87.62, Ba 137.33\n\n(iii) Cl 35.45, Br 79.90, I 126.90\n\n(iv) S 32.07, Se 78.97, Te 127.60\n\n(v) N 14.01, O 16.00, F 19.00\n\nQ30. Among the following four candidate element pairs, how many were placed out of strict increasing atomic-mass order in Mendeleev's original periodic table to preserve chemical group similarity: (Ar, K), (Co, Ni), (Te, I), (Mg, Al)?\n\nQ31. Mendeleev grouped iron, cobalt and nickel together as one triad-like set within \"Group VIII\" of his table, and did the same for two more rows of similar transition-metal triples (Ru-Rh-Pd and Os-Ir-Pt). How many elements in total did Mendeleev place within these three horizontal triads of Group VIII?\n\nQ32. Technetium, first predicted by Mendeleev as \"eka-manganese\" and only isolated in 1937, has an atomic number equal to how much?\n\n## Numerical Response\n\nQ33. Using standard atomic masses Li = 6.94 and K = 39.10, calculate the arithmetic mean predicted by Dobereiner's Law of Triads for the middle element (sodium) of this triad. Give your answer correct to two decimal places.\n\nQ34. Using standard atomic masses Cl = 35.45 and I = 126.90, calculate the arithmetic mean predicted by Dobereiner's Law of Triads for the middle element (bromine) of this triad. Give your answer correct to two decimal places.\n\nQ35. Using standard atomic masses S = 32.07 and Te = 127.60, Dobereiner's rule predicts a certain mean atomic mass for selenium. If the actual atomic mass of selenium is 78.97, calculate the percentage deviation of the predicted value from the actual value. Give your answer correct to two decimal places.\n\nQ36. Mendeleev predicted the atomic mass of eka-silicon to be approximately 72. The actual atomic mass of germanium, the element discovered later matching this prediction, is 72.63. Calculate the percentage error in Mendeleev's predicted atomic mass relative to the actual value, correct to two decimal places.\n\nQ37. Mendeleev predicted the density of eka-silicon to be approximately 5.5 g/cm cubed. The actual density of germanium is 5.35 g/cm cubed. Calculate the percentage error in this prediction relative to the actual value, correct to two decimal places.\n\nQ38. In a simplified Moseley plot of $\\sqrt{\\nu}$ (in arbitrary units of $10^8$ Hz$^{0.5}$) against atomic number Z for characteristic X-rays, a student records $\\sqrt{\\nu} = 5.44$ for magnesium (Z = 12) and $\\sqrt{\\nu} = 9.44$ for calcium (Z = 20). Assuming Moseley's relation $\\sqrt{\\nu} = a(Z - b)$ is linear, calculate the slope $a$ of this plot, correct to two decimal places.\n\nQ39. The modern long form periodic table has 2, 8, 8, 18, 18, 32 and 32 elements in Periods 1 through 7 respectively. Calculate the ratio of the total number of elements in Periods 6 and 7 combined to the total number of elements in Periods 1, 2 and 3 combined, correct to two decimal places.\n\n## Assertion\u2013Reason (A/R)\n\nInstructions: Each question gives an Assertion (A) and a Reason (R). Choose: (a) Both A and R are true and R is the correct explanation of A. (b) Both A and R are true but R is NOT the correct explanation of A. (c) A is true, R is false. (d) A is false, R is true.\n\nQ40. Assertion (A): Hydrogen cannot be assigned a unique, universally agreed position in either Group 1 or Group 17 of the periodic table.\n\nReason (R): A hydrogen atom has one electron in its valence shell, similar to alkali metals, but it also needs only one more electron to complete its shell, similar to halogens.\n\nQ41. Assertion (A): Dobereiner's Law of Triads could classify all the elements known during the early nineteenth century into triads.\n\nReason (R): A valid Dobereiner triad requires the atomic mass of the middle element to be approximately the arithmetic mean of the atomic masses of the outer two elements.\n\nQ42. Assertion (A): In Mendeleev's periodic table, tellurium (atomic mass 127.60) was placed before iodine (atomic mass 126.90).\n\nReason (R): Mendeleev arranged every one of the elements he knew strictly in increasing order of atomic mass, without exception.\n\nQ43. Assertion (A): In the modern periodic table, cobalt (Z = 27) is placed before nickel (Z = 28).\n\nReason (R): Cobalt has a slightly greater atomic mass (58.93) than nickel (58.69).\n\nQ44. Assertion (A): Elements such as gallium, scandium and germanium, discovered years after Mendeleev's 1869 table, closely matched the properties he had forecast for eka-aluminium, eka-boron and eka-silicon respectively.\n\nReason (R): Mendeleev left blank spaces in his table for undiscovered elements and estimated their properties by interpolating from the known properties of neighbouring elements in the same group and period.\n\nQ45. Assertion (A): The fourteen elements from cerium to lutetium, together with the fourteen from thorium to lawrencium, are placed as a separate block outside the main body of the modern long form periodic table.\n\nReason (R): These twenty-eight elements are called transition elements because their chemical properties differ widely from one another, unlike the d-block elements.\n\n## Matrix Match\n\nQ46. Match the scientist in List-I with their principal contribution to the periodic table in List-II. Each entry in List-I matches exactly one entry in List-II.\n\n| List-I | List-II |\n|---|---|\n| A. Dobereiner | p. Arranged elements in octaves of increasing atomic mass |\n| B. Newlands | q. Established atomic number as the basis of periodicity using X-ray spectra |\n| C. Mendeleev | r. Proposed triads governed by the mean atomic mass rule |\n| D. Moseley | s. Framed a periodic law based on atomic mass, with predictive gaps for undiscovered elements |\n\nQ47. Each pair of elements in List-I has a specific atomic mass difference. Match each pair with its approximate atomic mass difference in List-II. Each entry in List-I matches exactly one entry in List-II.\n\n| List-I | List-II |\n|---|---|\n| A. Ar (39.95) and K (39.10) | p. Approximately 0.85 |\n| B. Co (58.93) and Ni (58.69) | q. Approximately 0.70 |\n| C. Te (127.60) and I (126.90) | r. Approximately 4.50 |\n| D. Cl (35.45) and Ar (39.95) | s. Approximately 0.24 |\n\nQ48. Match the period in List-I with the number of elements it contains in the modern long form periodic table, given in List-II. Each entry in List-I matches exactly one entry in List-II.\n\n| List-I | List-II |\n|---|---|\n| A. Period 1 | p. 2 |\n| B. Period 2 | q. 8 |\n| C. Period 4 | r. 18 |\n| D. Period 6 | s. 32 |\n\nQ49. Match Mendeleev's predicted element name in List-I with the actual element later identified as fitting that prediction in List-II. Each entry in List-I matches exactly one entry in List-II.\n\n| List-I | List-II |\n|---|---|\n| A. Eka-aluminium | p. Scandium (Z = 21) |\n| B. Eka-boron | q. Gallium (Z = 31) |\n| C. Eka-silicon | r. Germanium (Z = 32) |\n| D. Eka-manganese | s. Technetium (Z = 43) |\n\n## Innovative Pattern\n\nQ50. The Periodic History Chain. Ten statements about the history of the periodic table are listed below. For each, decide whether it is TRUE or FALSE. Then report your final answer as N, the total number of TRUE statements among the ten.\n\nStatement 1: Dobereiner's Law of Triads states that the atomic mass of the middle element is approximately the arithmetic mean of the atomic masses of the other two elements in the triad.\n\nStatement 2: Newlands' Law of Octaves worked well even for elements heavier than calcium.\n\nStatement 3: Mendeleev's Periodic Law states that the properties of elements are periodic functions of their atomic masses.\n\nStatement 4: Mendeleev left gaps in his periodic table and successfully predicted the properties of eka-silicon, later identified as germanium.\n\nStatement 5: In Mendeleev's table, argon was placed after potassium, in strict accordance with increasing atomic mass.\n\nStatement 6: Moseley's Modern Periodic Law states that the properties of elements are periodic functions of their atomic number.\n\nStatement 7: Moseley's X-ray experiments showed that the square root of the frequency of characteristic X-rays varies linearly with atomic number.\n\nStatement 8: The modern long form periodic table has 7 periods and 18 groups.\n\nStatement 9: Period 6 of the modern periodic table contains 18 elements, the same number as Period 4.\n\nStatement 10: Hydrogen has a universally agreed, single fixed position in the modern periodic table.\n\n## Answer Key\n\n| Q. No. | Answer |\n|---|---|\n| Q1 | (a) |\n| Q2 | (b) |\n| Q3 | (c) |\n| Q4 | (d) |\n| Q5 | (a) |\n| Q6 | (b) |\n| Q7 | (c) |\n| Q8 | (d) |\n| Q9 | (a) |\n| Q10 | (b) |\n| Q11 | (c) |\n| Q12 | (d) |\n| Q13 | (a), (b) |\n| Q14 | (b), (c), (d) |\n| Q15 | (a), (b), (c) |\n| Q16 | (a), (b), (d) |\n| Q17 | (a), (b), (d) |\n| Q18 | (b), (c), (d) |\n| Q19 | (b) |\n| Q20 | (d) |\n| Q21 | (a) |\n| Q22 | (c) |\n| Q23 | (a) |\n| Q24 | (c) |\n| Q25 | 63 |\n| Q26 | 32 |\n| Q27 | 7 |\n| Q28 | 32 |\n| Q29 | 4 |\n| Q30 | 3 |\n| Q31 | 9 |\n| Q32 | 43 |\n| Q33 | 23.02 |\n| Q34 | 81.18 |\n| Q35 | 1.10 |\n| Q36 | 0.87 |\n| Q37 | 2.80 |\n| Q38 | 0.50 |\n| Q39 | 3.56 |\n| Q40 | (a) |\n| Q41 | (d) |\n| Q42 | (c) |\n| Q43 | (b) |\n| Q44 | (a) |\n| Q45 | (c) |\n| Q46 | A-r, B-p, C-s, D-q |\n| Q47 | A-p, B-s, C-q, D-r |\n| Q48 | A-p, B-q, C-r, D-s |\n| Q49 | A-q, B-p, C-r, D-s |\n| Q50 | 6 |\n\n## Worked Solutions\n\nS1. Johann Wolfgang Dobereiner (1817) proposed the Law of Triads, noting that the atomic mass of the middle element in certain triads of similar elements was close to the mean of the outer two. Newlands, Mendeleev and Moseley came later with different organizing principles.\n\nS2. Dobereiner's rule was only found to hold for a small number of triads among chemically similar elements, such as the alkali metals (Li, Na, K), alkaline earth metals (Ca, Sr, Ba), halogens (Cl, Br, I) and chalcogens (S, Se, Te); it never covered all known elements.\n\nS3. Newlands' analogy compared the recurrence of similar properties after every eighth element (when arranged by increasing atomic mass) to the repetition of the first note of a musical scale in the next octave.\n\nS4. Predicting germanium's existence and properties from gaps in the table was Mendeleev's achievement (1871), not Newlands'; therefore it was never a shortcoming attributed to Newlands' law, making option (d) the one that does NOT describe an actual limitation of the octaves law.\n\nS5. Mendeleev's original Periodic Law (1869) explicitly states that the properties of elements are a periodic function of their atomic masses; this was later superseded by Moseley's atomic-number-based law.\n\nS6. Gallium, discovered in 1875 by Lecoq de Boisbaudran, matched the properties Mendeleev had predicted for the then-missing element \"eka-aluminium,\" including its low melting point and atomic mass close to the forecast value.\n\nS7. Despite iodine having a slightly lower atomic mass (126.90) than tellurium (127.60), Mendeleev placed tellurium first so that each element remained in a group with chemically similar elements (tellurium with oxygen/sulfur/selenium, iodine with the halogens); this is confirmed correct by atomic number ordering (Te = 52, I = 53).\n\nS8. Henry Moseley (1913) studied characteristic X-ray spectra of elements and found a systematic relationship between X-ray frequency and atomic number, establishing atomic number as the fundamental periodic variable.\n\nS9. The Modern Periodic Law, established through Moseley's work, states that the physical and chemical properties of elements are periodic functions of their atomic number.\n\nS10. The long form periodic table, developed from Bohr's electronic-configuration-based scheme, has 7 periods and 18 groups (numbered 1-18 under modern IUPAC convention).\n\nS11. Since all isotopes of an element have the same number of protons (same atomic number) despite differing atomic masses, the atomic-number-based Modern Periodic Law naturally places all isotopes at a single position, resolving a problem the atomic-mass-based law could not handle.\n\nS12. Lothar Meyer independently supported periodicity by plotting atomic volume against atomic mass; alkali metals appeared at sharp maxima and transition metals near minima, reinforcing the case for a periodic law even before Mendeleev's table gained wide acceptance.\n\nS13. Li-Na-K and Cl-Br-I are two of the classical Dobereiner triads that closely satisfy the mean atomic mass rule. Fe-Co-Ni does not obey the rule with the precision required to be called a valid, generally accepted triad, and O-N-F is not chemically analogous or numerically consistent, so (a) and (b) alone are correct.\n\nS14. Mendeleev's table struggled to place hydrogen uniquely, could not explain isotopes since it was mass-based, and grouped chemically dissimilar elements (coinage metals with alkali metals) together. However, the noble gases were successfully accommodated later by simply adding a new \"zero group,\" which is regarded as a strength, not a limitation, so (a) is false while (b), (c) and (d) are correct.\n\nS15. Ar-K, Co-Ni and Te-I are the three classic pairs where Mendeleev reversed strict atomic-mass order to preserve group-wise chemical similarity; Na and Mg were correctly ordered by both atomic mass and atomic number, with no anomaly.\n\nS16. Moseley's X-rays were indeed characteristic X-rays (not visible light), \u221a\u03bd was linear in atomic number, and this directly resolved the Co-Ni and Ar-K anomalies by showing atomic number (not atomic mass) governs periodicity; hence (a), (b) and (d) are correct, while (c) reverses the actual conclusion.\n\nS17. The long form table has 18 groups, Period 1 has only H and He (2 elements), and for representative elements the period number matches the highest principal quantum number in the ground state. However, lanthanides and actinides are conventionally displayed separately below the main table, not within groups 3-17, so (c) is false.\n\nS18. Newlands' law failed for elements heavier than calcium (so (a) is false), while the arrangement by atomic mass, the octave repetition pattern, and its failure to accommodate later-discovered elements are all accurate, giving (b), (c) and (d).\n\nS19. Checking each set against the mean rule: Ca-Sr-Ba gives a predicted mean of (40.08+137.33)/2 = 88.705, close to the actual Sr mass of 87.62 (about 1.2% deviation), a valid triad. The other sets either mix chemically dissimilar elements or fail the numerical test.\n\nS20. The passage explicitly states that beyond calcium, the eighth-element repetition broke down and no provision existed for newly discovered elements, which is why the law was abandoned as the periodic table grew.\n\nS21. In Newlands' original table, cobalt and nickel were controversially placed in the same slot because his strict eight-element cycle left no separate room for both, exposing a structural flaw of the scheme.\n\nS22. Germanium, discovered by Clemens Winkler in 1886, matched Mendeleev's predicted values for atomic mass and density for \"eka-silicon\" remarkably closely.\n\nS23. Moseley's atomic-number-based ordering directly resolved why tellurium (Z=52) correctly precedes iodine (Z=53), cobalt (Z=27) precedes nickel (Z=28), and argon (Z=18) precedes potassium (Z=19), despite their atomic-mass order sometimes suggesting otherwise.\n\nS24. Moseley identified the whole-number property governing periodicity as the atomic number, equal to the number of protons (and, in a neutral atom, electrons) in the atom.\n\nS25. Mendeleev's 1869 periodic table was built from the 63 elements known to chemistry at that time.\n\nS26. Eka-silicon corresponds to germanium, atomic number 32.\n\nS27. The long form periodic table has 7 periods.\n\nS28. Period 6 (Cs through Rn, including the lanthanides) contains 32 elements.\n\nS29. Checking means: (i) 23.02 vs Na 22.99 (0.13% off, valid); (ii) 88.705 vs Sr 87.62 (1.24% off, valid); (iii) 81.175 vs Br 79.90 (1.60% off, valid); (iv) 79.835 vs Se 78.97 (1.10% off, valid); (v) 16.505 vs O 16.00 (3.16% off, invalid, and N-O-F are not a chemically analogous family). So 4 of the 5 triples qualify.\n\nS30. Ar-K, Co-Ni and Te-I are genuine anomalies reversed relative to strict atomic-mass order; Mg-Al follow normal increasing order with no exception, giving a count of 3.\n\nS31. Mendeleev's Group VIII contained three horizontal triads: (Fe, Co, Ni), (Ru, Rh, Pd) and (Os, Ir, Pt), a total of 3 x 3 = 9 elements.\n\nS32. Technetium, predicted as \"eka-manganese,\" has atomic number 43; it was first synthesized in 1937, filling the gap Mendeleev had anticipated.\n\nS33. Predicted mean = (6.94 + 39.10) / 2 = 46.04 / 2 = 23.02, very close to sodium's actual atomic mass of 22.99.\n\nS34. Predicted mean = (35.45 + 126.90) / 2 = 162.35 / 2 = 81.175, which rounds to 81.18.\n\nS35. Predicted mean = (32.07 + 127.60) / 2 = 79.835. Percentage deviation from actual Se (78.97) = (79.835 - 78.97) / 78.97 x 100 = 0.865 / 78.97 x 100 = 1.10%.\n\nS36. Percentage error = |72 - 72.63| / 72.63 x 100 = 0.63 / 72.63 x 100 = 0.87%.\n\nS37. Percentage error = |5.5 - 5.35| / 5.35 x 100 = 0.15 / 5.35 x 100 = 2.80%.\n\nS38. Slope a = (9.44 - 5.44) / (20 - 12) = 4.00 / 8 = 0.50.\n\nS39. Ratio = (32 + 32) / (2 + 8 + 8) = 64 / 18 = 3.5556, which rounds to 3.56.\n\nS40. Both statements are true, and the reason (hydrogen's dual resemblance to Group 1 and Group 17 elements) directly and correctly explains why it cannot be given one unambiguous position.\n\nS41. The assertion is false: Dobereiner's triads covered only a handful of chemically similar element groups, not all known elements of the era. The reason correctly states the defining rule of a valid triad, making it true on its own. Hence A is false, R is true.\n\nS42. It is a historical fact that Mendeleev placed tellurium before iodine (A is true), but he did not follow strict atomic-mass order without exception; this placement was itself a deliberate deviation from strict mass order to preserve chemical similarity, so R is false.\n\nS43. Both statements are individually true (cobalt does precede nickel in the periodic table, and cobalt's atomic mass is indeed marginally higher than nickel's), but the actual reason cobalt precedes nickel is its lower atomic number (27 versus 28), not its atomic mass; hence R does not correctly explain A.\n\nS44. Both statements are true: gallium, scandium and germanium matched Mendeleev's forecasts closely, and this predictive success arose precisely because he estimated properties of gap elements by interpolation from neighbouring elements, which is exactly what the reason describes.\n\nS45. It is true that lanthanides and actinides are shown as a separate block below the main table. However, they are properly called inner-transition or f-block elements (not simply \"transition elements,\" a term reserved for d-block elements), and the real reason for their separate placement is the successive filling of the (n-2)f subshell, not any claim about differing properties; hence R is false.\n\nS46. Dobereiner (A) proposed triads governed by the mean rule (r); Newlands (B) arranged elements in octaves of atomic mass (p); Mendeleev (C) framed the atomic-mass-based law with predictive gaps (s); Moseley (D) established atomic number via X-ray spectra (q).\n\nS47. Ar (39.95) and K (39.10) differ by 0.85 (p); Co (58.93) and Ni (58.69) differ by 0.24 (s); Te (127.60) and I (126.90) differ by 0.70 (q); Cl (35.45) and Ar (39.95) differ by 4.50 (r).\n\nS48. Period 1 has 2 elements (p); Period 2 has 8 elements (q); Period 4 has 18 elements (r); Period 6 has 32 elements (s).\n\nS49. Eka-aluminium corresponds to gallium (q); eka-boron corresponds to scandium (p); eka-silicon corresponds to germanium (r); eka-manganese corresponds to technetium (s).\n\nS50. Statements 1, 3, 4, 6, 7 and 8 are true (Dobereiner's rule, Mendeleev's atomic-mass law, the germanium prediction, Moseley's atomic-number law, the X-ray frequency relation, and the 7-period/18-group structure). Statements 2, 5, 9 and 10 are false (the octaves law actually broke down after calcium, argon was placed before, not after, potassium, Period 6 has 32 elements not 18, and hydrogen's position remains debated rather than universally fixed). This gives 6 true statements, so N = 6.\n";
const RAW_MD_CONFIGURATION = "## Single Correct (SCQ)\n\nQ1. The ground-state electronic configuration of chromium (Z = 24) is best represented as:\n\n(a) $[Ar]3d^5 4s^1$\n\n(b) $[Ar]3d^4 4s^2$\n\n(c) $[Ar]3d^6$\n\n(d) $[Ar]4s^2 3d^4$\n\nQ2. The ground-state electronic configuration of copper (Z = 29) is:\n\n(a) $[Ar]3d^9 4s^2$\n\n(b) $[Ar]3d^{10} 4s^1$\n\n(c) $[Ar]4s^2 3d^9$\n\n(d) $[Ar]3d^8 4s^2 4p^1$\n\nQ3. According to Hund's rule of maximum multiplicity, electrons occupying a set of degenerate orbitals (such as the three 2p orbitals) are:\n\n(a) Paired first, before singly filling all the orbitals\n\n(b) Filled randomly, with spin direction being irrelevant\n\n(c) Filled singly, with parallel spins, in all degenerate orbitals before pairing begins\n\n(d) Always paired with opposite spins from the very first electron placed\n\nQ4. The Pauli exclusion principle states that:\n\n(a) Electrons fill orbitals in order of increasing $(n+l)$ value\n\n(b) Degenerate orbitals must be singly occupied before any pairing occurs\n\n(c) Electrons repel each other within the same orbital\n\n(d) No two electrons in an atom can have the same set of all four quantum numbers\n\nQ5. Molybdenum (Z = 42) shows an exception to normal Aufbau filling, similar to chromium. Its ground-state configuration is:\n\n(a) $[Kr]4d^5 5s^1$\n\n(b) $[Kr]4d^4 5s^2$\n\n(c) $[Kr]4d^6$\n\n(d) $[Kr]5s^2 4d^4$\n\nQ6. The ground-state electronic configuration of silver (Z = 47) is:\n\n(a) $[Kr]4d^9 5s^2$\n\n(b) $[Kr]4d^{10} 5s^1$\n\n(c) $[Kr]4d^{10} 5s^2$\n\n(d) $[Kr]4d^8 5s^2 5p^1$\n\nQ7. The ground-state electronic configuration of gold (Z = 79) is:\n\n(a) $[Xe]4f^{14} 5d^9 6s^2$\n\n(b) $[Xe]4f^{14} 5d^{10} 6s^2$\n\n(c) $[Xe]4f^{14} 5d^{10} 6s^1$\n\n(d) $[Xe]4f^{13} 5d^{10} 6s^2$\n\nQ8. For a d-block element with configuration $(n-1)d^x ns^y$ (excluding well-known anomalies), the group number of the element is generally given by:\n\n(a) $x$ only\n\n(b) $y + 10$\n\n(c) $x - y$\n\n(d) $x + y$\n\nQ9. Which of the following configurations represents an element belonging to the p-block, Period 4, Group 15?\n\n(a) $[Ar]3d^{10} 4s^2 4p^3$\n\n(b) $[Ar]4s^2 4p^5$\n\n(c) $[Kr]4d^{10} 5s^2 5p^3$\n\n(d) $[Ar]3d^{10} 4s^2 4p^5$\n\nQ10. The number of unpaired electrons in the ground state of a free $Fe^{3+}$ ion ($[Ar]3d^5$) is:\n\n(a) 3\n\n(b) 5\n\n(c) 4\n\n(d) 1\n\nQ11. Which of the following sets of four quantum numbers is NOT permissible for an electron in an atom?\n\n(a) $n=3, l=2, m_l=-2, m_s=+1/2$\n\n(b) $n=2, l=1, m_l=0, m_s=-1/2$\n\n(c) $n=4, l=4, m_l=0, m_s=+1/2$\n\n(d) $n=3, l=0, m_l=0, m_s=-1/2$\n\nQ12. An atom with the electronic configuration $[Ne]3s^2 3p^5$ belongs to which block, group and period?\n\n(a) p-block, Group 15, Period 3\n\n(b) s-block, Group 17, Period 3\n\n(c) p-block, Group 17, Period 2\n\n(d) p-block, Group 17, Period 3\n\n## Multiple Correct (MCQ)\n\n(One or more options may be correct.)\n\nQ13. Which of the following ground-state configurations represent an exception to the simple Aufbau filling order, arising from the extra stability of a half-filled or completely filled subshell?\n\n(a) Cr: $[Ar]3d^5 4s^1$\n\n(b) Cu: $[Ar]3d^{10} 4s^1$\n\n(c) Fe: $[Ar]3d^6 4s^2$\n\n(d) Mo: $[Kr]4d^5 5s^1$\n\nQ14. Which of the following ions are isoelectronic with argon (18 electrons)?\n\n(a) $Ca^{2+}$\n\n(b) $Cl^{-}$\n\n(c) $K^{+}$\n\n(d) $S^{2-}$\n\nQ15. Which of the following statements about Hund's rule and electron pairing are correct?\n\n(a) Pairing of electrons in degenerate orbitals begins only after each orbital of that subshell contains one electron\n\n(b) Half-filled and fully-filled subshells possess extra stability due to symmetry and favourable exchange energy\n\n(c) Hund's rule is relevant only to subshells with a single orbital, such as the s-subshell\n\n(d) Parallel spins in degenerate orbitals minimize electron-electron repulsion compared with paired spins in the same orbital\n\nQ16. Which of the following species is/are diamagnetic in their ground state?\n\n(a) $Zn^{2+}$ ($[Ar]3d^{10}$)\n\n(b) $Fe^{2+}$ ($[Ar]3d^{6}$)\n\n(c) $Ca^{2+}$ ($[Ar]$)\n\n(d) $Cu^{+}$ ($[Ar]3d^{10}$)\n\nQ17. Which of the following statements correctly describe the $(n+l)$ rule (Aufbau principle) for filling atomic orbitals?\n\n(a) Orbitals with a lower $(n+l)$ value are filled first\n\n(b) If two orbitals have the same $(n+l)$ value, the one with the lower $n$ is filled first\n\n(c) The rule perfectly predicts the ground-state configuration of every known element without exception\n\n(d) The 4s orbital is filled before 3d because 4s has a lower $(n+l)$ value (4) than 3d (5)\n\nQ18. Which of the following element-to-block assignments are correctly matched?\n\n(a) Zn: d-block\n\n(b) La ($[Xe]5d^1 6s^2$): d-block\n\n(c) Ce ($[Xe]4f^1 5d^1 6s^2$): f-block\n\n(d) He ($1s^2$): p-block\n\n## Paragraph / Comprehension\n\nParagraph 1: The Aufbau principle guides the filling of atomic orbitals in order of increasing $(n+l)$ value, with ties broken in favour of the orbital having the lower principal quantum number $n$. This scheme correctly predicts the ground-state configuration of most elements, but a handful of transition metals deviate from it because a half-filled or completely filled d subshell provides extra stability through favourable exchange energy. Chromium and molybdenum, for instance, adopt a $d^5 s^1$ configuration instead of the $d^4 s^2$ configuration the simple rule would predict, while copper, silver and gold adopt a $d^{10} s^1$ configuration instead of $d^9 s^2$.\n\nQ19. Based on the passage, one might expect tungsten (Z = 74), which lies in the same group as chromium and molybdenum, to also show a $d^5 s^1$-type exception. Its actual ground-state configuration, however, is:\n\n(a) $[Xe]4f^{14} 5d^4 6s^2$\n\n(b) $[Xe]4f^{14} 5d^5 6s^1$\n\n(c) $[Xe]4f^{14} 5d^6$\n\n(d) $[Xe]4f^{13} 5d^5 6s^2$\n\nQ20. Which of the following correctly explains why chromium prefers $[Ar]3d^5 4s^1$ over $[Ar]3d^4 4s^2$?\n\n(a) The lower ionization energy of 4s electrons\n\n(b) Greater stability arising from a half-filled d subshell, due to symmetrical electron distribution and greater exchange energy\n\n(c) Repulsion between the paired 4s electrons\n\n(d) The 3d orbitals are lower in energy than 4s for every element\n\nQ21. The exchange energy responsible for the extra stability of half-filled and fully-filled subshells arises primarily from:\n\n(a) Attraction between electrons of opposite spin in different orbitals\n\n(b) Shielding of nuclear charge by inner electrons\n\n(c) The difference in orbital angular momentum between subshells\n\n(d) The quantum mechanical stabilization that occurs when electrons with parallel spins in degenerate orbitals can exchange positions\n\nParagraph 2: Removing or adding electrons to a neutral atom changes its electronic configuration and can dramatically alter its magnetic behaviour. Species that possess the same number of electrons, regardless of nuclear charge, are termed isoelectronic and often show similar (though not identical) electronic arrangements. The number of unpaired electrons in the ground state of a species can be used to compute its spin-only magnetic moment through the formula $\\mu = \\sqrt{n(n+2)}$ Bohr magnetons, where $n$ is the number of unpaired electrons; a species with $n = 0$ is diamagnetic, while one with $n \\geq 1$ is paramagnetic.\n\nQ22. The ions $Mn^{2+}$ and $Fe^{3+}$ both have the configuration $[Ar]3d^5$. The spin-only magnetic moment of each, in Bohr magnetons, correct to two significant figures, is closest to:\n\n(a) 1.73\n\n(b) 3.87\n\n(c) 5.92\n\n(d) 4.90\n\nQ23. Which of the following pairs of species is correctly isoelectronic with each other?\n\n(a) $Na^{+}$ and $Al^{3+}$\n\n(b) $O^{2-}$ and $Cl^{-}$\n\n(c) $Mg^{2+}$ and $Ca^{2+}$\n\n(d) $K^{+}$ and $Sr^{2+}$\n\nQ24. A certain dipositive ion $M^{2+}$ has the ground-state configuration $[Ar]3d^6$. Assuming a high-spin, free-ion configuration, the number of unpaired electrons in this ion is:\n\n(a) 6\n\n(b) 0\n\n(c) 4\n\n(d) 2\n\n## Integer Type\n\nQ25. How many unpaired electrons are present in the ground-state configuration of a chromium atom (Z = 24, $[Ar]3d^5 4s^1$)?\n\nQ26. How many unpaired electrons are present in the ground-state configuration of $Mn^{2+}$ ($[Ar]3d^5$)?\n\nQ27. Consider the ground-state configurations of the ten elements from Z = 21 to Z = 30 (Sc through Zn). How many of these ten elements have exactly one electron in the 4s subshell (that is, a $4s^1$ configuration) in their ground state?\n\nQ28. What is the sum of the modern IUPAC group numbers (1 to 18) of the three elements whose ground-state configurations are $[Ar]3d^5 4s^1$, $[Ar]3d^{10} 4s^1$, and $[Ar]3d^{10} 4s^2$?\n\nQ29. An atom X has the ground-state configuration $[Kr]4d^{10} 5s^2 5p^3$. What is the group number of X in the modern periodic table?\n\nQ30. How many of the five 3d orbitals in a ground-state $Zn^{2+}$ ion ($[Ar]3d^{10}$) are completely filled, containing two electrons each?\n\nQ31. How many elements in the fourth period of the periodic table (from Sc through Zn) belong to the d-block?\n\nQ32. Gadolinium (Gd, Z = 64) has the ground-state configuration $[Xe]4f^7 5d^1 6s^2$. Its $Gd^{3+}$ ion is formed by removing the $6s^2$ and $5d^1$ electrons, leaving the configuration $[Xe]4f^7$. How many unpaired electrons are present in the ground state of $Gd^{3+}$?\n\n## Numerical Response\n\nQ33. Calculate the spin-only magnetic moment (in Bohr magnetons) of a free $Fe^{2+}$ ion ($[Ar]3d^6$, high spin, 4 unpaired electrons), correct to two decimal places.\n\nQ34. Calculate the spin-only magnetic moment (in Bohr magnetons) of $Mn^{2+}$ ($[Ar]3d^5$, 5 unpaired electrons), correct to two decimal places.\n\nQ35. Calculate the spin-only magnetic moment (in Bohr magnetons) of $Ti^{3+}$ ($[Ar]3d^1$, 1 unpaired electron), correct to two decimal places.\n\nQ36. Calculate the spin-only magnetic moment (in Bohr magnetons) of $Ni^{2+}$ ($[Ar]3d^8$, 2 unpaired electrons), correct to two decimal places.\n\nQ37. An atom X has 33 electrons (ground-state configuration $[Ar]3d^{10} 4s^2 4p^3$). It gains 3 electrons to form the ion $X^{3-}$, which becomes isoelectronic with a noble gas. Calculate the percentage of the total electrons in $X^{3-}$ that occupy p-orbitals, correct to two decimal places.\n\nQ38. Calculate the percentage of unpaired electrons relative to the total number of electrons in a ground-state nitrogen atom (Z = 7, configuration $1s^2 2s^2 2p^3$), correct to two decimal places.\n\nQ39. An element has atomic number 25 (ground-state configuration $[Ar]3d^5 4s^2$). Calculate the ratio of the total number of s-electrons to the total number of d-electrons in this configuration, correct to two decimal places.\n\n## Assertion\u2013Reason (A/R)\n\nInstructions: Each question gives an Assertion (A) and a Reason (R). Choose: (a) Both A and R are true and R is the correct explanation of A. (b) Both A and R are true but R is NOT the correct explanation of A. (c) A is true, R is false. (d) A is false, R is true.\n\nQ40. Assertion (A): Chromium has the ground-state configuration $[Ar]3d^5 4s^1$ rather than $[Ar]3d^4 4s^2$.\n\nReason (R): A half-filled d subshell possesses extra stability due to symmetrical electron distribution and greater exchange energy.\n\nQ41. Assertion (A): Helium is placed in Group 18 of the periodic table.\n\nReason (R): The electronic configuration of helium is $1s^2$, which fits the general $ns^2$ pattern seen in the s-block alkaline earth metals.\n\nQ42. Assertion (A): The atom with configuration $[Ar]3d^{10} 4s^2 4p^1$ belongs to Group 3 of the periodic table.\n\nReason (R): For p-block elements, the group number equals 10 plus the total number of valence s and p electrons.\n\nQ43. Assertion (A): $Fe^{3+}$ ($[Ar]3d^5$) has more unpaired electrons than $Fe^{2+}$ ($[Ar]3d^6$).\n\nReason (R): In $Fe^{2+}$, all six 3d electrons occupy separate orbitals with parallel spin, giving six unpaired electrons.\n\nQ44. Assertion (A): Cerium (Ce, Z = 58) has the ground-state configuration $[Xe]4f^1 5d^1 6s^2$ rather than the \"expected\" $[Xe]4f^2 6s^2$.\n\nReason (R): The very small energy gap between the 4f and 5d subshells in the early lanthanides allows such exceptions to the simple filling pattern.\n\nQ45. Assertion (A): Molybdenum has the configuration $[Kr]4d^5 5s^1$ instead of $[Kr]4d^4 5s^2$.\n\nReason (R): Molybdenum is located in Group 6 of the periodic table, directly below chromium.\n\n## Matrix Match\n\nQ46. Match the element in List-I with its ground-state configuration in List-II. Each entry in List-I matches exactly one entry in List-II.\n\n| List-I | List-II |\n|---|---|\n| A. Cr (Z = 24) | p. $[Kr]4d^5 5s^1$ |\n| B. Cu (Z = 29) | q. $[Ar]3d^5 4s^1$ |\n| C. Mo (Z = 42) | r. $[Xe]4f^{14} 5d^{10} 6s^1$ |\n| D. Au (Z = 79) | s. $[Ar]3d^{10} 4s^1$ |\n\nQ47. Match the ion in List-I with the number of unpaired electrons in List-II. Each entry in List-I matches exactly one entry in List-II.\n\n| List-I | List-II |\n|---|---|\n| A. $Ti^{3+}$ ($[Ar]3d^1$) | p. 1 |\n| B. $V^{3+}$ ($[Ar]3d^2$) | q. 2 |\n| C. $Cr^{3+}$ ($[Ar]3d^3$) | r. 3 |\n| D. $Mn^{3+}$ ($[Ar]3d^4$, high spin) | s. 4 |\n\nQ48. Match the configuration in List-I with its correct block, group and period identity in List-II. Each entry in List-I matches exactly one entry in List-II.\n\n| List-I | List-II |\n|---|---|\n| A. $[Ne]3s^2$ | p. Group 2, s-block, Period 3 |\n| B. $[Ne]3s^2 3p^6$ | q. Group 18, p-block, Period 3 |\n| C. $[Ar]3d^{10} 4s^2 4p^6$ | r. Group 18, p-block, Period 4 |\n| D. $[Kr]4d^{10} 5s^1$ | s. Group 11, d-block, Period 5 |\n\nQ49. Match the ion in List-I with its spin-only magnetic moment (in Bohr magnetons, to two decimal places) in List-II. Each entry in List-I matches exactly one entry in List-II.\n\n| List-I | List-II |\n|---|---|\n| A. $Ti^{3+}$ (1 unpaired electron) | p. 1.73 |\n| B. $V^{3+}$ (2 unpaired electrons) | q. 2.83 |\n| C. $Cr^{3+}$ (3 unpaired electrons) | r. 3.87 |\n| D. $Mn^{2+}$ (5 unpaired electrons) | s. 5.92 |\n\n## Innovative Pattern\n\nQ50. The Configuration Detective. An element X satisfies all four of the following clues. Identify X, then determine the ion $X^{2+}$ and report the number of unpaired electrons in the ground state of $X^{2+}$ as your final numeric answer.\n\nClue 1: X is a d-block element located in Period 4.\n\nClue 2: The ground-state configuration of neutral X is an exception to the simple Aufbau (n+l) filling order.\n\nClue 3: X has exactly one electron in its 4s subshell in the ground state.\n\nClue 4: The sum of the digits of the atomic number of X is exactly 6.\n\n## Answer Key\n\n| Q. No. | Answer |\n|---|---|\n| Q1 | (a) |\n| Q2 | (b) |\n| Q3 | (c) |\n| Q4 | (d) |\n| Q5 | (a) |\n| Q6 | (b) |\n| Q7 | (c) |\n| Q8 | (d) |\n| Q9 | (a) |\n| Q10 | (b) |\n| Q11 | (c) |\n| Q12 | (d) |\n| Q13 | (a), (b), (d) |\n| Q14 | (a), (b), (c), (d) |\n| Q15 | (a), (b), (d) |\n| Q16 | (a), (c), (d) |\n| Q17 | (a), (b), (d) |\n| Q18 | (a), (b), (c) |\n| Q19 | (a) |\n| Q20 | (b) |\n| Q21 | (d) |\n| Q22 | (c) |\n| Q23 | (a) |\n| Q24 | (c) |\n| Q25 | 6 |\n| Q26 | 5 |\n| Q27 | 2 |\n| Q28 | 29 |\n| Q29 | 15 |\n| Q30 | 5 |\n| Q31 | 10 |\n| Q32 | 7 |\n| Q33 | 4.90 |\n| Q34 | 5.92 |\n| Q35 | 1.73 |\n| Q36 | 2.83 |\n| Q37 | 50.00 |\n| Q38 | 42.86 |\n| Q39 | 1.60 |\n| Q40 | (a) |\n| Q41 | (b) |\n| Q42 | (d) |\n| Q43 | (c) |\n| Q44 | (a) |\n| Q45 | (b) |\n| Q46 | A-q, B-s, C-p, D-r |\n| Q47 | A-p, B-q, C-r, D-s |\n| Q48 | A-p, B-q, C-r, D-s |\n| Q49 | A-p, B-q, C-r, D-s |\n| Q50 | 4 |\n\n## Worked Solutions\n\nS1. Chromium's ground-state configuration is $[Ar]3d^5 4s^1$, not $[Ar]3d^4 4s^2$, because a half-filled 3d subshell combined with a half-filled 4s subshell gives extra stability through symmetrical distribution and exchange energy.\n\nS2. Copper adopts $[Ar]3d^{10} 4s^1$ instead of $[Ar]3d^9 4s^2$ because a completely filled 3d subshell is more stable, again due to exchange energy considerations.\n\nS3. Hund's rule requires that electrons occupy each orbital of a degenerate set singly, with parallel spins, before any orbital receives a second electron; this minimizes electron-electron repulsion.\n\nS4. The Pauli exclusion principle forbids any two electrons in the same atom from sharing an identical set of all four quantum numbers, which limits each orbital to a maximum of two electrons with opposite spins.\n\nS5. Like chromium, molybdenum (Group 6) shows a $d^5 s^1$ exception, giving $[Kr]4d^5 5s^1$ instead of the Aufbau-predicted $[Kr]4d^4 5s^2$.\n\nS6. Silver, like copper, favours a completely filled d subshell: $[Kr]4d^{10} 5s^1$ instead of $[Kr]4d^9 5s^2$.\n\nS7. Gold favours a completely filled 5d subshell: $[Xe]4f^{14} 5d^{10} 6s^1$ instead of $[Xe]4f^{14} 5d^9 6s^2$.\n\nS8. For a normal (non-anomalous) d-block element with configuration $(n-1)d^x ns^y$, the group number is obtained by adding the d and s electrons: group number = $x + y$.\n\nS9. $[Ar]3d^{10} 4s^2 4p^3$ has its outermost electrons in $n=4$ (Period 4), is a p-block configuration (electrons entering the 4p subshell), and its group number is $10 + (2+3) = 15$; this is arsenic.\n\nS10. $Fe^{3+}$ has the configuration $[Ar]3d^5$; since all five 3d orbitals can each hold one electron by Hund's rule, all five electrons remain unpaired, giving 5 unpaired electrons.\n\nS11. For any value of $n$, the azimuthal quantum number $l$ can range only from 0 to $n-1$; since $n=4$ permits at most $l=3$, the combination $l=4$ is never permissible, making option (c) invalid.\n\nS12. $[Ne]3s^2 3p^5$ has 7 valence electrons in $n=3$, giving Period 3, p-block, and group number $10+(2+5)=17$; this is chlorine.\n\nS13. Cr, Cu and Mo all deviate from simple Aufbau filling to gain extra stability from a half-filled or fully-filled subshell, while Fe ($[Ar]3d^6 4s^2$) follows the normal Aufbau order and is not an exception.\n\nS14. Electron counts: $Ca^{2+}$ = 20 - 2 = 18; $Cl^-$ = 17 + 1 = 18; $K^+$ = 19 - 1 = 18; $S^{2-}$ = 16 + 2 = 18. All four ions have exactly 18 electrons, so all are isoelectronic with argon.\n\nS15. Hund's rule requires single occupancy with parallel spins before pairing (a), explains the extra stability of half-filled and fully-filled subshells (b), and favours parallel spins to minimize repulsion (d); it is not restricted to s-orbitals, since it only becomes relevant when a subshell has more than one orbital, so (c) is false.\n\nS16. $Zn^{2+}$, $Ca^{2+}$ and $Cu^{+}$ all have completely filled, paired configurations ($3d^{10}$ or a noble-gas core) and are diamagnetic. $Fe^{2+}$ ($3d^6$, high spin) has 4 unpaired electrons and is paramagnetic, so (b) is excluded.\n\nS17. The $(n+l)$ rule correctly orders orbital filling by increasing $(n+l)$ value, with lower $n$ breaking ties, and correctly places 4s (n+l=4) before 3d (n+l=5). However, it fails for several transition metals (Cr, Cu, Mo, Ag, Au, etc.), so it does not work \"without exception,\" making (c) false.\n\nS18. Zn, La and Ce are conventionally classified as d-block, d-block and f-block respectively based on their differentiating electrons. Helium, despite its $1s^2$ configuration technically fitting the s-block pattern, is conventionally shown in Group 18 with the noble gases (p-block region of the table) rather than being labelled p-block by its actual electron configuration, so pairing \"He: p-block\" as a configuration-based classification is not correct.\n\nS19. Although tungsten lies in the same group as chromium and molybdenum, it does not show the $d^5 s^1$ exception; its actual ground-state configuration is $[Xe]4f^{14} 5d^4 6s^2$, following normal Aufbau filling, illustrating that such exceptions are not automatically inherited by every member of a group.\n\nS20. The preference for $[Ar]3d^5 4s^1$ arises because a half-filled d subshell has extra stability from symmetrical electron distribution and greater exchange energy, not from any change in relative 4s/3d ionization behaviour.\n\nS21. Exchange energy stabilization arises because electrons with parallel spins occupying different orbitals of the same subshell can exchange positions in a quantum mechanically favourable way, lowering the overall energy of the configuration.\n\nS22. Both $Mn^{2+}$ and $Fe^{3+}$ have 5 unpaired electrons, so $\\mu = \\sqrt{5 \\times 7} = \\sqrt{35} = 5.92$ BM.\n\nS23. $Na^+$ (11 - 1 = 10 electrons) and $Al^{3+}$ (13 - 3 = 10 electrons) are isoelectronic with 10 electrons each; the other pairs have unequal electron counts.\n\nS24. A high-spin $d^6$ configuration fills all five orbitals singly first (5 electrons) and then places the sixth electron into one already-occupied orbital, leaving 4 unpaired electrons.\n\nS25. Chromium's $[Ar]3d^5 4s^1$ configuration has 5 unpaired electrons in the 3d subshell plus 1 unpaired electron in 4s, giving 6 unpaired electrons in total.\n\nS26. $Mn^{2+}$ ($[Ar]3d^5$) has all five 3d electrons unpaired by Hund's rule, giving 5 unpaired electrons.\n\nS27. Among Sc through Zn, only chromium ($[Ar]3d^5 4s^1$) and copper ($[Ar]3d^{10} 4s^1$) have a single 4s electron; the other eight elements have $4s^2$.\n\nS28. The three configurations correspond to Cr (Group 6), Cu (Group 11) and Zn (Group 12); their group numbers sum to $6 + 11 + 12 = 29$.\n\nS29. For a p-block element with configuration $ns^2 np^3$, the group number is $10 + (2+3) = 15$; this corresponds to antimony.\n\nS30. $Zn^{2+}$ has the configuration $[Ar]3d^{10}$, meaning all five 3d orbitals are completely filled with two electrons each.\n\nS31. The fourth period d-block spans scandium (Z=21) through zinc (Z=30), a total of 10 elements.\n\nS32. $Gd^{3+}$ has the configuration $[Xe]4f^7$; since the 4f subshell has seven orbitals, all seven electrons occupy separate orbitals with parallel spin by Hund's rule, giving 7 unpaired electrons (a half-filled, highly stable f subshell).\n\nS33. $Fe^{2+}$ has 4 unpaired electrons, so $\\mu = \\sqrt{4 \\times 6} = \\sqrt{24} = 4.90$ BM.\n\nS34. $Mn^{2+}$ has 5 unpaired electrons, so $\\mu = \\sqrt{5 \\times 7} = \\sqrt{35} = 5.92$ BM.\n\nS35. $Ti^{3+}$ has 1 unpaired electron, so $\\mu = \\sqrt{1 \\times 3} = \\sqrt{3} = 1.73$ BM.\n\nS36. $Ni^{2+}$ ($3d^8$) has 2 unpaired electrons, so $\\mu = \\sqrt{2 \\times 4} = \\sqrt{8} = 2.83$ BM.\n\nS37. X (33 electrons, As) gains 3 electrons to form $X^{3-}$ with 36 electrons, configuration $[Ar]3d^{10} 4s^2 4p^6$, isoelectronic with krypton. The p-orbital electrons are $2p^6 + 3p^6 + 4p^6 = 18$. Percentage = $18/36 \\times 100 = 50.00\\%$.\n\nS38. Nitrogen has 7 total electrons and 3 unpaired electrons in its half-filled $2p^3$ subshell. Percentage = $3/7 \\times 100 = 42.86\\%$.\n\nS39. Manganese's configuration $[Ar]3d^5 4s^2$ has s-electrons from $1s^2, 2s^2, 3s^2, 4s^2$, totalling 8, and d-electrons totalling 5 (from $3d^5$). Ratio = $8/5 = 1.60$.\n\nS40. Both statements are true, and the reason (extra stability from a symmetrically half-filled, high-exchange-energy d subshell) correctly explains why chromium adopts this configuration.\n\nS41. Helium's placement in Group 18 (A, true) is due to its complete, chemically inert valence shell and noble-gas-like behaviour, not because its $1s^2$ configuration formally resembles the alkaline earth $ns^2$ pattern; the reason, while a true observation about the configuration, does not correctly explain the Group 18 placement.\n\nS42. The configuration $[Ar]3d^{10} 4s^2 4p^1$ actually belongs to Group 13 (gallium), not Group 3, so the assertion is false; the stated group-number rule for p-block elements (10 + valence s and p electrons) is itself correct.\n\nS43. $Fe^{3+}$ ($3d^5$) has 5 unpaired electrons while $Fe^{2+}$ ($3d^6$) has only 4, since one of the five d-orbitals must accommodate a second, paired electron; the assertion is therefore true but the reason, claiming six unpaired electrons in $Fe^{2+}$, is false since a maximum of 5 orbitals limits unpaired electrons to 5 and pairing reduces this to 4.\n\nS44. Cerium's actual ground-state configuration is indeed $[Xe]4f^1 5d^1 6s^2$, and this arises because the 4f and 5d subshells are extremely close in energy for the early lanthanides, allowing such exceptions to the standard filling order.\n\nS45. Both statements are factually true (Mo does adopt $4d^5 5s^1$, and Mo does sit below Cr in Group 6), but merely stating Mo's group position does not itself explain why the $d^5 s^1$ configuration is energetically preferred; the true explanation is the exchange-energy stabilization of the half-filled d subshell, so the reason does not correctly explain the assertion.\n\nS46. Cr adopts $[Ar]3d^5 4s^1$ (q); Cu adopts $[Ar]3d^{10} 4s^1$ (s); Mo adopts $[Kr]4d^5 5s^1$ (p); Au adopts $[Xe]4f^{14} 5d^{10} 6s^1$ (r).\n\nS47. The number of unpaired electrons increases directly with the number of 3d electrons for these high-spin $d^1$ through $d^4$ ions: $Ti^{3+}$ has 1 (p), $V^{3+}$ has 2 (q), $Cr^{3+}$ has 3 (r), and $Mn^{3+}$ has 4 (s).\n\nS48. $[Ne]3s^2$ is magnesium (Group 2, s-block, Period 3) (p); $[Ne]3s^2 3p^6$ is argon (Group 18, p-block, Period 3) (q); $[Ar]3d^{10} 4s^2 4p^6$ is krypton (Group 18, p-block, Period 4) (r); $[Kr]4d^{10} 5s^1$ is silver, an exception with a filled 4d subshell (Group 11, d-block, Period 5) (s).\n\nS49. Using $\\mu = \\sqrt{n(n+2)}$: $Ti^{3+}$ (n=1) gives 1.73 (p); $V^{3+}$ (n=2) gives 2.83 (q); $Cr^{3+}$ (n=3) gives 3.87 (r); $Mn^{2+}$ (n=5) gives 5.92 (s).\n\nS50. Among Period 4 d-block exceptions with a $4s^1$ configuration, only chromium (Z=24) and copper (Z=29) qualify. The digit sum of 24 is $2+4=6$, matching Clue 4, while the digit sum of 29 is $2+9=11$, which does not match. Hence X is chromium. Removing 2 electrons from $[Ar]3d^5 4s^1$ gives $Cr^{2+}$ = $[Ar]3d^4$ (the single 4s electron is removed first, followed by one 3d electron). In a high-spin $d^4$ configuration, four of the five d-orbitals are singly occupied, giving 4 unpaired electrons.\n";
const RAW_MD_RADIUS = "## Single Correct (SCQ)\n\nQ1. A student lists the atomic radii of four period-3 elements without labels: 186 pm, 160 pm, 143 pm and 117 pm. These four values belong to Na, Mg, Al and Si in some order. Which assignment is correct?\n\n(a) Na = 186 pm, Mg = 160 pm, Al = 143 pm, Si = 117 pm\n\n(b) Na = 160 pm, Mg = 186 pm, Al = 117 pm, Si = 143 pm\n\n(c) Na = 143 pm, Mg = 160 pm, Al = 186 pm, Si = 117 pm\n\n(d) Na = 117 pm, Mg = 143 pm, Al = 160 pm, Si = 186 pm\n\nQ2. Four isoelectronic species, each possessing 18 electrons, are S2-, Cl-, K+ and Ca2+. Which of the following correctly arranges them in order of decreasing ionic radius?\n\n(a) S2- > Cl- > K+ > Ca2+\n\n(b) Ca2+ > K+ > Cl- > S2-\n\n(c) Cl- > S2- > Ca2+ > K+\n\n(d) K+ > Ca2+ > S2- > Cl-\n\nQ3. Due to the lanthanide contraction, which of the following pairs of transition metals has nearly identical atomic radii even though the two elements lie in the same group but different periods?\n\n(a) Ti and Zr\n\n(b) Zr and Hf\n\n(c) V and Nb\n\n(d) Sc and Y\n\nQ4. In the first transition series, zinc has a slightly larger atomic radius than copper even though it has one more proton. Which of the following best accounts for this?\n\n(a) Zinc has a lower effective nuclear charge than copper due to Slater shielding by inner shells alone\n\n(b) In zinc, the 3d subshell becomes completely filled (3d10), and the increased electron-electron repulsion within this filled subshell expands the electron cloud slightly\n\n(c) Zinc belongs to group 12 whereas copper belongs to group 11, and elements of group 12 are always larger than those of group 11\n\n(d) Zinc has a smaller nuclear charge than copper\n\nQ5. For a given element that can be assigned a covalent radius, a metallic radius and a van der Waals radius, the correct relative ordering from smallest to largest is:\n\n(a) covalent radius < metallic radius < van der Waals radius\n\n(b) metallic radius < covalent radius < van der Waals radius\n\n(c) van der Waals radius < metallic radius < covalent radius\n\n(d) covalent radius < van der Waals radius < metallic radius\n\nQ6. Among Na+, Mg2+, Al3+ and F-, all of which possess 10 electrons, the smallest ionic radius is shown by:\n\n(a) F-\n\n(b) Na+\n\n(c) Mg2+\n\n(d) Al3+\n\nQ7. Among the halide ions F-, Cl-, Br- and I-, the largest ionic radius belongs to:\n\n(a) F-\n\n(b) Cl-\n\n(c) Br-\n\n(d) I-\n\nQ8. The atomic radius of gallium (135 pm) is smaller than that of aluminium (143 pm), even though gallium lies directly below aluminium in group 13. This anomaly is best explained by:\n\n(a) Poor shielding of the nucleus by the intervening filled 3d10 electrons in gallium, which raises the effective nuclear charge felt by its valence electron\n\n(b) Gallium having fewer electron shells than aluminium\n\n(c) Gallium having a lower nuclear charge than aluminium\n\n(d) Gallium being a non-metal while aluminium is a metal\n\nQ9. When a neutral atom loses an electron to form a cation, the resulting ion is almost always smaller than the parent atom mainly because:\n\n(a) the nucleus simultaneously loses a proton\n\n(b) the remaining electrons now experience a higher effective nuclear charge per electron, and often an entire outer shell is removed\n\n(c) the remaining electrons repel each other more strongly than before\n\n(d) the atomic mass decreases sharply\n\nQ10. For the iron species Fe, Fe2+ and Fe3+, the correct order of decreasing radius is:\n\n(a) Fe > Fe2+ > Fe3+\n\n(b) Fe3+ > Fe2+ > Fe\n\n(c) Fe2+ > Fe > Fe3+\n\n(d) Fe > Fe3+ > Fe2+\n\nQ11. K+ and Cl- are isoelectronic, each having 18 electrons. Which is smaller, and why?\n\n(a) Cl- is smaller because chlorine has a smaller atomic number\n\n(b) K+ is smaller because potassium has a greater nuclear charge (Z = 19) than chlorine (Z = 17), giving a higher effective nuclear charge per electron\n\n(c) They are exactly the same size since they have equal electron counts\n\n(d) Cl- is smaller because it carries a negative charge\n\nQ12. The van der Waals radii of the group 18 elements increase in which of the following orders?\n\n(a) He < Ne < Ar < Kr < Xe\n\n(b) Xe < Kr < Ar < Ne < He\n\n(c) Ar < He < Ne < Kr < Xe\n\n(d) He < Ar < Ne < Xe < Kr\n\n## Multiple Correct (MCQ)\n\n(One or more options may be correct.)\n\nQ13. Which of the following statements about atomic and ionic radii are correct?\n\n(a) Among isoelectronic species, the one with the greater nuclear charge has the smaller radius\n\n(b) The ionic radius of a cation is always smaller than the atomic radius of its parent atom\n\n(c) F- is larger than Na+, even though both have 10 electrons\n\n(d) Atomic radius decreases smoothly and without exception across every row of the periodic table, including the transition series\n\nQ14. For the ten-electron isoelectronic series N3-, O2-, F-, Na+, Mg2+ and Al3+, which of the following statements are correct?\n\n(a) The ionic radius decreases steadily from N3- to Al3+\n\n(b) All six species have identical electronic configurations, $1s^2 2s^2 2p^6$\n\n(c) Al3+ has the highest effective nuclear charge per electron among these species\n\n(d) O2- has a smaller radius than F-\n\nQ15. Due to the lanthanide contraction, which of the following pairs show nearly equal atomic radii despite being one full period apart?\n\n(a) Zr and Hf\n\n(b) Nb and Ta\n\n(c) Mo and W\n\n(d) Ti and Zr\n\nQ16. Which of the following statements correctly describe real trends in atomic radius?\n\n(a) Atomic radius across the first transition series decreases from Sc to Cr and then remains fairly constant through the rest of the series\n\n(b) Zinc has a larger atomic radius than copper partly because its completely filled 3d10 subshell increases electron-electron repulsion\n\n(c) Atomic radius generally increases on descending a group because electrons occupy shells of increasingly higher principal quantum number\n\n(d) The atomic radius of alkali metals decreases steadily on descending group 1\n\nQ17. Manganese can exist in several oxidation states in different compounds. Which of the following statements about its ionic radius are correct?\n\n(a) A higher positive oxidation state corresponds to a smaller ionic radius for the same element\n\n(b) Mn4+ has a smaller ionic radius than Mn2+\n\n(c) Ionic radius decreases progressively as the oxidation state of manganese increases\n\n(d) Fe3+ has a larger ionic radius than Fe2+\n\nQ18. Regarding van der Waals radius, which of the following statements are correct?\n\n(a) The van der Waals radius of an atom is always larger than its covalent radius\n\n(b) Van der Waals radius describes the effective size of an atom in non-bonded contact with a neighbouring atom, such as in a solid noble gas lattice\n\n(c) Van der Waals radii of the noble gases increase steadily on descending group 18\n\n(d) The covalent radius of an atom is always exactly half of its van der Waals radius\n\n## Paragraph / Comprehension\n\nParagraph 1 (for Q19 to Q21): Species that possess the same number of electrons but different nuclear charges are called isoelectronic. Because such species have the same number of electrons, their radius is governed by how strongly the nucleus pulls on that common electron cloud: a larger nuclear charge acting on the same number of electrons produces a higher effective nuclear charge per electron and therefore a smaller radius. A well-known ten-electron isoelectronic series, all sharing the neon-like configuration $1s^2 2s^2 2p^6$, consists of N3-, O2-, F-, Na+, Mg2+ and Al3+, formed as the atomic number rises steadily from nitrogen (Z = 7) to aluminium (Z = 13). Approximate ionic radii for these six species are 171 pm, 140 pm, 136 pm, 102 pm, 72 pm and 53 pm, though not necessarily listed in a matching order.\n\nQ19. Based on the trend described, which species in this series has the smallest radius?\n\n(a) N3-\n\n(b) F-\n\n(c) Mg2+\n\n(d) Al3+\n\nQ20. Which of the following correctly ranks three members of this series in order of increasing radius?\n\n(a) Al3+ < Mg2+ < Na+\n\n(b) Na+ < Mg2+ < Al3+\n\n(c) Mg2+ < Al3+ < Na+\n\n(d) Na+ < Al3+ < Mg2+\n\nQ21. As we move from N3- to Al3+ in this series, which statement is correct regarding the effective nuclear charge (Zeff) experienced by the ten electrons?\n\n(a) Zeff per electron decreases steadily\n\n(b) Zeff per electron increases steadily, causing the steady decrease in radius\n\n(c) Zeff per electron remains constant since the electron count is unchanged\n\n(d) Zeff per electron changes with no discernible pattern\n\nParagraph 2 (for Q22 to Q24): Lanthanide contraction refers to the steady decrease in atomic and ionic radii across the lanthanide series (La to Lu), caused by the imperfect mutual shielding of one 4f electron by another. Because the 5d and 6s electrons of elements that follow the lanthanides must penetrate through this contracted 4f core, the second-row (4d) and third-row (5d) transition metals belonging to the same group end up with almost identical atomic radii, defying the usual expectation that radius should increase substantially on descending a group. This has real chemical consequences: pairs such as zirconium and hafnium, or niobium and tantalum, are notoriously difficult to separate because their chemistries are nearly identical, and the third-row (5d) transition metals are markedly denser than their second-row (4d) counterparts, since a similar atomic volume now houses a considerably larger atomic mass.\n\nQ22. Which pair of transition metals shows almost identical atomic radii primarily as a consequence of the lanthanide contraction?\n\n(a) Ti and Zr\n\n(b) Zr and Hf\n\n(c) Cr and Mo\n\n(d) Fe and Ru\n\nQ23. The unusually high densities of third-row (5d) transition metals compared to their second-row (4d) congeners are best explained by:\n\n(a) 5d metals having a much larger atomic radius than 4d metals\n\n(b) 5d metals having a similar atomic volume to 4d metals but a substantially greater atomic mass\n\n(c) 5d metals adopting a completely different crystal structure in every case\n\n(d) 5d metals having fewer valence electrons\n\nQ24. The imperfect shielding responsible for the lanthanide contraction arises specifically because:\n\n(a) 4f electrons shield each other very effectively\n\n(b) the diffuse, multi-lobed shape of 4f orbitals makes one 4f electron shield another 4f electron rather poorly\n\n(c) 3d electrons shield 4f electrons very poorly\n\n(d) 6s electrons shield 4f electrons completely\n\n## Integer Type\n\nQ25. Among the following eight species \u2014 K+, Ca2+, Cl-, S2-, Ar, P3-, Br- and Se2- \u2014 how many contain exactly 18 electrons?\n\nQ26. Consider the following six pairs: (Na, Na+), (Cl, Cl-), (Fe2+, Fe3+), (S, S2-), (Br, Br-) and (Al, Al3+). In how many of these pairs is the radius of the second species listed greater than the radius of the first species listed?\n\nQ27. Using Slater's rules, the effective nuclear charge (Zeff) experienced by a 3p electron in a chlorine atom (Z = 17, configuration $1s^2 2s^2 2p^6 3s^2 3p^5$) works out to a non-integer value. Rounded to the nearest whole number, what is this Zeff?\n\nQ28. How many of the following five statements about periodic trends in radius are correct?\n\nStatement I: Atomic radius increases from left to right across a period.\n\nStatement II: The ionic radius of an anion is always greater than the atomic radius of its parent atom.\n\nStatement III: Zr and Hf have nearly the same atomic radius because of the lanthanide contraction.\n\nStatement IV: Caesium has a smaller atomic radius than lithium.\n\nStatement V: Among isoelectronic species, a higher nuclear charge corresponds to a smaller radius.\n\nQ29. Given the following approximate ionic radii \u2014 Li+ = 76 pm, K+ = 138 pm, Mg2+ = 72 pm, F- = 133 pm, Al3+ = 53 pm, Cl- = 181 pm, Ba2+ = 135 pm \u2014 how many of these seven ions have a radius smaller than that of Na+ (102 pm)?\n\nQ30. Given the following atomic radii, in pm, for the first transition series \u2014 Sc = 162, Ti = 147, V = 134, Cr = 128, Mn = 127, Fe = 126, Co = 125, Ni = 125, Cu = 128, Zn = 134 \u2014 how many of these ten elements have an atomic radius smaller than that of titanium?\n\nQ31. Among the following seven ions \u2014 Fe2+, Cu+, Zn2+, Cr3+, Sc3+, Ti4+ and Mn2+ \u2014 how many possess an electronic configuration identical to that of a noble gas atom, that is, containing no d electrons at all?\n\nQ32. Consider the 18-electron isoelectronic series Ca2+, K+, Cl-, S2- and P3-, with approximate ionic radii 100 pm, 138 pm, 181 pm, 184 pm and 212 pm respectively. How many of these five ions have an ionic radius greater than 150 pm?\n\n## Numerical Response\n\nQ33. Using Slater's rules, calculate the effective nuclear charge (Zeff) experienced by a 3s valence electron in a magnesium atom (Z = 12, configuration $1s^2 2s^2 2p^6 3s^2$). Give your answer correct to two decimal places.\n\nQ34. Given ionic radii of Na+ = 102 pm and Mg2+ = 72 pm, calculate the ratio (radius of Na+)/(radius of Mg2+), correct to two decimal places.\n\nQ35. The atomic radius of sodium is 186 pm, while the ionic radius of Na+ is 102 pm. Calculate the percentage decrease in radius on forming Na+ from Na, correct to two decimal places.\n\nQ36. Using the Bohr model expression $r_n = 0.529 (n^2/Z)$ in angstrom, calculate the ratio of the radius of a Li2+ ion (Z = 3) to the radius of a hydrogen atom (Z = 1), both in their ground state (n = 1). Give your answer correct to two decimal places.\n\nQ37. Using the Bohr model expression $r_n = 0.529 (n^2/Z)$ in angstrom, calculate the radius of a Be3+ ion in its ground state (Z = 4, n = 1), correct to two decimal places.\n\nQ38. The atomic radius of lanthanum (La, Z = 57) is 187 pm, while that of lutetium (Lu, Z = 71) is 172 pm. Calculate the percentage contraction in atomic radius across the lanthanide series, correct to two decimal places.\n\nQ39. Using Slater's rules, calculate the effective nuclear charge (Zeff) experienced by a 2p electron in a fluorine atom (Z = 9, configuration $1s^2 2s^2 2p^5$), correct to two decimal places.\n\n## Assertion\u2013Reason (A/R)\n\nEach question below has an Assertion (A) and a Reason (R). Choose (a) if both A and R are true and R is the correct explanation of A; (b) if both A and R are true but R is not the correct explanation of A; (c) if A is true but R is false; (d) if A is false but R is true.\n\nQ40. Assertion (A): The ionic radius of Na+ (102 pm) is considerably smaller than the atomic radius of Na (186 pm).\n\nReason (R): On losing its single valence electron, the remaining ten electrons of Na+ occupy a shell one principal quantum number lower than in the neutral atom, and they experience a higher effective nuclear charge per electron.\n\n(a) Both A and R are true, and R is the correct explanation of A\n\n(b) Both A and R are true, but R is not the correct explanation of A\n\n(c) A is true, but R is false\n\n(d) A is false, but R is true\n\nQ41. Assertion (A): The atomic radius of magnesium (160 pm) is greater than that of aluminium (143 pm).\n\nReason (R): Magnesium crystallises in a hexagonal close-packed structure while aluminium crystallises in a face-centred cubic structure.\n\n(a) Both A and R are true, and R is the correct explanation of A\n\n(b) Both A and R are true, but R is not the correct explanation of A\n\n(c) A is true, but R is false\n\n(d) A is false, but R is true\n\nQ42. Assertion (A): Fluoride ion (F-) has a smaller ionic radius than nitride ion (N3-).\n\nReason (R): This is because fluorine has a smaller nuclear charge than nitrogen.\n\n(a) Both A and R are true, and R is the correct explanation of A\n\n(b) Both A and R are true, but R is not the correct explanation of A\n\n(c) A is true, but R is false\n\n(d) A is false, but R is true\n\nQ43. Assertion (A): Atomic radius decreases smoothly and continuously from scandium to zinc across the first transition series.\n\nReason (R): Increasing nuclear charge across a period generally pulls the valence electrons closer to the nucleus, decreasing atomic size.\n\n(a) Both A and R are true, and R is the correct explanation of A\n\n(b) Both A and R are true, but R is not the correct explanation of A\n\n(c) A is true, but R is false\n\n(d) A is false, but R is true\n\nQ44. Assertion (A): Among Na+, Mg2+ and Al3+, the ionic radius decreases in that order, that is, Na+ > Mg2+ > Al3+.\n\nReason (R): All three ions are isoelectronic, possessing ten electrons each, and the one with the greatest nuclear charge experiences the highest effective nuclear charge per electron, pulling the common electron cloud in most tightly.\n\n(a) Both A and R are true, and R is the correct explanation of A\n\n(b) Both A and R are true, but R is not the correct explanation of A\n\n(c) A is true, but R is false\n\n(d) A is false, but R is true\n\nQ45. Assertion (A): The ionic radius of Al3+ is greater than the ionic radius of Mg2+.\n\nReason (R): Among isoelectronic ions, radius decreases as nuclear charge increases.\n\n(a) Both A and R are true, and R is the correct explanation of A\n\n(b) Both A and R are true, but R is not the correct explanation of A\n\n(c) A is true, but R is false\n\n(d) A is false, but R is true\n\n## Matrix Match\n\nQ46. List-I contains four isoelectronic species (each with 10 electrons) and List-II contains four approximate ionic radii in pm. Match each species in List-I with its correct radius in List-II.\n\nList-I\n\n| Code | Species |\n|---|---|\n| A | Na+ |\n| B | Mg2+ |\n| C | F- |\n| D | O2- |\n\nList-II\n\n| Code | Radius (pm) |\n|---|---|\n| p | 140 |\n| q | 133 |\n| r | 102 |\n| s | 72 |\n\nQ47. List-I contains four periodic observations concerning radius, and List-II contains the reason responsible for each. Match them correctly.\n\nList-I\n\n| Code | Observation |\n|---|---|\n| A | Zirconium and hafnium have almost identical atomic radii |\n| B | Fe3+ has a smaller ionic radius than Fe2+ |\n| C | Al3+ has the smallest radius among Na+, Mg2+ and Al3+ |\n| D | Iodide ion is the largest of the halide ions |\n\nList-II\n\n| Code | Reason |\n|---|---|\n| p | Among isoelectronic species, a greater nuclear charge gives a smaller radius |\n| q | The lanthanide contraction causes near-equal radii for corresponding 4d and 5d elements |\n| r | Radius increases down a group as electrons occupy successively higher principal shells |\n| s | Removing an additional electron increases the effective nuclear charge experienced per remaining electron |\n\nQ48. List-I contains four radius-related trends, and List-II gives the correct underlying description. Match them.\n\nList-I\n\n| Code | Trend |\n|---|---|\n| A | Relative order of covalent, metallic and van der Waals radii for the same element |\n| B | Relative order of radius for an isoelectronic anion versus the corresponding isoelectronic cation |\n| C | Atomic radius trend from Sc to Cr in the first transition series |\n| D | Atomic radius trend from Mn to Zn in the first transition series |\n\nList-II\n\n| Code | Description |\n|---|---|\n| p | Covalent radius < metallic radius < van der Waals radius |\n| q | Radius decreases steadily due to rising effective nuclear charge |\n| r | Radius stays roughly constant or rises slightly due to increased electron-electron repulsion as the 3d subshell fills |\n| s | The anion is larger than the isoelectronic cation because it has more electrons per unit nuclear charge |\n\nQ49. List-I contains four ions, and List-II contains descriptions of electronic configuration. Match each ion to the correct description; a description may apply to more than one ion.\n\nList-I\n\n| Code | Ion |\n|---|---|\n| A | Sc3+ |\n| B | Cu+ |\n| C | Ti4+ |\n| D | Zn2+ |\n\nList-II\n\n| Code | Description |\n|---|---|\n| p | True noble-gas configuration, [Ar], with no d electrons |\n| q | Pseudo-noble-gas configuration, [Ar]3d10, completely filled d-subshell |\n| r | [Kr] core configuration |\n| s | Partially filled d-subshell with unpaired electrons |\n\n## Innovative Pattern\n\nQ50. Data-Table Detective. A laboratory logbook records five unidentified species labelled X1 to X5. All five are known to belong to the same 18-electron isoelectronic series, meaning every species has exactly 18 electrons and an argon-like electron cloud. The logbook records only partial data for each, as shown below, with missing entries marked by a question mark.\n\n| Species | Electrons | Protons (Z) | Charge | Radius (pm) |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| X1 | 18 | ? | +2 | 100 |\n| X2 | 18 | 17 | ? | 181 |\n| X3 | ? | 19 | +1 | 138 |\n| X4 | 18 | 16 | -2 | ? |\n| X5 | 18 | ? | +3 | 74.5 |\n\nUsing the relation charge = protons minus electrons, and the fact that every species has 18 electrons, identify the missing entries and hence compute the sum: (protons in X1) + (electrons in X3) + (protons in X5). Report this sum as a single integer.\n\n## Answer Key\n\n| Question | Answer |\n|---|---|\n| Q1 | (a) |\n| Q2 | (a) |\n| Q3 | (b) |\n| Q4 | (b) |\n| Q5 | (a) |\n| Q6 | (d) |\n| Q7 | (d) |\n| Q8 | (a) |\n| Q9 | (b) |\n| Q10 | (a) |\n| Q11 | (b) |\n| Q12 | (a) |\n| Q13 | (a), (b), (c) |\n| Q14 | (a), (b), (c) |\n| Q15 | (a), (b), (c) |\n| Q16 | (a), (b), (c) |\n| Q17 | (a), (b), (c) |\n| Q18 | (a), (b), (c) |\n| Q19 | (d) |\n| Q20 | (a) |\n| Q21 | (b) |\n| Q22 | (b) |\n| Q23 | (b) |\n| Q24 | (b) |\n| Q25 | 6 |\n| Q26 | 3 |\n| Q27 | 6 |\n| Q28 | 3 |\n| Q29 | 3 |\n| Q30 | 8 |\n| Q31 | 2 |\n| Q32 | 3 |\n| Q33 | 2.85 |\n| Q34 | 1.42 |\n| Q35 | 45.16 |\n| Q36 | 0.33 |\n| Q37 | 0.13 |\n| Q38 | 8.02 |\n| Q39 | 5.20 |\n| Q40 | (a) |\n| Q41 | (b) |\n| Q42 | (c) |\n| Q43 | (d) |\n| Q44 | (a) |\n| Q45 | (d) |\n| Q46 | A-r, B-s, C-q, D-p |\n| Q47 | A-q, B-s, C-p, D-r |\n| Q48 | A-p, B-s, C-q, D-r |\n| Q49 | A-p, B-q, C-p, D-q |\n| Q50 | 59 |\n\n## Worked Solutions\n\nS1. Standard NCERT-level atomic radii for period 3 decrease steadily left to right: Na (186 pm) > Mg (160 pm) > Al (143 pm) > Si (117 pm), because effective nuclear charge rises while the principal shell stays the same. Option (a) is the only assignment consistent with this decreasing trend.\n\nS2. All four species have 18 electrons but different nuclear charges: S (Z=16), Cl (Z=17), K (Z=19), Ca (Z=20). A higher nuclear charge pulls the same 18 electrons in more tightly, so radius decreases as Z increases, giving S2- > Cl- > K+ > Ca2+.\n\nS3. Zr (period 5) and Hf (period 6) lie in the same group, but the 14 lanthanides intervene between them in the periodic table. The resulting lanthanide contraction almost exactly cancels the expected increase in radius on descending the group, so Zr and Hf end up nearly identical in size (about 160 pm and 159 pm).\n\nS4. Going from Cu ([Ar]3d10 4s1) to Zn ([Ar]3d10 4s2), the 3d subshell is already full in both, so the extra 4s electron in Zn adds electron-electron repulsion without a proportionate increase in shielding, causing a slight expansion rather than the expected contraction.\n\nS5. For the same element, van der Waals contacts occur between non-bonded atoms and are the loosest form of contact, metallic bonding is intermediate, and a covalent bond pulls the two nuclei closest together, giving covalent < metallic < van der Waals.\n\nS6. All four are isoelectronic with 10 electrons, but nuclear charges are F (9), Na (11), Mg (12), Al (13). The highest nuclear charge, Al3+, exerts the greatest pull on the fixed number of electrons, giving it the smallest radius.\n\nS7. Down group 17, an additional principal shell is added at each step (F to Cl to Br to I), and this shell addition dominates over the increasing nuclear charge, so ionic radius increases down the group, making I- the largest.\n\nS8. Gallium's valence electron must penetrate a filled but poorly shielding 3d10 subshell absent in aluminium's core, so gallium experiences an unusually high effective nuclear charge, shrinking it below its expected size relative to Al.\n\nS9. Removing an electron does not change the number of protons; instead, the remaining electrons are pulled in by the same nuclear charge with one less electron to share it (and often lose the outermost shell entirely), so the cation is smaller than the parent atom.\n\nS10. Removing electrons from Fe successively increases the positive charge while the number of protons stays fixed, raising Zeff per electron each time, so radius falls steadily: Fe > Fe2+ > Fe3+.\n\nS11. K+ (Z=19) and Cl- (Z=17) both have 18 electrons, but potassium's greater nuclear charge produces a higher effective nuclear charge per electron, contracting K+ to a smaller radius than Cl-.\n\nS12. Van der Waals radius reflects the size of the outermost filled shell; as one descends group 18, an extra shell is added at each step, so the van der Waals radius increases steadily: He < Ne < Ar < Kr < Xe.\n\nS13. (a) and (c) restate the isoelectronic principle correctly; (b) is the general rule for cation formation. (d) is false because transition-series radii flatten out or slightly rise near the end of the series rather than decreasing smoothly throughout.\n\nS14. All six species share the neon-like 10-electron configuration, so (b) is true; nuclear charge rises steadily from N to Al, so radius falls steadily (a) and Al3+ has the greatest Zeff per electron (c). (d) is false since O2- (140 pm) is larger than F- (136 pm), not smaller.\n\nS15. Zr/Hf, Nb/Ta and Mo/W are the classic 4d-5d pairs whose radii are nearly equalised by the lanthanide contraction. Ti and Zr are not such a pair; Zr is noticeably larger than Ti since no lanthanide contraction operates between periods 4 and 5 for group 4.\n\nS16. (a)-(c) are established facts: radius falls till around Cr then flattens, Zn's filled 3d10 raises electron repulsion, and new shells added down a group increase radius. (d) is false because alkali metal radius increases down the group (Li < Na < K < Rb < Cs).\n\nS17. As oxidation state rises, the same nucleus holds progressively fewer electrons, raising Zeff per electron and shrinking the ion, so Mn2+ > Mn3+ > Mn4+, confirming (a), (b) and (c); (d) is false since Fe3+ is smaller than Fe2+, following the same principle.\n\nS18. Van der Waals radius always exceeds covalent radius for the same atom (a), and it specifically describes non-bonded contact distances such as in solid noble gases (b); it increases down group 18 (c). (d) is false \u2014 there is no fixed factor-of-two relationship between the two radii.\n\nS19. Al3+ has the highest nuclear charge (Z = 13) among the six 10-electron species listed, so it experiences the greatest pull on the shared electron cloud and has the smallest radius, about 53 pm.\n\nS20. Using the given approximate values, Al3+ (53 pm) < Mg2+ (72 pm) < Na+ (102 pm), consistent with increasing nuclear charge producing decreasing radius through the series in reverse.\n\nS21. Because the electron count stays fixed at ten throughout the series while the nuclear charge climbs from Z = 7 (N) to Z = 13 (Al), the effective nuclear charge experienced by each electron rises steadily, which is exactly why the radius contracts steadily.\n\nS22. Zr and Hf are the textbook example: despite lying one full period apart in group 4, the lanthanide contraction leaves their atomic radii almost identical (about 160 pm and 159 pm).\n\nS23. Since Zr/Hf-type pairs have nearly the same atomic volume but the 5d element has a much larger atomic mass (due to the additional lanthanide-series protons and neutrons), the density (mass/volume) of the 5d metal is significantly higher.\n\nS24. The 4f orbitals are radially very diffuse and poorly overlap with each other, so one 4f electron does a poor job of shielding another 4f electron from the increasing nuclear charge, causing the cumulative contraction across the lanthanide series.\n\nS25. K+, Ca2+, Cl-, S2-, Ar and P3- are all isoelectronic with argon and have 18 electrons each; Br- (36 electrons) and Se2- (36 electrons) do not. That gives 6 species with exactly 18 electrons.\n\nS26. Forming an anion (Cl to Cl-, S to S2-, Br to Br-) always increases radius, while forming a cation (Na to Na+, Al to Al3+) or further oxidising a cation (Fe2+ to Fe3+) always decreases it. Only the three anion-forming pairs show an increase, so the count is 3.\n\nS27. For the 3p electron of Cl: same-group (3s,3p) contribution = 6 \u00d7 0.35 = 2.10; n-1 shell (2s,2p, 8 electrons) contributes 8 \u00d7 0.85 = 6.80; n-2 shell (1s, 2 electrons) contributes 2 \u00d7 1.00 = 2.00. Total shielding = 10.90, so Zeff = 17 \u2212 10.90 = 6.10, which rounds to 6.\n\nS28. Statement I is false (radius decreases, not increases, across a period). Statement II, III and V are true standard facts. Statement IV is false since Cs is much larger than Li. So exactly 3 statements are correct.\n\nS29. Comparing to Na+ (102 pm): Li+ (76 pm), Mg2+ (72 pm) and Al3+ (53 pm) are all smaller, while K+ (138), F- (133), Cl- (181) and Ba2+ (135) are all larger. That gives 3 ions smaller than Na+.\n\nS30. Sc (162 pm) is the only element in the list larger than Ti (147 pm); the remaining eight elements \u2014 V, Cr, Mn, Fe, Co, Ni, Cu and Zn \u2014 all have radii smaller than or equal to 134 pm, which is less than Ti's 147 pm, giving a count of 8.\n\nS31. Sc3+ (Z=21, minus 3 electrons = 18 electrons, configuration [Ar]) and Ti4+ (Z=22, minus 4 = 18 electrons, [Ar]) are the only two with a pure noble-gas configuration and zero d electrons. Fe2+, Cr3+ and Mn2+ retain partially filled d subshells, while Cu+ and Zn2+ retain a filled but present 3d10 subshell, so none of these five qualify. The count is 2.\n\nS32. Among the given radii, Cl- (181 pm), S2- (184 pm) and P3- (212 pm) all exceed 150 pm, while K+ (138 pm) and Ca2+ (100 pm) do not. The count is 3.\n\nS33. For the 3s electron of Mg: same-group contribution = 1 \u00d7 0.35 = 0.35; n-1 shell (2s,2p, 8 electrons) = 8 \u00d7 0.85 = 6.80; n-2 shell (1s, 2 electrons) = 2 \u00d7 1.00 = 2.00. Total shielding = 9.15, so Zeff = 12 \u2212 9.15 = 2.85.\n\nS34. The ratio is 102/72 = 1.4166..., which rounds to 1.42.\n\nS35. Percentage decrease = (186 \u2212 102)/186 \u00d7 100 = 84/186 \u00d7 100 = 45.1613%, which rounds to 45.16.\n\nS36. Using r \u221d n\u00b2/Z with n = 1 for both, the ratio r(Li2+)/r(H) = (1/3)/(1/1) = 1/3 = 0.3333, which rounds to 0.33.\n\nS37. r(Be3+) = 0.529 \u00d7 (1\u00b2/4) = 0.529/4 = 0.13225 \u00c5, which rounds to 0.13.\n\nS38. Percentage contraction = (187 \u2212 172)/187 \u00d7 100 = 15/187 \u00d7 100 = 8.0214%, which rounds to 8.02.\n\nS39. For the 2p electron of F: same-group (2s,2p) contribution = 6 \u00d7 0.35 = 2.10; n-1 shell (1s, 2 electrons) = 2 \u00d7 0.85 = 1.70. Total shielding = 3.80, so Zeff = 9 \u2212 3.80 = 5.20.\n\nS40. Na+ loses its lone 3s electron, leaving a smaller 10-electron core that is pulled in by the same 11 protons, sharply increasing Zeff per electron; this directly and correctly explains the large drop in radius, so the answer is (a).\n\nS41. Mg (160 pm) is indeed larger than Al (143 pm) because Al has a higher effective nuclear charge as it lies one place to the right in the same period; the given reason about crystal structures, though factually true, is not the actual cause of the radius difference, so the answer is (b).\n\nS42. F- is genuinely smaller than N3- because fluorine has a higher nuclear charge (Z=9) than nitrogen (Z=7), not a smaller one as the reason claims; so A is true but R is false, giving (c).\n\nS43. Atomic radius in the 3d series decreases only up to about Cr/Mn and then stays roughly flat or rises slightly toward Zn due to increasing electron-electron repulsion in the filling d-subshell, so A (claiming a smooth continuous decrease) is false. The reason itself states a genuine general periodic principle and is true, giving (d).\n\nS44. All three ions share 10 electrons, and increasing nuclear charge from Na (11) to Mg (12) to Al (13) raises Zeff per electron steadily, correctly explaining the observed radius order Na+ > Mg2+ > Al3+, so the answer is (a).\n\nS45. In reality Al3+ (about 53 pm) is smaller than Mg2+ (about 72 pm), so A is false; the reason, that isoelectronic radius falls as nuclear charge rises, is a true general principle (and in fact correctly predicts that Al3+, having the greater charge, should be smaller), so the answer is (d).\n\nS46. All four species are isoelectronic with 10 electrons; increasing nuclear charge from O (8) to F (9) to Na (11) to Mg (12) gives decreasing radius, so O2- = 140 pm (p), F- = 133 pm (q), Na+ = 102 pm (r), Mg2+ = 72 pm (s). Hence A-r, B-s, C-q, D-p.\n\nS47. A pairs with the lanthanide-contraction reason (q); B pairs with the \"extra charge raises Zeff per electron\" reason (s); C, comparing three isoelectronic cations, pairs with the isoelectronic nuclear-charge reason (p); D, a group trend, pairs with the added-shell reason (r).\n\nS48. A is the general size hierarchy of radius types (p); B is the isoelectronic anion/cation comparison (s); C is the steady fall in radius from Sc to Cr due to rising Zeff (q); D is the roughly constant/slightly rising radius from Mn to Zn due to d-electron repulsion (r).\n\nS49. Sc3+ and Ti4+ both reduce to the pure [Ar] configuration with no d electrons (p); Cu+ and Zn2+ both retain a filled 3d10 subshell, a pseudo-noble-gas configuration (q). Hence A-p, B-q, C-p, D-q.\n\nS50. Since every species has 18 electrons, charge = protons \u2212 18. X1 has charge +2, so protons = 20 (this is Ca2+). X3 has 19 protons and charge +1, so electrons = 19 \u2212 1 = 18, confirming consistency (this is K+). X5 has charge +3, so protons = 18 + 3 = 21 (this is Sc3+). The requested sum is 20 (protons in X1) + 18 (electrons in X3) + 21 (protons in X5) = 59.\n";
const RAW_MD_IONIZATION = "## Single Correct (SCQ)\n\nQ1. The first ionization enthalpies (in kJ/mol) of four period-3 elements are approximately 496, 738, 578 and 786, though not necessarily in the order Na, Mg, Al, Si. Which of the following correctly matches each element to its value?\n\n(a) Na = 496, Mg = 738, Al = 578, Si = 786\n\n(b) Na = 738, Mg = 496, Al = 786, Si = 578\n\n(c) Na = 578, Mg = 786, Al = 496, Si = 738\n\n(d) Na = 786, Mg = 578, Al = 738, Si = 496\n\nQ2. Both beryllium/boron and nitrogen/oxygen show a reversal in the expected first ionization enthalpy trend. Which of these two reversals is specifically explained by the extra stability of a half-filled subshell rather than a completely filled one?\n\n(a) Be > B\n\n(b) N > O\n\n(c) Mg > Al\n\n(d) Zn > Ga\n\nQ3. Nitrogen's first ionization enthalpy (1402 kJ/mol) exceeds that of oxygen (1314 kJ/mol) even though oxygen has one more proton. The correct reason for this is:\n\n(a) increased shielding of nitrogen's valence electrons by inner shells\n\n(b) the exceptional stability of nitrogen's half-filled $2p^3$ configuration, which oxygen's $2p^4$ configuration does not share\n\n(c) the lanthanide contraction, which is irrelevant here\n\n(d) nitrogen having a larger atomic size than oxygen\n\nQ4. Aluminium has the ground-state configuration $1s^2 2s^2 2p^6 3s^2 3p^1$. Between which two successive ionization enthalpies would the largest relative jump be expected?\n\n(a) IE1 to IE2\n\n(b) IE2 to IE3\n\n(c) IE3 to IE4\n\n(d) IE4 to IE5\n\nQ5. An element X shows successive ionization enthalpies (in MJ/mol) of 0.58, 1.82, 2.75, 11.6 and 14.8. Based on the location of the large jump, element X most likely belongs to which group?\n\n(a) Group 13\n\n(b) Group 14\n\n(c) Group 2\n\n(d) Group 1\n\nQ6. Which of the following has the highest first ionization enthalpy of any element in the periodic table?\n\n(a) He\n\n(b) Ne\n\n(c) F\n\n(d) H\n\nQ7. Considering only Li, Be, B and C, which experiences the greatest effective nuclear charge (Zeff) on its outermost valence electron, and therefore requires the most energy to remove that electron among these four?\n\n(a) Li\n\n(b) Be\n\n(c) B\n\n(d) C\n\nQ8. Ionization enthalpy decreases on descending a group even though the nuclear charge increases with atomic number. The dominant reason for this is:\n\n(a) the increase in atomic radius and shielding by additional inner shells outweighs the increase in nuclear charge\n\n(b) the nuclear charge actually decreases down a group\n\n(c) electrons are removed from a different element altogether\n\n(d) valence electrons become negatively charged\n\nQ9. Copper, with configuration $[Ar]3d^{10}4s^1$, has a lower first ionization enthalpy than expected from a naive extrapolation of the 3d-series trend. This is best explained because:\n\n(a) removing the single 4s electron leaves behind an exceptionally stable, completely filled $3d^{10}$ configuration\n\n(b) copper has a smaller atomic radius than nickel\n\n(c) copper has a lower effective nuclear charge than nickel\n\n(d) copper belongs to group 12 of the periodic table\n\nQ10. Among Na, Mg, Al and Si, which element would be expected to show the LARGEST ratio of IE2 to IE1?\n\n(a) Na\n\n(b) Mg\n\n(c) Al\n\n(d) Si\n\nQ11. The first ionization enthalpies of the halogens are F = 1681, Cl = 1251, Br = 1140 and I = 1008 kJ/mol. Which of the following is the correct order of first ionization enthalpy for these elements?\n\n(a) F > Cl > Br > I\n\n(b) I > Br > Cl > F\n\n(c) Cl > F > Br > I\n\n(d) F > Br > Cl > I\n\nQ12. Which of the following correctly represents the trend in first ionization enthalpy on descending group 2 (Be, Mg, Ca, Sr, Ba)?\n\n(a) Be > Mg > Ca > Sr > Ba\n\n(b) Ba > Sr > Ca > Mg > Be\n\n(c) Be > Ca > Mg > Ba > Sr\n\n(d) Mg > Be > Ca > Sr > Ba\n\n## Multiple Correct (MCQ)\n\n(One or more options may be correct.)\n\nQ13. Which of the following relationships in first ionization enthalpy are genuine anomalies caused by extra electronic stability?\n\n(a) Be > B\n\n(b) N > O\n\n(c) Mg > Al\n\n(d) Na > Mg\n\nQ14. Regarding the successive ionization enthalpies of aluminium ($1s^2 2s^2 2p^6 3s^2 3p^1$), which of the following statements are correct?\n\n(a) Each successive ionization enthalpy is always greater than the one before it, for any element\n\n(b) The jump from IE3 to IE4 is proportionally much larger than the jump from IE1 to IE2\n\n(c) IE1 corresponds to removal of the single $3p$ electron\n\n(d) IE4 corresponds to removal of a $3s$ electron\n\nQ15. Which of the following statements about the factors governing ionization enthalpy are correct?\n\n(a) An increase in effective nuclear charge (Zeff) increases ionization enthalpy\n\n(b) An increase in atomic radius increases ionization enthalpy\n\n(c) Extra stability from a completely filled or exactly half-filled subshell increases ionization enthalpy relative to the naive trend\n\n(d) Increased shielding by inner-shell electrons lowers the effective nuclear charge on valence electrons and thereby decreases ionization enthalpy\n\nQ16. Regarding the successive ionization enthalpies of magnesium ($1s^2 2s^2 2p^6 3s^2$), which of the following statements are correct?\n\n(a) IE3 is very much greater than IE2\n\n(b) IE1 is always less than IE2\n\n(c) Mg2+ has the same electronic configuration as Ne\n\n(d) Mg2+ is larger in radius than Na+\n\nQ17. Considering the first ionization enthalpies across period 3 (Na, Mg, Al, Si, P, S, Cl, Ar), which of the following statements are correct?\n\n(a) IE1 generally increases from left to right across the period\n\n(b) There is a dip in IE1 from Mg to Al\n\n(c) There is a dip in IE1 from P to S\n\n(d) Ar has a lower IE1 than Cl\n\nQ18. Regarding Slater's rules as applied to estimating ionization enthalpy trends, which of the following statements are correct?\n\n(a) The effective nuclear charge (Zeff) calculated using Slater's rules generally increases across a period for valence electrons\n\n(b) Slater's rules treat all electrons within the same principal shell identically, regardless of whether they occupy s, p, d or f subshells\n\n(c) The shielding constant contributed by another electron in the same (ns, np) group is 0.35, except for a 1s electron, where it is 0.30\n\n(d) For an s or p electron being shielded, electrons with a principal quantum number one less than that of the electron under consideration contribute a shielding constant of 1.00 each\n\n## Paragraph / Comprehension\n\nParagraph 1 (for Q19 to Q21): When electrons are removed one after another from a gaseous atom, each successive ionization enthalpy is always higher than the preceding one, since the electron being removed is pulled away from a progressively more positively charged species. The increase, however, is not uniform. Once every valence electron of an atom has been stripped away, removing a further electron means breaking into a completely filled, noble-gas-like inner core, and this always requires a disproportionately large jump in energy compared with the jumps seen among the valence electrons themselves.\n\nQ19. For phosphorus, with configuration $1s^2 2s^2 2p^6 3s^2 3p^3$ and five valence electrons, between which two successive ionization enthalpies would the biggest relative jump be expected?\n\n(a) IE2 to IE3\n\n(b) IE3 to IE4\n\n(c) IE4 to IE5\n\n(d) IE5 to IE6\n\nQ20. An element M shows successive ionization enthalpies (in MJ/mol) of 0.90, 1.76, 14.8 and 21.0. Based on where the large jump occurs, element M most likely belongs to which group?\n\n(a) Group 1\n\n(b) Group 2\n\n(c) Group 13\n\n(d) Group 14\n\nQ21. Which of the following statements about successive ionization enthalpies is true for every element without exception?\n\n(a) The ratio IE2/IE1 is always greater than 2\n\n(b) IE(n+1) is always greater than IE(n) for every value of n\n\n(c) The largest jump always occurs between IE1 and IE2\n\n(d) Successive ionization enthalpies increase by a constant, fixed amount each time\n\nParagraph 2 (for Q22 to Q24): Moving across period 2 from lithium to neon, the first ionization enthalpy generally rises because the effective nuclear charge experienced by the outermost electron increases while the electrons remain confined to the same principal shell. Two reversals interrupt this otherwise smooth rise: beryllium's IE1 exceeds boron's, and nitrogen's IE1 exceeds oxygen's. Both reversals arise from extra electronic stability \u2014 a completely filled $2s^2$ subshell in beryllium, and a half-filled $2p^3$ subshell in nitrogen \u2014 which makes removing the very next electron comparatively easier for boron and for oxygen respectively.\n\nQ22. Which pair of period-2 elements shows an IE1 reversal caused by a completely filled subshell rather than a half-filled one?\n\n(a) Be, B\n\n(b) N, O\n\n(c) B, C\n\n(d) O, F\n\nQ23. In oxygen ($2p^4$), the fourth $2p$ electron must pair up with an already singly occupied orbital. What is the primary reason this makes oxygen's IE1 lower than nitrogen's?\n\n(a) Oxygen has a larger atomic radius than nitrogen\n\n(b) The inter-electronic (Coulombic) repulsion between the two paired electrons sharing one $2p$ orbital destabilises that electron, making it easier to remove\n\n(c) Oxygen has a lower nuclear charge than nitrogen\n\n(d) Oxygen's valence electrons are shielded by an additional inner shell absent in nitrogen\n\nQ24. By exactly the same reasoning applied to period 2, which pair of period-3 elements shows an analogous half-filled-subshell-based IE1 reversal?\n\n(a) Na, Mg\n\n(b) Al, Si\n\n(c) P, S\n\n(d) S, Cl\n\n## Integer Type\n\nQ25. An element shows successive ionization enthalpies (in kJ/mol) of 590, 1145, 4912, 6491 and 8153. How many valence electrons does this element most likely have, based on where the large jump in ionization enthalpy occurs?\n\nQ26. Consider six period-2 elements in order: Li, Be, B, C, N, O, with first ionization enthalpies (kJ/mol) of 520, 899, 801, 1086, 1402 and 1314 respectively. Moving from left to right and comparing each element only to the one immediately before it, in how many cases does the ionization enthalpy increase?\n\nQ27. How many of the following six statements about ionization enthalpy are correct?\n\nStatement I: The first ionization enthalpy of a noble gas is the highest in its period.\n\nStatement II: Ionization enthalpy decreases on descending a group.\n\nStatement III: The second ionization enthalpy of an element is always less than its first.\n\nStatement IV: Chromium has a lower first ionization enthalpy than a naive trend would predict, because removing its single $4s$ electron leaves behind a stable half-filled $3d^5 4s^0$ configuration.\n\nStatement V: Fluorine has a higher first ionization enthalpy than neon.\n\nStatement VI: Magnesium has a greater first ionization enthalpy than aluminium.\n\nQ28. Given the first ionization enthalpies (kJ/mol) N = 1402, O = 1314, F = 1681, Ne = 2081, Na = 496, Mg = 738 and Al = 578, how many of these seven elements have a first ionization enthalpy exceeding 1000 kJ/mol?\n\nQ29. An element X has the ground-state configuration $[Ne]3s^2 3p^3$. Its successive ionization enthalpies show one exceptionally large jump. Immediately after removing how many electrons (that is, between IE_n and IE_(n+1), report n) does this large jump occur?\n\nQ30. Using Slater's rules, the effective nuclear charge (Zeff) experienced by the electron removed during the first ionization of phosphorus (Z = 15, configuration $1s^2 2s^2 2p^6 3s^2 3p^3$) works out to a non-integer value. Rounded to the nearest whole number, what is this Zeff?\n\nQ31. Given first ionization enthalpies (kJ/mol) for period 3: Na = 496, Mg = 738, Al = 578, Si = 786, P = 1012, S = 1000, Cl = 1251, Ar = 1521, how many elements in this list show a LOWER first ionization enthalpy than the element immediately before them in the period?\n\nQ32. Among the following five pairs \u2014 (Be, B), (N, O), (Mg, Al), (P, S) and (Na, Mg) \u2014 in how many pairs does the FIRST-listed element have a HIGHER first ionization enthalpy than the SECOND-listed element, despite the second having the greater atomic number?\n\n## Numerical Response\n\nQ33. Using the Bohr formula $IE = 13.6 (Z^2/n^2)$ in eV for hydrogen-like species, calculate the ionization energy of Li2+ (Z = 3, n = 1), correct to two decimal places.\n\nQ34. Using the Bohr formula, calculate the ratio of the ionization energy of He+ (Z = 2, n = 1) to that of a hydrogen atom (Z = 1, n = 1), correct to two decimal places.\n\nQ35. Using Slater's rules, calculate the effective nuclear charge (Zeff) experienced by the valence $3s$ electron of sodium (Z = 11, configuration $1s^2 2s^2 2p^6 3s^1$), correct to two decimal places.\n\nQ36. The first ionization enthalpies of sodium and magnesium are 496 kJ/mol and 738 kJ/mol respectively. Calculate the percentage increase in first ionization enthalpy from sodium to magnesium, correct to two decimal places.\n\nQ37. The first three successive ionization enthalpies of aluminium are IE1 = 578 kJ/mol, IE2 = 1817 kJ/mol and IE3 = 2745 kJ/mol. Calculate the ratio IE2/IE1, correct to two decimal places.\n\nQ38. The second ionization enthalpy of magnesium is 1450 kJ/mol. Using Avogadro's number as $6.022 \\times 10^{23}$, calculate the energy required to remove an electron from a single Mg+ ion, expressed in units of $10^{-19}$ J and correct to two decimal places.\n\nQ39. Using the formula $E = -13.6 (Z^2/n^2)$ in eV, calculate the magnitude of the energy needed to remove the last electron from a ground-state Be3+ ion (Z = 4, n = 1), correct to two decimal places.\n\n## Assertion\u2013Reason (A/R)\n\nEach question below has an Assertion (A) and a Reason (R). Choose (a) if both A and R are true and R is the correct explanation of A; (b) if both A and R are true but R is not the correct explanation of A; (c) if A is true but R is false; (d) if A is false but R is true.\n\nQ40. Assertion (A): The second ionization enthalpy of sodium is vastly greater than its first ionization enthalpy.\n\nReason (R): Removing the second electron from Na+ requires breaking into the completely filled, neon-like inner core, which is far more difficult than removing the single loosely held valence electron.\n\n(a) Both A and R are true, and R is the correct explanation of A\n\n(b) Both A and R are true, but R is not the correct explanation of A\n\n(c) A is true, but R is false\n\n(d) A is false, but R is true\n\nQ41. Assertion (A): The first ionization enthalpy of magnesium (738 kJ/mol) is higher than that of aluminium (578 kJ/mol).\n\nReason (R): Ionization enthalpy generally decreases on descending a group as atomic size and shielding by inner shells increase.\n\n(a) Both A and R are true, and R is the correct explanation of A\n\n(b) Both A and R are true, but R is not the correct explanation of A\n\n(c) A is true, but R is false\n\n(d) A is false, but R is true\n\nQ42. Assertion (A): Fluorine has the highest first ionization enthalpy among all the halogens.\n\nReason (R): This is because fluorine has the highest electron gain enthalpy magnitude of any element in the periodic table.\n\n(a) Both A and R are true, and R is the correct explanation of A\n\n(b) Both A and R are true, but R is not the correct explanation of A\n\n(c) A is true, but R is false\n\n(d) A is false, but R is true\n\nQ43. Assertion (A): Boron has a higher first ionization enthalpy than beryllium.\n\nReason (R): Removing an electron from boron's singly occupied $2p$ orbital requires less energy than removing an electron from beryllium's filled, more penetrating $2s$ orbital, because the $2p$ electron is comparatively shielded and lies at higher energy.\n\n(a) Both A and R are true, and R is the correct explanation of A\n\n(b) Both A and R are true, but R is not the correct explanation of A\n\n(c) A is true, but R is false\n\n(d) A is false, but R is true\n\nQ44. Assertion (A): Among Na+, Mg2+ and Al3+, the ionic radius decreases in that order, that is, Na+ > Mg2+ > Al3+. (This fact underlies why successive removal of electrons in this series requires progressively more energy per electron removed for the parent atoms.)\n\nReason (R): All three ions are isoelectronic, and the one with the greatest nuclear charge experiences the highest effective nuclear charge per electron.\n\n(a) Both A and R are true, and R is the correct explanation of A\n\n(b) Both A and R are true, but R is not the correct explanation of A\n\n(c) A is true, but R is false\n\n(d) A is false, but R is true\n\nQ45. Assertion (A): Aluminium's fourth ionization enthalpy (IE4) is far greater than its third (IE3).\n\nReason (R): IE4 corresponds to removing an electron from aluminium's completely filled $2p^6$ inner core, immediately after all three valence electrons ($3s^2 3p^1$) have already been removed.\n\n(a) Both A and R are true, and R is the correct explanation of A\n\n(b) Both A and R are true, but R is not the correct explanation of A\n\n(c) A is true, but R is false\n\n(d) A is false, but R is true\n\n## Matrix Match\n\nQ46. List-I contains four period-3 elements and List-II contains four approximate first ionization enthalpy values in kJ/mol. Match each element in List-I with its correct value in List-II.\n\nList-I\n\n| Code | Element |\n|---|---|\n| A | Na |\n| B | Mg |\n| C | Al |\n| D | Si |\n\nList-II\n\n| Code | IE1 (kJ/mol) |\n|---|---|\n| p | 786 |\n| q | 496 |\n| r | 738 |\n| s | 578 |\n\nQ47. List-I contains four observations about ionization enthalpy anomalies, and List-II contains the reason responsible for each. Match them correctly.\n\nList-I\n\n| Code | Observation |\n|---|---|\n| A | Be has a higher IE1 than B |\n| B | N has a higher IE1 than O, attributable to nitrogen's own configuration |\n| C | Na's IE2 is far larger than its IE1 |\n| D | O's IE1 is lower than a naive trend predicts, attributable to oxygen's own configuration |\n\nList-II\n\n| Code | Reason |\n|---|---|\n| p | Fully-filled $2s^2$ subshell stability |\n| q | Half-filled $2p^3$ subshell extra stability |\n| r | Huge jump from core-breaking after all valence electrons are removed |\n| s | Electron-electron repulsion from forced pairing in a $2p^4$ configuration |\n| t | Lanthanide contraction (unrelated decoy) |\n\nQ48. List-I contains four ionization-enthalpy trends, and List-II gives the correct underlying description. Match them.\n\nList-I\n\n| Code | Trend |\n|---|---|\n| A | First ionization enthalpy trend down group 1 |\n| B | First ionization enthalpy trend across period 2, left to right |\n| C | First ionization enthalpy trend across the 3d series, Sc to Zn |\n| D | First ionization enthalpy trend down group 18 |\n\nList-II\n\n| Code | Description |\n|---|---|\n| p | Rises overall due to increasing Zeff, but with no reversal at all |\n| q | Decreases steadily because the added valence electron is progressively farther from the nucleus and better shielded |\n| r | Rises overall but with two reversals, at Be/B and at N/O |\n| s | Decreases steadily because size increases down the group despite the rise in nuclear charge |\n| t | Rises gradually overall but fluctuates mildly due to variable shielding by the filling $(n-1)d$ electrons |\n\nQ49. List-I contains four alkali metals and List-II contains four approximate first ionization enthalpy values in kJ/mol. Match each metal to its correct value.\n\nList-I\n\n| Code | Element |\n|---|---|\n| A | Li |\n| B | Na |\n| C | K |\n| D | Cs |\n\nList-II\n\n| Code | IE1 (kJ/mol) |\n|---|---|\n| p | 520 |\n| q | 496 |\n| r | 419 |\n| s | 376 |\n| t | 738 (decoy, belongs to Mg) |\n\n## Innovative Pattern\n\nQ50. Data-Table Detective. A reference table records the successive ionization enthalpies (in kJ/mol) of five unidentified period-2/period-3 elements, labelled X1 to X5, each showing exactly one exceptionally large jump somewhere in its sequence.\n\nX1: 1402, 2856, 4578, 7475, 9445, 53266\n\nX2: 738, 1450, 7732, 10540\n\nX3: 578, 1816, 2744, 11577\n\nX4: 1000, 2251, 3361, 4564, 7013, 8495, 27106\n\nX5: 1251, 2298, 3822, 5158, 6540, 9362, 11018, 38600\n\nFor each element, the number of valence electrons equals the position (counting from IE1) of the ionization enthalpy immediately BEFORE the exceptionally large jump (for example, if the huge jump occurs between IE3 and IE4, the element has 3 valence electrons). Determine the number of valence electrons for each of X1 to X5, and report the sum of all five values as a single integer.\n\n## Answer Key\n\n| Question | Answer |\n|---|---|\n| Q1 | (a) |\n| Q2 | (b) |\n| Q3 | (b) |\n| Q4 | (c) |\n| Q5 | (a) |\n| Q6 | (a) |\n| Q7 | (d) |\n| Q8 | (a) |\n| Q9 | (a) |\n| Q10 | (a) |\n| Q11 | (a) |\n| Q12 | (a) |\n| Q13 | (a), (b), (c) |\n| Q14 | (a), (b), (c) |\n| Q15 | (a), (c), (d) |\n| Q16 | (a), (b), (c) |\n| Q17 | (a), (b), (c) |\n| Q18 | (a), (c) |\n| Q19 | (d) |\n| Q20 | (b) |\n| Q21 | (b) |\n| Q22 | (a) |\n| Q23 | (b) |\n| Q24 | (c) |\n| Q25 | 2 |\n| Q26 | 3 |\n| Q27 | 4 |\n| Q28 | 4 |\n| Q29 | 5 |\n| Q30 | 5 |\n| Q31 | 2 |\n| Q32 | 4 |\n| Q33 | 122.40 |\n| Q34 | 4.00 |\n| Q35 | 2.20 |\n| Q36 | 48.79 |\n| Q37 | 3.14 |\n| Q38 | 24.08 |\n| Q39 | 217.60 |\n| Q40 | (a) |\n| Q41 | (b) |\n| Q42 | (c) |\n| Q43 | (d) |\n| Q44 | (a) |\n| Q45 | (a) |\n| Q46 | A-q, B-r, C-s, D-p |\n| Q47 | A-p, B-q, C-r, D-s |\n| Q48 | A-q, B-r, C-t, D-s |\n| Q49 | A-p, B-q, C-r, D-s |\n| Q50 | 23 |\n\n## Worked Solutions\n\nS1. Standard values (kJ/mol) show Na = 496 (lowest, single loosely held 3s electron), Mg = 738 (filled 3s2 subshell adds stability), Al = 578 (dip, since the 3p electron removed is higher in energy and better shielded than a 3s electron), and Si = 786 (rises again as Zeff increases with an additional proton). This matches only option (a).\n\nS2. The Be/B reversal is due to a completely filled $2s^2$ subshell in beryllium, whereas the N/O reversal is due to a half-filled $2p^3$ subshell in nitrogen. Since the question specifically asks for the half-filled-subshell case, the answer is N > O, option (b).\n\nS3. Nitrogen's three 2p electrons are unpaired and mutually stabilised by exchange energy in a half-filled subshell; oxygen's fourth 2p electron must pair up, introducing extra electron-electron repulsion that makes it easier to remove despite oxygen's higher nuclear charge. This is option (b).\n\nS4. Aluminium has three valence electrons ($3s^2 3p^1$). IE1, IE2 and IE3 remove these three valence electrons in turn, while IE4 must break into the completely filled, neon-like $2p^6$ core, producing by far the largest jump between IE3 and IE4, option (c).\n\nS5. The huge jump occurs between IE3 (2.75 MJ/mol) and IE4 (11.6 MJ/mol), indicating exactly three valence electrons were removed before hitting the core; three valence electrons corresponds to group 13, option (a).\n\nS6. Helium has the smallest atomic radius of any element combined with a full, tightly bound $1s^2$ shell and no shielding complications, giving it the highest first ionization enthalpy (2372 kJ/mol) in the entire periodic table, option (a).\n\nS7. Across Li, Be, B and C there is no reversal yet (that appears later, between N and O); nuclear charge and hence Zeff on the 2s/2p valence electron increases steadily from Li to C, so carbon, having the highest nuclear charge among these four, experiences the greatest Zeff, option (d).\n\nS8. Although nuclear charge increases down a group, each new period adds an entire new principal shell, and the resulting increase in both radius and shielding by inner electrons outweighs the added protons, net-lowering the pull on the outermost electron; hence option (a).\n\nS9. In copper, removing the single $4s^1$ electron leaves a fully filled, unusually stable $3d^{10}$ configuration, which lowers the energy of the resulting Cu+ ion and effectively reduces the energy needed to ionize the neutral atom compared to the trend expected from nickel, option (a).\n\nS10. Sodium has only one valence electron (3s1); removing a second electron means breaking into the filled neon core, producing the largest IE2/IE1 ratio among these four elements, since Mg, Al and Si all still have valence electrons available for their second ionization. The answer is (a).\n\nS11. Ionization enthalpy of halogens follows the normal periodic trend of decreasing down a group as atomic radius increases; with the given values, F (1681) > Cl (1251) > Br (1140) > I (1008), option (a). This is distinct from electron gain enthalpy, where Cl is more exothermic than F.\n\nS12. Ionization enthalpy decreases steadily down group 2 as atomic radius increases and shielding by additional inner shells grows, giving Be > Mg > Ca > Sr > Ba, option (a).\n\nS13. Be > B and N > O are the two classical reversals caused by filled and half-filled subshell stability respectively; Mg > Al is the period-3 analogue of Be > B (filled $3s^2$ versus $3p^1$). Na > Mg is not anomalous \u2014 it simply reflects the normal periodic increase in Zeff, so (d) is false; the correct set is (a), (b), (c).\n\nS14. IE always increases with each successive removal for any element (a); the jump from IE3 to IE4 involves breaking into the neon core and is proportionally far larger than the jump between the first two valence electrons (b); IE1 does remove the single $3p^1$ electron (c); IE4 removes a $2p$ electron from the core, not a $3s$ electron, since $3s$ and $3p$ are already exhausted by then, so (d) is false.\n\nS15. Higher Zeff raises IE (a, true); larger atomic radius lowers IE, not raises it, so (b) is false; filled/half-filled subshell stability raises IE relative to the naive trend (c, true); increased inner-shell shielding lowers Zeff and hence lowers IE (d, true). Correct: (a), (c), (d).\n\nS16. Removing both 3s electrons of Mg to reach Mg2+ leaves the neon-like core, so IE3 (breaking that core) is far larger than IE2 (a, true); successive IEs always increase (b, true); Mg2+, having lost both 3s electrons, indeed has the same configuration as Ne (c, true); Mg2+ is smaller than Na+ since it has one more proton pulling on the same ten electrons, so (d) is false.\n\nS17. IE1 generally rises left to right across period 3 (a, true); there is a dip from Mg (738) to Al (578) due to filled 3s2 versus 3p1 (b, true); there is a dip from P (1012) to S (1000) due to half-filled $3p^3$ versus paired $3p^4$ (c, true); Ar, being a noble gas, has the highest IE1 in the period, not lower than Cl, so (d) is false.\n\nS18. Slater's rules do give a generally increasing Zeff across a period (a, true), and the same-group shielding constant is indeed 0.35 (0.30 for 1s) (c, true). However, Slater's rules treat s and p electrons of the same shell as one group but treat d and f electrons of that same shell as separate groups, so (b) is false; and electrons one shell below (n-1) contribute 0.85, not 1.00, for an s or p electron being shielded (only n-2 and lower contribute 1.00), so (d) is false. Correct: (a), (c).\n\nS19. Phosphorus has five valence electrons ($3s^2 3p^3$); the sixth ionization would require breaking into the filled $2p^6$ neon-like core, so the largest relative jump occurs between IE5 and IE6, option (d).\n\nS20. The jump between IE2 (1.76 MJ/mol) and IE3 (14.8 MJ/mol) is enormous, showing that only two valence electrons were available before the core was reached; two valence electrons corresponds to group 2, option (b).\n\nS21. The only statement guaranteed to hold for every element without exception is that each successive ionization enthalpy exceeds the previous one; the exact ratio and the location of the largest jump both vary depending on the number of valence electrons, so option (b) is correct.\n\nS22. Beryllium's completely filled $2s^2$ subshell provides the extra stability responsible for Be > B; nitrogen's reversal, by contrast, involves a half-filled subshell, so the filled-subshell case is (a) Be, B.\n\nS23. Oxygen's fourth 2p electron must occupy an orbital already holding one electron, and the resulting electron-electron (Coulombic) repulsion between the paired electrons destabilises that electron, lowering the energy needed to remove it relative to nitrogen's fully unpaired, half-filled arrangement. This is option (b).\n\nS24. In period 3, phosphorus ($3p^3$, half-filled) shows a higher IE1 than sulfur ($3p^4$, paired), directly analogous to the N/O reversal in period 2, giving option (c).\n\nS25. The ratio IE2/IE1 = 1145/590 \u2248 1.94 is modest, but IE3/IE2 = 4912/1145 \u2248 4.29 is a large jump, indicating that only two valence electrons were removed before this jump; hence the element has 2 valence electrons.\n\nS26. Comparing each element only to its immediate predecessor: Be(899) > Li(520) is an increase; B(801) < Be(899) is a decrease; C(1086) > B(801) is an increase; N(1402) > C(1086) is an increase; O(1314) < N(1402) is a decrease. There are 3 increases in total.\n\nS27. Statements I, II, IV and VI are all correct standard facts (noble gases peak IE1 in their period; IE decreases down a group; Cr's stable half-filled 3d5 configuration lowers its IE1 relative to a naive trend; Mg > Al is a genuine anomaly). Statement III is false since IE always increases with each successive removal, never decreases. Statement V is false since Ne, being a noble gas, has a higher IE1 than F, not lower. The count of correct statements is 4.\n\nS28. Checking each value against the 1000 kJ/mol threshold: N (1402), O (1314), F (1681) and Ne (2081) all exceed it, while Na (496), Mg (738) and Al (578) do not. The count is 4.\n\nS29. Element X, with configuration $[Ne]3s^2 3p^3$, has 5 valence electrons; the large jump therefore occurs after the 5th electron is removed, that is, between IE5 and IE6, so n = 5.\n\nS30. For the valence electron of P (3p, group 15): same-group (3s,3p) shielding = 4 \u00d7 0.35 = 1.40; n-1 shell (2s,2p, 8 electrons) = 8 \u00d7 0.85 = 6.80; n-2 shell (1s, 2 electrons) = 2 \u00d7 1.00 = 2.00. Total shielding = 10.20, giving Zeff = 15 \u2212 10.20 = 4.80, which rounds to 5.\n\nS31. Comparing each element's IE1 to the one before it in the period: Mg(738) > Na(496) is not a dip; Al(578) < Mg(738) is a dip; Si(786) > Al(578) is not; P(1012) > Si(786) is not; S(1000) < P(1012) is a dip; Cl(1251) > S(1000) is not; Ar(1521) > Cl(1251) is not. There are 2 dips (at Al and at S).\n\nS32. Be > B (899 > 801), N > O (1402 > 1314), Mg > Al (738 > 578) and P > S (1012 > 1000) are all genuine anomalies where the first element's IE1 exceeds the second despite the second having a higher atomic number. Na versus Mg is not anomalous, since Na(496) < Mg(738) simply follows the normal increasing trend. The count is 4.\n\nS33. IE = 13.6 \u00d7 Z\u00b2/n\u00b2 = 13.6 \u00d7 9/1 = 122.4 eV, which is 122.40 to two decimal places.\n\nS34. IE(He+)/IE(H) = (13.6 \u00d7 4/1)/(13.6 \u00d7 1/1) = 4/1 = 4.00.\n\nS35. For the 3s electron of Na: same-group contribution = 0 (no other electrons in the 3s,3p group); n-1 shell (2s,2p, 8 electrons) = 8 \u00d7 0.85 = 6.80; n-2 shell (1s, 2 electrons) = 2 \u00d7 1.00 = 2.00. Total shielding = 8.80, giving Zeff = 11 \u2212 8.80 = 2.20.\n\nS36. Percentage increase = (738 \u2212 496)/496 \u00d7 100 = 242/496 \u00d7 100 = 48.7903%, which rounds to 48.79.\n\nS37. IE2/IE1 = 1817/578 = 3.1436, which rounds to 3.14.\n\nS38. Energy per ion = 1450 \u00d7 1000 J/mol \u00f7 6.022 \u00d7 10^23 = 1,450,000/6.022\u00d710^23 = 2.4078 \u00d7 10^-18 J = 24.08 \u00d7 10^-19 J, so the answer is 24.08.\n\nS39. Be3+ is a one-electron (hydrogen-like) species with Z = 4; energy required = 13.6 \u00d7 4\u00b2/1\u00b2 = 13.6 \u00d7 16 = 217.6 eV, which is 217.60 to two decimal places.\n\nS40. Removing Na+'s second electron requires breaking into the fully filled, neon-like inner shell, an inherently much harder process than removing the single loosely bound valence 3s electron; the reason correctly and directly explains the assertion, giving option (a).\n\nS41. Mg does have a higher IE1 than Al (a genuine same-period anomaly caused by the extra stability of Mg's filled $3s^2$ subshell versus Al's higher-energy, better-shielded $3p^1$ electron), so A is true. The reason given describes a genuine but unrelated principle (the down-a-group trend), which does not explain a same-period comparison, so both are true but R does not explain A, giving option (b).\n\nS42. Fluorine genuinely has the highest IE1 among the halogens (A is true), but the reason is false: chlorine, not fluorine, has the more negative (higher-magnitude) electron gain enthalpy of the two, and in any case electron gain enthalpy is an unrelated property that does not explain ionization enthalpy. This gives option (c).\n\nS43. In reality beryllium (899 kJ/mol) has a HIGHER IE1 than boron (801 kJ/mol), not a lower one, so the assertion, which claims boron is higher, is false. The reason correctly describes why boron's 2p electron is easier to remove than beryllium's 2s2 electron \u2014 it is a true statement, just attached to a false assertion (with the elements reversed). This gives option (d).\n\nS44. All three ions are isoelectronic with ten electrons, and the increasing nuclear charge from Na to Mg to Al raises the effective nuclear charge per electron, directly and correctly explaining the observed decreasing radius order; option (a).\n\nS45. Aluminium's fourth ionization does require breaking into the filled $2p^6$ inner core immediately after all three valence electrons are gone, making IE4 far larger than IE3; both statements are true, and the reason directly and correctly explains the assertion, giving option (a).\n\nS46. Standard period-3 first ionization enthalpies rise overall with two dips: Na = 496 (q), Mg = 738 (r), Al = 578 (s), Si = 786 (p). Hence A-q, B-r, C-s, D-p.\n\nS47. A (Be > B) matches the filled-subshell reason (p); B (N > O, focusing on nitrogen's own stability) matches the half-filled-subshell reason (q); C (Na's huge IE2/IE1 jump) matches the core-breaking reason (r); D (O's lower IE1, focusing on oxygen's own configuration) matches the pairing-repulsion reason (s). The lanthanide-contraction option (t) is an unrelated decoy.\n\nS48. A (group 1 IE1 trend) decreases due to the added electron being progressively farther and better shielded (q); B (period 2 IE1 trend) rises overall with the two classic reversals (r); C (3d-series IE1 trend) rises gradually but fluctuates due to variable (n-1)d shielding (t); D (group 18 IE1 trend) decreases steadily as atomic size grows down the group (s). Option (p) is an unused decoy since period 2's trend is not reversal-free.\n\nS49. Standard first ionization enthalpies: Li = 520 (p), Na = 496 (q), K = 419 (r), Cs = 376 (s). Hence A-p, B-q, C-r, D-s; option (t), 738 kJ/mol, belongs to magnesium and is an unrelated decoy.\n\nS50. Locating the huge jump in each series: X1 jumps between the 5th and 6th values (1402\u21922856\u21924578\u21927475\u21929445\u219253266), giving 5 valence electrons (this is nitrogen's real data). X2 jumps between the 2nd and 3rd values (738\u21921450\u21927732\u219210540), giving 2 valence electrons (magnesium). X3 jumps between the 3rd and 4th values (578\u21921816\u21922744\u219211577), giving 3 valence electrons (aluminium). X4 jumps between the 6th and 7th values (1000\u21922251\u21923361\u21924564\u21927013\u21928495\u219227106), giving 6 valence electrons (sulfur). X5 jumps between the 7th and 8th values (1251\u21922298\u21923822\u21925158\u21926540\u21929362\u219211018\u219238600), giving 7 valence electrons (chlorine). The sum is 5 + 2 + 3 + 6 + 7 = 23.\n";
const RAW_MD_ELECTRONGAIN = "**Classification of Elements and Periodicity in Properties \u2014 Electron Gain Enthalpy Practice Set (50 Original Questions)**\n\nThis set covers sign conventions, the fluorine anomaly, second electron gain enthalpy, and group/period trends including the group 2, group 15, and group 18 exceptions. All numerical data used are standard reference values presented explicitly so every calculation is self-contained.\n\n## Single Correct (SCQ)\n\nQ1. Which of the following correctly represents the order of magnitude (ignoring sign) of the first electron gain enthalpy of the halogens?\n\n(a) F > Cl > Br > I\n\n(b) Cl > F > Br > I\n\n(c) I > Br > Cl > F\n\n(d) Cl > Br > F > I\n\nQ2. Which of the following elements has a positive first electron gain enthalpy?\n\n(a) S\n\n(b) Cl\n\n(c) Mg\n\n(d) Br\n\nQ3. The approximate first electron gain enthalpies of carbon, nitrogen, and oxygen are $-122$, $\\approx 0$, and $-141$ kJ/mol respectively. The correct order of increasingly negative (more exothermic) $\\Delta_{eg}H$ is\n\n(a) N < C < O\n\n(b) O < C < N\n\n(c) C < N < O\n\n(d) N < O < C\n\nQ4. The second electron gain enthalpy of an element, corresponding to $X^-(g) + e^- \\rightarrow X^{2-}(g)$, is\n\n(a) always negative\n\n(b) always positive\n\n(c) negative only for halogens\n\n(d) zero for all elements\n\nQ5. Which period 3 element shows an anomalously less negative first electron gain enthalpy compared to both of its neighbours (Si and S), because of a stable half-filled $3p^3$ configuration?\n\n(a) Al\n\n(b) P\n\n(c) Cl\n\n(d) Mg\n\nQ6. Given first electron gain enthalpy values (kJ/mol): F $= -328$, Cl $= -349$, Br $= -325$, I $= -295$, the element with the least negative first electron gain enthalpy is\n\n(a) F\n\n(b) Cl\n\n(c) Br\n\n(d) I\n\nQ7. The first electron gain enthalpy of sulfur ($-200$ kJ/mol) is more negative than that of oxygen ($-141$ kJ/mol) mainly because\n\n(a) sulfur has a higher electronegativity than oxygen\n\n(b) the larger $3p$ subshell of sulfur experiences less inter-electronic repulsion than the compact $2p$ subshell of oxygen\n\n(c) sulfur has a smaller atomic radius than oxygen\n\n(d) oxygen has a higher nuclear charge than sulfur\n\nQ8. An element with valence configuration $ns^2np^6$ is expected to have a first electron gain enthalpy that is\n\n(a) large and negative\n\n(b) small and negative\n\n(c) positive\n\n(d) exactly zero for every such element without exception\n\nQ9. Which statement correctly describes electron gain enthalpy?\n\n(a) It is the enthalpy change when an electron is removed from a gaseous atom\n\n(b) It is always released as heat for every known element\n\n(c) It is the enthalpy change when an electron is added to an isolated gaseous atom to form an anion\n\n(d) It has the same value as the ionisation enthalpy of the resulting anion\n\nQ10. Although chlorine has a more negative first electron gain enthalpy than fluorine, fluorine is still the strongest oxidising agent among the halogens. This is best explained by\n\n(a) fluorine's greater electronegativity alone\n\n(b) the low F\u2013F bond dissociation enthalpy and the high hydration/lattice enthalpy associated with the small F$^-$ ion, which together make the overall process more favourable despite the smaller $\\Delta_{eg}H$ release\n\n(c) fluorine's larger atomic radius\n\n(d) fluorine having a positive electron gain enthalpy\n\nQ11. The first electron gain enthalpies of the alkali metals (kJ/mol) are approximately Li $= -60$, Na $= -53$, K $= -48$, Rb $= -46$. The correct order of decreasing magnitude (most negative to least negative) is\n\n(a) Li > Na > K > Rb\n\n(b) Rb > K > Na > Li\n\n(c) Na > Li > K > Rb\n\n(d) K > Na > Li > Rb\n\nQ12. Which of the following does NOT directly influence the magnitude of an atom's first electron gain enthalpy?\n\n(a) Atomic size\n\n(b) Effective nuclear charge\n\n(c) Stability of the resulting anion's electronic configuration\n\n(d) The melting point of the element in its standard state\n\n## Multiple Correct (MCQ)\n\n(One or more options may be correct.)\n\nQ13. Which of the following species have a positive first electron gain enthalpy?\n\n(a) He\n\n(b) Mg\n\n(c) Ar\n\n(d) Cl\n\nQ14. Which of the following statements about the second electron gain enthalpy of an element are correct?\n\n(a) It is always positive (endothermic)\n\n(b) The overall formation of a dianion such as $O^{2-}(g)$ from $O(g)$ is net endothermic when both successive steps are added together\n\n(c) It is positive because the incoming electron is repelled by the already negatively charged ion\n\n(d) It becomes more negative on descending a group\n\nQ15. Which of the following correctly explain why chlorine has a more negative first electron gain enthalpy than fluorine?\n\n(a) The small size of the fluorine atom causes greater electron-electron repulsion in its compact $2p$ subshell, partially offsetting its stronger nuclear attraction\n\n(b) Chlorine's larger $3p$ subshell can accommodate the incoming electron with comparatively less repulsion\n\n(c) Fluorine's smaller size means the nuclear attraction effect dominates over repulsion, making its $\\Delta_{eg}H$ the most negative of all elements\n\n(d) Chlorine has a higher effective nuclear charge than fluorine\n\nQ16. For oxygen and chlorine, which of the following processes are exothermic?\n\n(a) $O(g) + e^- \\rightarrow O^-(g)$\n\n(b) $O^-(g) + e^- \\rightarrow O^{2-}(g)$\n\n(c) $Cl(g) + e^- \\rightarrow Cl^-(g)$\n\n(d) $Cl^-(g) + e^- \\rightarrow Cl^{2-}(g)$\n\nQ17. Which of the following statements about the group 15 elements nitrogen and phosphorus are correct?\n\n(a) Nitrogen's first electron gain enthalpy is less negative than expected because of its stable half-filled $2p^3$ configuration\n\n(b) Phosphorus has a less negative first electron gain enthalpy than both its group 14 (Si) and group 16 (S) neighbours in period 3\n\n(c) The first electron gain enthalpy of phosphorus is more negative than that of nitrogen\n\n(d) Both nitrogen and phosphorus have a positive first electron gain enthalpy\n\nQ18. Which of the following factors tend to make the first electron gain enthalpy of an atom more negative?\n\n(a) An increase in effective nuclear charge\n\n(b) A decrease in atomic radius\n\n(c) An increase in the number of electrons already present in a stable, symmetrical configuration such as a filled subshell\n\n(d) An increase in shielding by inner-shell electrons\n\n## Paragraph / Comprehension\n\n### Paragraph 1\n\nElectron gain enthalpy ($\\Delta_{eg}H$) measures the enthalpy change when an electron is added to an isolated gaseous atom to form a monovalent anion. Among the halogens, chlorine has the most negative first electron gain enthalpy of the group (about $-349$ kJ/mol), even though fluorine has a higher electronegativity and a greater effective nuclear charge at its much smaller size. Fluorine's first electron gain enthalpy (about $-328$ kJ/mol) is less negative than chlorine's, an outcome often called the fluorine anomaly. Bromine (about $-325$ kJ/mol) and iodine (about $-295$ kJ/mol) show progressively less negative values as atomic size increases and the nucleus attracts the incoming electron more weakly.\n\nQ19. Which halogen releases the greatest amount of energy on gaining one electron?\n\n(a) F\n\n(b) Cl\n\n(c) Br\n\n(d) I\n\nQ20. The less negative $\\Delta_{eg}H$ of fluorine compared to chlorine is best attributed to\n\n(a) lower electronegativity of fluorine\n\n(b) the smaller, compact $2p$ subshell of fluorine causing greater inter-electronic repulsion for the incoming electron\n\n(c) fluorine having a lower effective nuclear charge than chlorine\n\n(d) fluorine's inability to form a stable anion\n\nQ21. Despite having a less negative $\\Delta_{eg}H$ than chlorine, fluorine remains the strongest oxidising halogen mainly because of its\n\n(a) higher ionisation enthalpy\n\n(b) very low F\u2013F bond dissociation enthalpy together with the very high hydration enthalpy of F$^-$, which together make the overall reduction process more favourable\n\n(c) larger atomic radius\n\n(d) higher melting point\n\n### Paragraph 2\n\nElements with a completely filled or half-filled stable electronic configuration show unusually small, or even positive, electron gain enthalpies, because the incoming electron cannot be accommodated within the same stable subshell. Alkaline earth metals such as magnesium and noble gases such as argon have positive first electron gain enthalpies since the added electron must enter a higher-energy subshell. Similarly, within group 15, nitrogen's half-filled $2p^3$ configuration makes its $\\Delta_{eg}H$ close to zero, noticeably less negative than that of its period 2 neighbours carbon and oxygen.\n\nQ22. Magnesium has a positive first electron gain enthalpy chiefly because\n\n(a) it is a metal and metals never accept electrons\n\n(b) the incoming electron must enter the $3p$ subshell after the stable filled $3s^2$ configuration, which is energetically unfavourable\n\n(c) magnesium has a very large atomic radius\n\n(d) magnesium has a low ionisation enthalpy\n\nQ23. The correct order of increasingly negative (more exothermic) first electron gain enthalpy among O, S, Se, and Te is\n\n(a) O > S > Se > Te\n\n(b) S > Se > Te > O\n\n(c) Te > Se > S > O\n\n(d) O > Te > Se > S\n\nQ24. Nitrogen's first electron gain enthalpy is close to zero mainly due to\n\n(a) nitrogen behaving like a noble gas\n\n(b) the extra stability of the half-filled $2p^3$ configuration, which resists accepting an additional electron\n\n(c) nitrogen having the smallest atomic radius in period 2\n\n(d) nitrogen's very high electronegativity\n\n## Integer Type\n\nQ25. The first electron gain enthalpies of chlorine and iodine are $-349$ kJ/mol and $-295$ kJ/mol respectively. What is the magnitude of the difference between them, in kJ/mol?\n\nQ26. Among He, Mg, N (treat its first electron gain enthalpy as approximately zero, not positive), F, Ne, Ca, Cl, and Ar, how many species have a positive first electron gain enthalpy?\n\nQ27. Given $\\Delta_{eg}H_1(O) = -141$ kJ/mol and $\\Delta_{eg}H_2(O) = +780$ kJ/mol for the two successive steps $O(g)+e^-\\rightarrow O^-(g)$ and $O^-(g)+e^-\\rightarrow O^{2-}(g)$, what is the magnitude of the net enthalpy change, in kJ/mol, for $O(g)+2e^-\\rightarrow O^{2-}(g)$?\n\nQ28. Using the approximate first electron gain enthalpy values (kJ/mol) Na $=-53$, Mg $=+230$, Al $=-43$, Si $=-134$, P $=-72$, S $=-200$, Cl $=-349$, Ar $=+35$, how many period 3 elements (Na to Ar) have a negative first electron gain enthalpy?\n\nQ29. Using the approximate values (kJ/mol) N $=0$, O $=-141$, P $=-72$, S $=-200$, As $=-78$, Se $=-195$, Sb $=-103$, Te $=-190$, in how many of the four group 15/16 pairs (N,O), (P,S), (As,Se), (Sb,Te) does the group 15 element show a less negative first electron gain enthalpy than its group 16 neighbour in the same period?\n\nQ30. Given $\\Delta_{eg}H_1(S) = -200$ kJ/mol and $\\Delta_{eg}H_2(S) = +590$ kJ/mol, what is the magnitude of the net enthalpy change, in kJ/mol (nearest integer), for $S(g)+2e^-\\rightarrow S^{2-}(g)$?\n\nQ31. Four hypothetical elements have first electron gain enthalpies (kJ/mol): A $=-60$, B $=+120$, C $=-348$, D $=-3$. How many of these four elements undergo an exothermic (energy-releasing) electron gain?\n\nQ32. The magnitude of the first electron gain enthalpy of iodine is 295 kJ/mol. Tennessine (Ts, Z $=117$), the heaviest known halogen, is estimated to have a first electron gain enthalpy about 30 kJ/mol less negative than iodine's, due to relativistic effects and poor shielding by filled f and d subshells. Estimate the magnitude of the first electron gain enthalpy of Ts, in kJ/mol.\n\n## Numerical Response\n\nQ33. Using the Mulliken definition $\\chi_M = (IE + EA)/2$ (in eV), calculate the Mulliken electronegativity of chlorine given $IE_1(Cl) = 12.97$ eV and $EA(Cl) = 3.61$ eV. (Answer correct to two decimal places, in eV.)\n\nQ34. Using $\\chi_M = (IE + EA)/2$ (in eV), calculate the Mulliken electronegativity of fluorine given $IE_1(F) = 17.42$ eV and $EA(F) = 3.40$ eV. (Answer correct to two decimal places, in eV.)\n\nQ35. The first electron gain enthalpy of oxygen is $-141$ kJ/mol. Using $1$ eV $= 96.485$ kJ/mol, calculate the magnitude of this value in eV/atom. (Answer correct to two decimal places.)\n\nQ36. The electron affinities of chlorine and bromine are 3.61 eV and 3.37 eV respectively. Calculate the percentage by which chlorine's electron affinity exceeds bromine's, relative to chlorine's value. (Answer correct to two decimal places.)\n\nQ37. The Mulliken electronegativities of fluorine and chlorine, calculated from $\\chi_M=(IE+EA)/2$, are 10.41 eV and 8.29 eV respectively. Calculate the difference $\\chi_M(F) - \\chi_M(Cl)$. (Answer correct to two decimal places, in eV.)\n\nQ38. In the Born-Haber cycle for NaCl(s): $\\Delta_{sub}H(Na) = +108$ kJ/mol, $IE_1(Na) = +496$ kJ/mol, half the Cl\u2013Cl bond dissociation enthalpy $= +121$ kJ/mol, the lattice enthalpy of formation ($Na^+(g)+Cl^-(g)\\rightarrow NaCl(s)$) $= -788$ kJ/mol, and $\\Delta_fH(NaCl,s) = -411$ kJ/mol. Calculate the first electron gain enthalpy of chlorine (in kJ/mol) implied by this cycle. (Answer correct to two decimal places.)\n\nQ39. Using $\\chi_M = (IE+EA)/2$ and $\\chi_P \\approx \\chi_M/2.8$ (all energies in eV), calculate the approximate Pauling electronegativity of iodine given $IE_1(I) = 10.45$ eV and $EA(I) = 3.06$ eV. (Answer correct to two decimal places.)\n\n## Assertion\u2013Reason (A/R)\n\nEach question below has an Assertion (A) and a Reason (R). Choose the correct option using this scheme: (a) Both A and R are true and R is the correct explanation of A. (b) Both A and R are true but R is not the correct explanation of A. (c) A is true but R is false. (d) A is false but R is true.\n\nQ40. Assertion (A): The first electron gain enthalpy of chlorine is more negative than that of fluorine.\n\nReason (R): The added electron in fluorine experiences greater electron-electron repulsion in its small, compact $2p$ subshell than the added electron in chlorine's larger $3p$ subshell, which partially offsets fluorine's stronger nuclear attraction.\n\nQ41. Assertion (A): Oxygen's first electron gain enthalpy is less negative than that of sulfur.\n\nReason (R): Oxygen is more electronegative than sulfur.\n\nQ42. Assertion (A): The second electron gain enthalpy of oxygen, for $O^-(g)+e^-\\rightarrow O^{2-}(g)$, is positive.\n\nReason (R): This is because oxygen has a very low electronegativity and does not attract additional electrons.\n\nQ43. Assertion (A): The magnitude of first electron gain enthalpy decreases monotonically on descending every group of the periodic table, without any exception.\n\nReason (R): On descending a group, atomic size generally increases and the effective nuclear charge experienced by an incoming electron generally decreases.\n\nQ44. Assertion (A): The electron affinity of chlorine (3.61 eV) is higher than that of fluorine (3.40 eV).\n\nReason (R): Chlorine has a larger atomic radius than fluorine.\n\nQ45. Assertion (A): The first electron gain enthalpy of nitrogen is close to zero.\n\nReason (R): Nitrogen is the most electronegative element in period 2.\n\n## Matrix Match\n\nEach entry in List-I may match one or more entries in List-II unless stated otherwise.\n\nQ46. List-I\n\n| Item | Species |\n|---|---|\n| A | Fluorine |\n| B | Chlorine |\n| C | Magnesium |\n| D | Argon |\n\nList-II\n\n| Item | Description |\n|---|---|\n| p | Most negative first electron gain enthalpy among the halogens |\n| q | Less negative first electron gain enthalpy than chlorine, because of small size and high electron-electron repulsion |\n| r | Positive first electron gain enthalpy due to a stable filled $ns^2$ configuration |\n| s | Positive first electron gain enthalpy due to a stable filled $ns^2np^6$ configuration |\n\nQ47. List-I\n\n| Item | Case |\n|---|---|\n| A | Oxygen (top of group 16) |\n| B | Nitrogen (group 15, period 2) |\n| C | Group 2 elements |\n| D | Group 18 elements |\n\nList-II\n\n| Item | Description |\n|---|---|\n| p | First EGE close to zero or slightly positive, owing to a stable half-filled $np^3$ configuration |\n| q | First EGE less negative than the element directly below it in the same group, owing to small size and high electron density |\n| r | Positive first EGE due to a stable filled $ns^2$ configuration |\n| s | Positive first EGE, generally the largest positive value in the period, due to a stable filled $ns^2np^6$ configuration |\n\nQ48. List-I (each item may match more than one entry in List-II)\n\n| Item | Process |\n|---|---|\n| A | $O(g)+e^-\\rightarrow O^-(g)$ |\n| B | $O^-(g)+e^-\\rightarrow O^{2-}(g)$ |\n| C | $Cl(g)+e^-\\rightarrow Cl^-(g)$ |\n| D | $Cl^-(g)+e^-\\rightarrow Cl^{2-}(g)$ |\n\nList-II\n\n| Item | Description |\n|---|---|\n| p | Exothermic, $\\Delta H \\approx -141$ kJ/mol |\n| q | Exothermic, $\\Delta H \\approx -349$ kJ/mol |\n| r | Endothermic, $\\Delta H \\approx +780$ kJ/mol |\n| s | Endothermic, $\\Delta H \\approx +590$ kJ/mol |\n| t | Represents a second electron gain step, which is always positive |\n\nQ49. List-I\n\n| Item | Concept |\n|---|---|\n| A | Increasingly negative EGE across a period, left to right |\n| B | Fluorine's anomalously less negative EGE compared to chlorine |\n| C | Positive EGE of group 2 elements |\n| D | Positive EGE of group 18 elements |\n\nList-II\n\n| Item | Explanation |\n|---|---|\n| p | Extra stability of a filled $ns^2np^6$ configuration |\n| q | Extra stability of a filled $ns^2$ configuration |\n| r | General increase in effective nuclear charge across a period |\n| s | Strong electron-electron repulsion in the compact $2p$ subshell of the small fluorine atom |\n\n## Innovative Pattern\n\nQ50. Four statements about electron gain enthalpy are given below. For each statement, write 1 if it is True and 0 if it is False, reading the results in the order S1, S2, S3, S4 to form a 4-digit binary number. Convert this binary number to its decimal equivalent; that decimal number is your answer.\n\nS1: The first electron gain enthalpy of fluorine is more negative than that of chlorine.\n\nS2: The second electron gain enthalpy of any element is always positive.\n\nS3: Group 2 elements have a negative first electron gain enthalpy mainly because of their large atomic size.\n\nS4: First electron gain enthalpy generally becomes less negative on descending a group because atomic size increases, though notable exceptions exist (for example, within group 16).\n\n## Answer Key\n\n| Question | Answer |\n|---|---|\n| Q1 | (b) |\n| Q2 | (c) |\n| Q3 | (a) |\n| Q4 | (b) |\n| Q5 | (b) |\n| Q6 | (d) |\n| Q7 | (b) |\n| Q8 | (c) |\n| Q9 | (c) |\n| Q10 | (b) |\n| Q11 | (a) |\n| Q12 | (d) |\n| Q13 | (a), (b), (c) |\n| Q14 | (a), (b), (c) |\n| Q15 | (a), (b) |\n| Q16 | (a), (c) |\n| Q17 | (a), (b), (c) |\n| Q18 | (a), (b) |\n| Q19 | (b) |\n| Q20 | (b) |\n| Q21 | (b) |\n| Q22 | (b) |\n| Q23 | (b) |\n| Q24 | (b) |\n| Q25 | 54 |\n| Q26 | 5 |\n| Q27 | 639 |\n| Q28 | 6 |\n| Q29 | 4 |\n| Q30 | 390 |\n| Q31 | 3 |\n| Q32 | 265 |\n| Q33 | 8.29 |\n| Q34 | 10.41 |\n| Q35 | 1.46 |\n| Q36 | 6.65 |\n| Q37 | 2.12 |\n| Q38 | -348.00 |\n| Q39 | 2.41 |\n| Q40 | (a) |\n| Q41 | (b) |\n| Q42 | (c) |\n| Q43 | (d) |\n| Q44 | (b) |\n| Q45 | (c) |\n| Q46 | A-q, B-p, C-r, D-s |\n| Q47 | A-q, B-p, C-r, D-s |\n| Q48 | A-p, B-r&t, C-q, D-s&t |\n| Q49 | A-r, B-s, C-q, D-p |\n| Q50 | 5 |\n\n## Worked Solutions\n\nS1. Although fluorine is more electronegative and smaller than chlorine, its added electron enters a very compact $2p$ subshell and suffers strong inter-electronic repulsion, making $\\Delta_{eg}H(F)$ less negative than $\\Delta_{eg}H(Cl)$. Bromine and iodine are progressively less negative as size increases. The correct order is Cl > F > Br > I, option (b).\n\nS2. Magnesium has a filled $3s^2$ configuration, so the incoming electron must occupy the higher-energy $3p$ subshell, making the process endothermic. S, Cl, and Br all have negative first EGE. Answer: (c).\n\nS3. Nitrogen's half-filled $2p^3$ configuration makes its EGE nearly zero, which is less negative than carbon's, which in turn is less negative than oxygen's. So N < C < O, option (a).\n\nS4. Once an atom becomes an anion, adding a further electron requires overcoming repulsion from the existing negative charge, so the second electron gain enthalpy is always positive (endothermic) for every element. Answer: (b).\n\nS5. Phosphorus's half-filled $3p^3$ configuration makes its first EGE less negative than both silicon and sulfur, its period 3 neighbours. Answer: (b).\n\nS6. Among the given values, iodine's $-295$ kJ/mol has the smallest magnitude, making it the least negative. Answer: (d).\n\nS7. Sulfur's larger $3p$ subshell allows the incoming electron to be accommodated with less electron-electron repulsion than in oxygen's compact $2p$ subshell, so sulfur's EGE is more negative despite oxygen's smaller size and comparable nuclear charge. Answer: (b).\n\nS8. A filled $ns^2np^6$ configuration is exceptionally stable; the incoming electron must start a new shell, making the process endothermic (positive EGE). Answer: (c).\n\nS9. Electron gain enthalpy is defined as the enthalpy change on adding an electron to a gaseous atom to form an anion. Answer: (c).\n\nS10. Fluorine's high reactivity arises from the very low bond dissociation enthalpy of F2 and the very high hydration/lattice enthalpy of the small F$^-$ ion, both of which favour the overall thermodynamics despite its smaller $\\Delta_{eg}H$ magnitude. Answer: (b).\n\nS11. All alkali metals have negative EGE that becomes progressively less negative down the group as atomic size increases and nuclear attraction weakens, giving Li > Na > K > Rb in magnitude. Answer: (a).\n\nS12. Melting point is a bulk physical property unrelated to the atomic-level factors (size, nuclear charge, electronic configuration) that govern EGE. Answer: (d).\n\nS13. He and Ar are noble gases with filled $ns^2np^6$ shells, and Mg has a filled $3s^2$ configuration \u2014 all three require the incoming electron to enter a higher energy level, giving positive EGE. Cl has a very negative EGE. Answer: (a), (b), (c).\n\nS14. Adding an electron to an already negative ion is always endothermic (positive), so both individual second EGE values are positive and their sum with the first (negative) step is still net endothermic for oxygen; this positivity arises from repulsion between the anion and incoming electron. Answer: (a), (b), (c).\n\nS15. Fluorine's small compact $2p$ subshell causes strong repulsion that partly cancels its high nuclear attraction, while chlorine's larger $3p$ subshell has comparatively less repulsion; this \u2014 not a higher nuclear attraction dominating in F, and not simply \"higher Zeff for Cl\" \u2014 explains the anomaly. Answer: (a), (b).\n\nS16. Both $O\\rightarrow O^-$ and $Cl\\rightarrow Cl^-$ release energy (exothermic), while adding a second electron to either anion is endothermic due to repulsion. Answer: (a), (c).\n\nS17. Nitrogen's half-filled $2p^3$ gives it a near-zero EGE; phosphorus is less negative than silicon and sulfur for the same reason, yet phosphorus's EGE ($-72$) is still more negative than nitrogen's ($\\approx 0$). Neither element has a positive EGE. Answer: (a), (b), (c).\n\nS18. Higher effective nuclear charge and smaller radius both increase attraction for the incoming electron, making EGE more negative; a stable, symmetrical configuration and greater inner shielding both work against accepting an electron, making EGE less negative or positive. Answer: (a), (b).\n\nS19. Chlorine has the most negative first EGE ($-349$ kJ/mol) among the halogens, releasing the most energy. Answer: (b).\n\nS20. Fluorine's small, compact $2p$ subshell causes strong electron-electron repulsion for the incoming electron, offsetting its high nuclear attraction and making its EGE less negative than chlorine's. Answer: (b).\n\nS21. Fluorine's exceptionally low F\u2013F bond dissociation enthalpy and the very high hydration enthalpy of F$^-$ make its overall reactions strongly favourable, overriding its smaller EGE magnitude. Answer: (b).\n\nS22. Magnesium's stable filled $3s^2$ configuration forces the incoming electron into the higher-energy $3p$ subshell, making the process endothermic (positive EGE). Answer: (b).\n\nS23. Using the given approximate values, sulfur ($-200$) is most negative, followed by selenium ($-195$), tellurium ($-190$), and oxygen ($-141$) is least negative due to its small size and high electron density. Answer: (b).\n\nS24. Nitrogen's half-filled $2p^3$ configuration is unusually stable, so it resists accepting an additional electron, keeping its EGE close to zero. Answer: (b).\n\nS25. $|-349-(-295)| = |-54| = 54$ kJ/mol.\n\nS26. He, Mg, Ne, Ca, and Ar have positive first EGE (5 species); nitrogen is treated as approximately zero and F, Cl are negative.\n\nS27. Net $\\Delta H = -141+780 = 639$ kJ/mol (magnitude).\n\nS28. Negative EGE elements are Na, Al, Si, P, S, and Cl \u2014 six elements; Mg and Ar are positive.\n\nS29. Comparing magnitudes: $|0|<|141|$, $|72|<|200|$, $|78|<|195|$, $|103|<|190|$ \u2014 all four pairs show the group 15 element with a less negative value, so the count is 4.\n\nS30. Net $\\Delta H = -200+590 = 390$ kJ/mol (magnitude).\n\nS31. A ($-60$), C ($-348$), and D ($-3$) are negative (exothermic); B ($+120$) is positive. Count = 3.\n\nS32. $295-30 = 265$ kJ/mol.\n\nS33. $\\chi_M(Cl) = (12.97+3.61)/2 = 16.58/2 = 8.29$ eV.\n\nS34. $\\chi_M(F) = (17.42+3.40)/2 = 20.82/2 = 10.41$ eV.\n\nS35. $141/96.485 = 1.4614 \\approx 1.46$ eV.\n\nS36. $(3.61-3.37)/3.61 \\times 100 = 0.24/3.61\\times100 = 6.65\\%$.\n\nS37. $10.41-8.29 = 2.12$ eV.\n\nS38. From the cycle: $-411 = 108+496+121+\\Delta_{eg}H(Cl)+(-788)$, so $-411 = -63+\\Delta_{eg}H(Cl)$, giving $\\Delta_{eg}H(Cl) = -348.00$ kJ/mol.\n\nS39. $\\chi_M(I) = (10.45+3.06)/2 = 6.755$ eV; $\\chi_P = 6.755/2.8 = 2.41$.\n\nS40. Both statements are true, and the reason correctly explains why chlorine's EGE is more negative despite fluorine's smaller size \u2014 the repulsion in F's compact $2p$ subshell partly cancels its stronger attraction. Answer: (a).\n\nS41. Both A and R are factually true (O's EGE is less negative than S's, and O is indeed more electronegative than S), but higher electronegativity alone would naively predict a *more* negative EGE, not less \u2014 the real cause is small size and $2p$-subshell repulsion, so R does not correctly explain A. Answer: (b).\n\nS42. The second EGE of oxygen is indeed positive (A is true), but the reason given is false \u2014 oxygen actually has high electronegativity; the true cause of the positive second EGE is repulsion between the already negative ion and the incoming electron. Answer: (c).\n\nS43. The claim of a strictly monotonic decrease \"without exception\" is false (for instance sulfur's EGE is more negative than oxygen's, breaking simple top-to-bottom monotonicity within group 16), while the general reasoning about increasing size and decreasing effective nuclear charge down a group is a true statement on its own. Answer: (d).\n\nS44. Both facts are true (Cl's EA exceeds F's; Cl has the larger radius), but a larger radius alone would predict a *weaker* attraction and lower EA, so it does not correctly explain why Cl's EA is higher \u2014 the real reason is reduced electron-electron repulsion in Cl's larger $3p$ subshell. Answer: (b).\n\nS45. Nitrogen's EGE is indeed close to zero (A is true), but nitrogen is not the most electronegative element in period 2 \u2014 oxygen and fluorine are both more electronegative (R is false). Answer: (c).\n\nS46. Fluorine (A) is less negative than chlorine due to small-size repulsion (q); chlorine (B) has the most negative EGE among halogens (p); magnesium (C) is positive due to filled $ns^2$ (r); argon (D) is positive due to filled $ns^2np^6$ (s).\n\nS47. Oxygen (A) is less negative than sulfur below it (q); nitrogen (B) shows the half-filled anomaly (p); group 2 (C) is positive due to filled $ns^2$ (r); group 18 (D) is positive with the largest positive value due to filled $ns^2np^6$ (s).\n\nS48. First EGE of O is exothermic near $-141$ kJ/mol (A-p); second EGE of O is endothermic near $+780$ kJ/mol and represents a generic second-step positive process (B-r, t); first EGE of Cl is exothermic near $-349$ kJ/mol (C-q); second EGE of Cl is endothermic near $+590$ kJ/mol and is also a generic second-step positive process (D-s, t).\n\nS49. Increasing EGE negativity across a period follows increasing effective nuclear charge (A-r); fluorine's anomaly is due to $2p$ repulsion (B-s); group 2's positive EGE is due to filled $ns^2$ (C-q); group 18's positive EGE is due to filled $ns^2np^6$ (D-p).\n\nS50. S1 is false (Cl is more negative than F, so 0), S2 is true (1), S3 is false because group 2 elements have positive, not negative, EGE, and size is not the stated correct reason (0), S4 is true as a general statement with acknowledged exceptions (1). Reading S1\u2013S4 gives binary 0101, which equals decimal 5.\n";
const RAW_MD_ELECTRONEGATIVITY = "**Classification of Elements and Periodicity in Properties \u2014 Electronegativity Practice Set (50 Original Questions)**\n\nThis set covers the Pauling, Mulliken, and Allred-Rochow scales, the Hannay-Smith and Pauling exponential formulas for percent ionic character, the Schomaker-Stevenson bond-length correction, hybridisation and group-electronegativity effects, and Fajans' rules. All numerical data used are stated explicitly so every calculation is self-contained.\n\n## Single Correct (SCQ)\n\nQ1. Among the carbon atoms in $HC\\equiv CH$ (sp), $H_2C=CH_2$ (sp2), and $CH_4$ (sp3), which carbon is expected to be the most electronegative?\n\n(a) sp3 carbon in $CH_4$\n\n(b) sp2 carbon in $H_2C=CH_2$\n\n(c) sp carbon in $HC\\equiv CH$\n\n(d) All three have identical electronegativity\n\nQ2. The effective (group) electronegativity of the carbon atom is expected to be higher in\n\n(a) $CH_4$\n\n(b) $CHCl_3$\n\n(c) $CH_3CH_3$\n\n(d) $CH_3Li$\n\nQ3. Comparing the substituent groups $-CF_3$ and $-CH_3$, the group electronegativity order is\n\n(a) $-CH_3 > -CF_3$\n\n(b) $-CF_3 > -CH_3$\n\n(c) both are identical\n\n(d) cannot be compared\n\nQ4. The Allred-Rochow electronegativity scale is based on\n\n(a) the average of ionisation energy and electron affinity of an atom\n\n(b) the electrostatic force exerted by the effective nuclear charge on the bonding electron at the covalent radius\n\n(c) the arithmetic mean of bond dissociation energies of homonuclear diatomic molecules\n\n(d) the geometric mean of the ionic radii of a cation and an anion\n\nQ5. On the Mulliken scale, the electronegativity of an atom is defined as\n\n(a) the difference between its ionisation energy and electron affinity\n\n(b) the average of its ionisation energy and electron affinity\n\n(c) its ionisation energy alone\n\n(d) its electron affinity alone\n\nQ6. According to Fajans' rules, covalent character in an otherwise ionic compound is favoured by\n\n(a) a large cation with a low charge and a small, hard anion\n\n(b) a small, highly charged cation and a large, easily polarisable anion\n\n(c) a small cation and a small anion, both with low charge\n\n(d) a large cation and a large anion, both with high charge\n\nQ7. In the Schomaker-Stevenson equation for predicting bond length, the correction term involving electronegativity difference is\n\n(a) added to the sum of covalent radii, making the bond longer than expected\n\n(b) subtracted from the sum of covalent radii, making the bond shorter than expected\n\n(c) multiplied with the sum of covalent radii\n\n(d) irrelevant whenever the electronegativity difference is large\n\nQ8. Between NaF and NaI, the bond expected to have the greater percentage of ionic character, based on electronegativity difference, is\n\n(a) NaI, because iodine is a larger atom\n\n(b) NaF, because the electronegativity difference between Na and F is greater than between Na and I\n\n(c) both are equally ionic\n\n(d) NaI, because it has a lower melting point\n\nQ9. A bond is generally regarded as predominantly ionic (more ionic than covalent) once its percent ionic character, estimated from the electronegativity difference, exceeds approximately\n\n(a) 10%\n\n(b) 25%\n\n(c) 50%\n\n(d) 90%\n\nQ10. Which statement about the variation of electronegativity across a transition series (for example, Sc to Zn) is most accurate?\n\n(a) It increases as sharply as across a main-group period, because of similar effective nuclear charge increments\n\n(b) It varies relatively little compared to a main-group period, because the added d electrons shield the increasing nuclear charge fairly effectively\n\n(c) It decreases steadily from Sc to Zn\n\n(d) It is identical for every transition element\n\nQ11. A student calculates fluorine's electronegativity on the Mulliken scale and converts it to the Pauling scale using an approximate relation, obtaining a value somewhat different from the standard Pauling value of 3.98. This discrepancy mainly arises because\n\n(a) fluorine does not actually have the highest electronegativity\n\n(b) different electronegativity scales use different reference data and empirical scaling constants, so their absolute numerical values need not match exactly even though the relative order of elements is preserved\n\n(c) the Mulliken scale cannot be applied to fluorine\n\n(d) electronegativity is a directly measurable physical constant, so all scales must agree exactly\n\nQ12. On Pauling's original electronegativity scale, values were generally not assigned to noble gases mainly because\n\n(a) noble gases have no electrons\n\n(b) noble gases were regarded as chemically inert and did not form the covalent bonds whose energies the scale relies on\n\n(c) noble gases have the smallest atomic radii\n\n(d) noble gases have negative ionisation energies\n\n## Multiple Correct (MCQ)\n\n(One or more options may be correct.)\n\nQ13. Which of the following are recognised electronegativity scales?\n\n(a) Pauling scale\n\n(b) Mulliken scale\n\n(c) Allred-Rochow scale\n\n(d) Avogadro scale\n\nQ14. Which of the following factors tend to increase the electronegativity of an atom?\n\n(a) An increase in effective nuclear charge\n\n(b) A decrease in atomic/covalent radius\n\n(c) An increase in the number of inner shielding shells with poor shielding of the nucleus\n\n(d) An increase in the s-character of the hybrid orbital used for bonding\n\nQ15. Which of the following statements about group (substituent) electronegativity are correct?\n\n(a) The group electronegativity of $-CF_3$ is greater than that of $-CH_3$\n\n(b) $-NO_2$ is a strongly electron-withdrawing group with high group electronegativity\n\n(c) The group electronegativity of $-OCH_3$ is lower than that of $-F$\n\n(d) Alkyl groups such as $-CH_3$ are more electronegative than halogens\n\nQ16. Using the Hannay-Smith relation $\\%ionic = 16\\Delta\\chi + 3.5\\Delta\\chi^2$, which of the following bonds, with the given Pauling electronegativity differences $\\Delta\\chi$, are predicted to have more than 50% ionic character?\n\n(a) $\\Delta\\chi = 1.2$\n\n(b) $\\Delta\\chi = 1.8$\n\n(c) $\\Delta\\chi = 2.3$\n\n(d) $\\Delta\\chi = 2.9$\n\nQ17. Which of the following statements about hybridisation and electronegativity are correct?\n\n(a) An sp hybridised carbon is more electronegative than an sp3 hybridised carbon\n\n(b) Increasing s-character in a hybrid orbital brings the bonding electron pair closer to the nucleus on average, increasing effective attraction\n\n(c) The C\u2013H bond in an sp3 hybridised alkane is more acidic than the terminal C\u2013H bond in an sp hybridised alkyne\n\n(d) The greater electronegativity of an sp hybridised carbon makes the terminal alkyne proton more acidic than an alkane proton\n\nQ18. Which of the following statements about periodic trends and exceptions in electronegativity are correct?\n\n(a) Gallium has a slightly higher electronegativity than aluminium, due to poor shielding by the intervening 3d electrons\n\n(b) Electronegativity generally increases across a period and decreases down a group\n\n(c) On Pauling's original scale, helium and neon were assigned the highest electronegativity values of all elements\n\n(d) Transition metals show comparatively small variation in electronegativity across a row\n\n## Paragraph / Comprehension\n\n### Paragraph 1\n\nThe Pauling scale assigns fluorine the highest electronegativity value (3.98) among all elements, with values decreasing down a group and generally increasing across a period. When two atoms of different electronegativity combine, the shared electron pair is displaced towards the more electronegative atom, imparting partial ionic character to an otherwise covalent bond. Hannay and Smith proposed an empirical relation, $\\%ionic = 16\\Delta\\chi + 3.5\\Delta\\chi^2$, to estimate this ionic contribution directly from the Pauling electronegativity difference $\\Delta\\chi$. For a bond such as H\u2013Cl, with $\\chi(H)=2.20$ and $\\chi(Cl)=3.16$, this relation predicts a modest but significant ionic contribution.\n\nQ19. For the H\u2013Cl bond described above, $\\Delta\\chi$ equals\n\n(a) 0.86\n\n(b) 0.96\n\n(c) 1.16\n\n(d) 1.36\n\nQ20. Using the Hannay-Smith relation, the percent ionic character of the H\u2013Cl bond ($\\Delta\\chi=0.96$) is closest to\n\n(a) 12%\n\n(b) 19%\n\n(c) 26%\n\n(d) 34%\n\nQ21. Compared to H\u2013Cl, the H\u2013F bond ($\\Delta\\chi=1.78$) is expected to show\n\n(a) a lower percent ionic character than H\u2013Cl\n\n(b) an appreciably higher percent ionic character than H\u2013Cl, because percent ionic character increases with $\\Delta\\chi$\n\n(c) exactly the same percent ionic character as H\u2013Cl\n\n(d) zero ionic character, since both are covalent molecules\n\n### Paragraph 2\n\nInductive effects transmitted through sigma bonds mean that the effective electronegativity of an atom or group depends on what is attached to it. Replacing the hydrogen atoms of methane one by one with strongly electronegative halogens raises the effective electron-withdrawing power of the remaining carbon framework, which is why trichloroacetic acid is a far stronger acid than acetic acid. Similarly, the group electronegativity of $-CF_3$ exceeds that of $-CH_3$, and this is reflected in the greater acidity of trifluoroacetic acid compared with acetic acid, since the electron-withdrawing $-CF_3$ group stabilises the conjugate-base carboxylate anion more effectively.\n\nQ22. The greater acid strength of trichloroacetic acid compared with acetic acid is best explained by\n\n(a) chlorine atoms increasing the molecular weight of the acid\n\n(b) the electron-withdrawing inductive effect of the three chlorine atoms, which stabilises the negative charge on the conjugate base\n\n(c) chlorine atoms donating electron density to the carboxylate group\n\n(d) chlorine having a lower electronegativity than hydrogen\n\nQ23. The group electronegativity order for $-CF_3$ and $-CH_3$ is\n\n(a) $-CH_3 > -CF_3$\n\n(b) $-CF_3 > -CH_3$\n\n(c) they are equal\n\n(d) cannot be determined\n\nQ24. Which of the following acids is expected to be the weakest, based on the inductive/group-electronegativity argument above?\n\n(a) Trichloroacetic acid\n\n(b) Trifluoroacetic acid\n\n(c) Acetic acid\n\n(d) Monochloroacetic acid\n\n## Integer Type\n\nQ25. Among Li, Be, B, C, N, O, and F (period 2), using the Pauling electronegativity values Li $=0.98$, Be $=1.57$, B $=2.04$, C $=2.55$, N $=3.04$, O $=3.44$, F $=3.98$, how many of these elements have an electronegativity greater than 2.50?\n\nQ26. Among Na, Mg, Al, Si, P, S, and Cl (period 3), using Pauling values Na $=0.93$, Mg $=1.31$, Al $=1.61$, Si $=1.90$, P $=2.19$, S $=2.58$, Cl $=3.16$, how many of these elements have an electronegativity less than 1.50?\n\nQ27. Using Slater's rules for the $3s$ electron of sodium ($Z=11$, configuration $1s^2\\,2s^2\\,2p^6\\,3s^1$), calculate the effective nuclear charge $Z_{eff}$ and report the value of $10\\times Z_{eff}$, rounded to the nearest integer.\n\nQ28. Using Slater's rules for a $3s$ electron of magnesium ($Z=12$, configuration $1s^2\\,2s^2\\,2p^6\\,3s^2$), calculate the effective nuclear charge $Z_{eff}$ and report the value of $100\\times Z_{eff}$, rounded to the nearest integer.\n\nQ29. Using the Hannay-Smith relation $\\%ionic = 16\\Delta\\chi + 3.5\\Delta\\chi^2$ with $\\Delta\\chi = 1.2$, calculate the percent ionic character and report it rounded to the nearest integer.\n\nQ30. Among F, Cl, O, N, C, and S, using Pauling values F $=3.98$, Cl $=3.16$, O $=3.44$, N $=3.04$, C $=2.55$, S $=2.58$, how many of these elements have an electronegativity greater than 3.00?\n\nQ31. Using the Hannay-Smith relation, how many of the following four bonds, with Pauling electronegativity differences $\\Delta\\chi = 1.4$, $2.0$, $2.4$, and $3.1$, are predicted to have more than 50% ionic character?\n\nQ32. Using the Hannay-Smith relation, how many of the following five compounds, with electronegativity differences $\\Delta\\chi(NaCl)=2.23$, $\\Delta\\chi(HCl)=0.96$, $\\Delta\\chi(HF)=1.78$, $\\Delta\\chi(CsF)=3.19$, and $\\Delta\\chi(LiH)=1.24$, are predicted to have more than 50% ionic character?\n\n## Numerical Response\n\nQ33. The bond dissociation enthalpies of $H_2$, $Cl_2$, and $HCl$ are 436, 242, and 431 kJ/mol respectively. Using Pauling's relation $\\Delta\\chi = 0.102\\sqrt{\\Delta}$ (with $\\Delta$ in kJ/mol, $\\Delta = E(H\\text{-}Cl) - \\sqrt{E(H\\text{-}H)\\times E(Cl\\text{-}Cl)}$), calculate the electronegativity difference $\\Delta\\chi$ between H and Cl. (Answer correct to two decimal places.)\n\nQ34. Given $IE_1(Br) = 11.81$ eV and $EA(Br) = 3.37$ eV, calculate the Mulliken electronegativity $\\chi_M = (IE+EA)/2$, then estimate the Pauling electronegativity using $\\chi_P \\approx \\chi_M/2.8$. (Answer correct to two decimal places.)\n\nQ35. Using Slater's rules, the effective nuclear charge felt by a $3p$ valence electron of chlorine is $Z_{eff} = 6.10$, and the covalent radius of chlorine is 0.99 \u00c5. Using the Allred-Rochow formula $\\chi_{AR} = 0.359\\,Z_{eff}/r^2 + 0.744$ (r in \u00c5), calculate $\\chi_{AR}$ for chlorine. (Answer correct to two decimal places.)\n\nQ36. The covalent radii of carbon and fluorine are 0.77 \u00c5 and 0.72 \u00c5 respectively, and their Pauling electronegativities are 2.55 and 3.98 respectively. Using the Schomaker-Stevenson equation $r(C\\text{-}F) = r(C)+r(F) - 0.09|\\Delta\\chi|$ (correction constant 0.09 \u00c5), calculate the predicted C\u2013F bond length. (Answer correct to two decimal places, in \u00c5.)\n\nQ37. Using the Hannay-Smith relation $\\%ionic = 16\\Delta\\chi + 3.5\\Delta\\chi^2$, calculate the percent ionic character of the H\u2013F bond given $\\chi(H)=2.20$ and $\\chi(F)=3.98$. (Answer correct to two decimal places.)\n\nQ38. Using Pauling's exponential relation, fractional ionic character $= 1-e^{-\\Delta\\chi^2/4}$, calculate the percent ionic character of the H\u2013Cl bond given $\\chi(H)=2.20$ and $\\chi(Cl)=3.16$. (Answer correct to two decimal places.)\n\nQ39. Given $IE_1(O) = 13.62$ eV and $EA(O) = 1.46$ eV, calculate the Mulliken electronegativity $\\chi_M=(IE+EA)/2$, then estimate the Pauling electronegativity as $\\chi_P \\approx \\chi_M/2.8$. Calculate the magnitude of the difference between this estimated value and the accepted Pauling electronegativity of oxygen (3.44). (Answer correct to two decimal places.)\n\n## Assertion\u2013Reason (A/R)\n\nEach question below has an Assertion (A) and a Reason (R). Choose the correct option using this scheme: (a) Both A and R are true and R is the correct explanation of A. (b) Both A and R are true but R is not the correct explanation of A. (c) A is true but R is false. (d) A is false but R is true.\n\nQ40. Assertion (A): Fluorine has the highest electronegativity of any element on the Pauling scale.\n\nReason (R): Fluorine has the smallest covalent radius among elements that form stable covalent bonds and a very high effective nuclear charge, so it attracts a shared electron pair most strongly.\n\nQ41. Assertion (A): The carbon atom in acetylene ($HC\\equiv CH$) is more electronegative than the carbon atom in ethane ($H_3C\\text{-}CH_3$).\n\nReason (R): Ethane has a higher molecular weight than acetylene.\n\nQ42. Assertion (A): The group electronegativity of $-CF_3$ is higher than that of $-CH_3$.\n\nReason (R): Hydrogen is more electronegative than fluorine.\n\nQ43. Assertion (A): Electronegativity of an atom can be measured directly with a single physical instrument, just like mass or length.\n\nReason (R): Electronegativity values on the Pauling scale are derived indirectly from bond dissociation energy data, with the scale anchored by an arbitrary reference value.\n\nQ44. Assertion (A): The percent ionic character of a bond generally increases as the electronegativity difference between the bonded atoms increases.\n\nReason (R): A greater electronegativity difference produces greater charge separation and a larger bond dipole, pulling the shared electron density more strongly towards the more electronegative atom.\n\nQ45. Assertion (A): The Allred-Rochow electronegativity of an atom correlates reasonably well with its Pauling electronegativity across the periodic table.\n\nReason (R): Both scales assign fluorine the single highest electronegativity value among all commonly considered elements.\n\n## Matrix Match\n\nEach entry in List-I may match one or more entries in List-II unless stated otherwise.\n\nQ46. List-I\n\n| Item | Scale/Relation |\n|---|---|\n| A | Pauling scale |\n| B | Mulliken scale |\n| C | Allred-Rochow scale |\n| D | Hannay-Smith relation |\n\nList-II\n\n| Item | Basis |\n|---|---|\n| p | Based on bond dissociation energies, $\\Delta\\chi = k\\sqrt{\\Delta}$ |\n| q | Based on the average of ionisation energy and electron affinity |\n| r | Based on effective nuclear charge and covalent radius |\n| s | Used to estimate percent ionic character of a bond from $\\Delta\\chi$ |\n\nQ47. List-I\n\n| Item | Carbon type / group |\n|---|---|\n| A | sp hybridised carbon |\n| B | sp2 hybridised carbon |\n| C | sp3 hybridised carbon |\n| D | $-CF_3$ group |\n\nList-II\n\n| Item | Description |\n|---|---|\n| p | Lowest s-character among the three hybridised carbons, comparatively least electronegative |\n| q | Highest electronegativity among hybridised carbons, due to greatest s-character |\n| r | Intermediate electronegativity, found in alkenes |\n| s | High group electronegativity due to three strongly electronegative fluorine atoms |\n\nQ48. List-I\n\n| Item | Bond |\n|---|---|\n| A | NaF |\n| B | HCl |\n| C | HF |\n| D | CsF |\n\nList-II\n\n| Item | Description ($\\Delta\\chi$, Pauling scale) |\n|---|---|\n| p | $\\Delta\\chi \\approx 0.96$, lowest ionic character among these four |\n| q | $\\Delta\\chi \\approx 1.78$, moderate ionic character |\n| r | $\\Delta\\chi \\approx 3.19$, highest ionic character among these four |\n| s | $\\Delta\\chi \\approx 3.05$, second-highest ionic character among these four |\n\nQ49. List-I\n\n| Item | Concept |\n|---|---|\n| A | Fajans' rule for a small, highly charged cation |\n| B | Schomaker-Stevenson correction |\n| C | Group electronegativity comparison of $-OCH_3$ and $-F$ |\n| D | Acidity of the terminal proton in an sp hybridised alkyne |\n\nList-II\n\n| Item | Statement |\n|---|---|\n| p | Predicts greater covalent character in the resulting bond |\n| q | Predicts that the actual bond length is shorter than the simple sum of covalent radii when $\\Delta\\chi$ is large |\n| r | $-F$ has a higher group electronegativity than $-OCH_3$ |\n| s | The proton is more acidic than an analogous alkane proton because the sp carbon is more electronegative |\n\n## Innovative Pattern\n\nQ50. Five statements about electronegativity are given below. Score each statement $+2$ if it is True and $-1$ if it is False, then add up the five scores to obtain a single net integer, which is your answer.\n\nS1: On the Pauling scale, fluorine has an electronegativity of 3.98, the highest value among all elements.\n\nS2: The Allred-Rochow electronegativity formula contains a term inversely proportional to the square of the covalent radius.\n\nS3: According to Hannay and Smith, percent ionic character depends only on the electronegativity of the more electronegative atom in the bond, not on the difference between the two atoms' electronegativities.\n\nS4: An sp3 hybridised carbon atom is more electronegative than an sp hybridised carbon atom.\n\nS5: The Schomaker-Stevenson equation predicts that bonds with a large electronegativity difference are shorter than the simple sum of the covalent radii.\n\n## Answer Key\n\n| Question | Answer |\n|---|---|\n| Q1 | (c) |\n| Q2 | (b) |\n| Q3 | (b) |\n| Q4 | (b) |\n| Q5 | (b) |\n| Q6 | (b) |\n| Q7 | (b) |\n| Q8 | (b) |\n| Q9 | (c) |\n| Q10 | (b) |\n| Q11 | (b) |\n| Q12 | (b) |\n| Q13 | (a), (b), (c) |\n| Q14 | (a), (b), (d) |\n| Q15 | (a), (b), (c) |\n| Q16 | (c), (d) |\n| Q17 | (a), (b), (d) |\n| Q18 | (a), (b), (d) |\n| Q19 | (b) |\n| Q20 | (b) |\n| Q21 | (b) |\n| Q22 | (b) |\n| Q23 | (b) |\n| Q24 | (c) |\n| Q25 | 4 |\n| Q26 | 2 |\n| Q27 | 22 |\n| Q28 | 285 |\n| Q29 | 24 |\n| Q30 | 4 |\n| Q31 | 2 |\n| Q32 | 2 |\n| Q33 | 1.05 |\n| Q34 | 2.71 |\n| Q35 | 2.98 |\n| Q36 | 1.36 |\n| Q37 | 39.57 |\n| Q38 | 20.58 |\n| Q39 | 0.75 |\n| Q40 | (a) |\n| Q41 | (b) |\n| Q42 | (c) |\n| Q43 | (d) |\n| Q44 | (a) |\n| Q45 | (b) |\n| Q46 | A-p, B-q, C-r, D-s |\n| Q47 | A-q, B-r, C-p, D-s |\n| Q48 | A-s, B-p, C-q, D-r |\n| Q49 | A-p, B-q, C-r, D-s |\n| Q50 | 4 |\n\n## Worked Solutions\n\nS1. Increasing s-character in the hybrid orbital pulls the bonding electron pair closer to the more compact, lower-energy s-dominated orbital, increasing effective electronegativity. The order is sp > sp2 > sp3, so the sp carbon in acetylene is most electronegative. Answer: (c).\n\nS2. Each chlorine atom withdraws electron density inductively, raising the effective (group) electronegativity of the attached carbon; $CHCl_3$'s carbon is therefore more electronegative than in $CH_4$, $CH_3CH_3$, or $CH_3Li$. Answer: (b).\n\nS3. The three highly electronegative fluorine atoms in $-CF_3$ withdraw electron density strongly through induction, giving it a much higher group electronegativity than $-CH_3$. Answer: (b).\n\nS4. The Allred-Rochow scale defines electronegativity from the electrostatic attractive force ($\\propto Z_{eff}/r^2$) exerted by the effective nuclear charge on a bonding electron at the covalent radius. Answer: (b).\n\nS5. Mulliken's definition averages the ionisation energy and electron affinity of an atom, $\\chi_M=(IE+EA)/2$. Answer: (b).\n\nS6. Fajans' rules state that covalent character is favoured by a small, highly charged cation (high polarising power) combined with a large, easily polarisable anion. Answer: (b).\n\nS7. The Schomaker-Stevenson correction term is subtracted from the simple sum of covalent radii, reflecting partial double-bond/ionic character that shortens the bond when the electronegativity difference is large. Answer: (b).\n\nS8. NaF has a much larger Pauling electronegativity difference ($\\Delta\\chi\\approx3.05$) than NaI ($\\Delta\\chi\\approx1.7$), so NaF is predicted to have greater ionic character. Answer: (b).\n\nS9. By convention, a bond is regarded as predominantly ionic once its estimated percent ionic character crosses roughly 50%. Answer: (c).\n\nS10. Across a transition series, added electrons enter inner d orbitals that shield the increasing nuclear charge fairly well, so effective nuclear charge \u2014 and hence electronegativity \u2014 changes much less than across a main-group period. Answer: (b).\n\nS11. Different electronegativity scales (Pauling, Mulliken, Allred-Rochow, etc.) rest on different underlying data and empirical scaling constants, so their absolute numbers legitimately differ even though they agree on relative ordering. Answer: (b).\n\nS12. Pauling's scale is built from bond energies of covalent compounds; since noble gases were traditionally considered chemically inert and did not form such bonds, they were not assigned values on the original scale. Answer: (b).\n\nS13. Pauling, Mulliken, and Allred-Rochow are all established, independently defined electronegativity scales; \"Avogadro scale\" does not exist. Answer: (a), (b), (c).\n\nS14. Higher effective nuclear charge, smaller radius, and greater s-character in a hybrid orbital all increase an atom's pull on bonding electrons, raising electronegativity; more poorly-shielding inner shells do not by themselves increase electronegativity in the way stated. Answer: (a), (b), (d).\n\nS15. $-CF_3$ and $-NO_2$ are strong electron-withdrawing groups with high group electronegativity, and $-OCH_3$'s group electronegativity is lower than fluorine's; alkyl groups are electron-donating, not more electronegative than halogens. Answer: (a), (b), (c).\n\nS16. Computing $16\\Delta\\chi+3.5\\Delta\\chi^2$: for 1.2 it is about 24.2%, for 1.8 about 40.1%, for 2.3 about 55.3%, and for 2.9 about 75.8%. Only 2.3 and 2.9 exceed 50%. Answer: (c), (d).\n\nS17. Greater s-character in the sp orbital pulls bonding electrons closer to the nucleus, making sp carbon more electronegative than sp3 carbon and making the terminal alkyne proton (attached to the more electronegative sp carbon) more acidic than an alkane proton; the alkane C\u2013H is therefore less, not more, acidic than the alkyne C\u2013H. Answer: (a), (b), (d).\n\nS18. Poor shielding by the intervening 3d electrons makes gallium slightly more electronegative than aluminium; electronegativity does generally increase across a period and decrease down a group; transition metals vary comparatively little across a row. Noble gases were not conventionally assigned electronegativity on Pauling's original scale. Answer: (a), (b), (d).\n\nS19. $\\Delta\\chi = \\chi(Cl)-\\chi(H) = 3.16-2.20 = 0.96$. Answer: (b).\n\nS20. $\\%ionic = 16(0.96)+3.5(0.96)^2 = 15.36+3.23 = 18.59\\% \\approx 19\\%$. Answer: (b).\n\nS21. Since percent ionic character increases with $\\Delta\\chi$ in the Hannay-Smith relation, and H\u2013F's $\\Delta\\chi$ (1.78) exceeds H\u2013Cl's (0.96), H\u2013F shows appreciably higher ionic character. Answer: (b).\n\nS22. The three electronegative chlorine atoms inductively withdraw electron density and stabilise the negative charge on the conjugate-base carboxylate ion, making the acid stronger. Answer: (b).\n\nS23. Fluorine's very high electronegativity gives $-CF_3$ a higher group electronegativity than $-CH_3$. Answer: (b).\n\nS24. With the weakest electron-withdrawing substituents (only hydrogens), acetic acid has the least stabilised conjugate base and is therefore the weakest acid among the options. Answer: (c).\n\nS25. C (2.55), N (3.04), O (3.44), and F (3.98) all exceed 2.50 \u2014 four elements.\n\nS26. Only Na (0.93) and Mg (1.31) are below 1.50 \u2014 two elements.\n\nS27. For Na's $3s^1$ electron: shielding $S = 8(0.85)+2(1.00) = 6.8+2.0 = 8.8$; $Z_{eff}=11-8.8=2.2$; $10\\times Z_{eff}=22$.\n\nS28. For Mg's $3s^2$ electrons: shielding from the other $3s$ electron $=0.35$, from the 8 electrons in $n=2$ shell $=8(0.85)=6.8$, from the 2 electrons in $n=1$ shell $=2(1.00)=2.0$; total $S=9.15$; $Z_{eff}=12-9.15=2.85$; $100\\times Z_{eff}=285$.\n\nS29. $16(1.2)+3.5(1.2)^2 = 19.2+5.04=24.24\\approx24\\%$.\n\nS30. F (3.98), Cl (3.16), O (3.44), and N (3.04) all exceed 3.00 \u2014 four elements (C and S do not).\n\nS31. Computing $16\\Delta\\chi+3.5\\Delta\\chi^2$: 1.4 gives about 29.3%, 2.0 gives 46%, 2.4 gives about 58.6%, and 3.1 gives about 83.2%. Only 2.4 and 3.1 exceed 50% \u2014 two bonds.\n\nS32. Computing the relation: NaCl ($\\Delta\\chi=2.23$) gives about 53.1%, HCl (0.96) gives about 18.6%, HF (1.78) gives about 39.6%, CsF (3.19) gives about 86.7%, and LiH (1.24) gives about 25.2%. Only NaCl and CsF exceed 50% \u2014 two compounds.\n\nS33. $\\sqrt{436\\times242}=\\sqrt{105512}\\approx324.83$; $\\Delta = 431-324.83=106.17$ kJ/mol; $\\Delta\\chi=0.102\\sqrt{106.17}=0.102\\times10.30=1.05$.\n\nS34. $\\chi_M=(11.81+3.37)/2=7.59$ eV; $\\chi_P=7.59/2.8=2.71$.\n\nS35. $\\chi_{AR}=0.359(6.10)/(0.99)^2+0.744 = 2.190/0.980+0.744 = 2.234+0.744=2.98$.\n\nS36. $r(C\\text{-}F)=0.77+0.72-0.09(3.98-2.55)=1.49-0.09(1.43)=1.49-0.129=1.36$ \u00c5.\n\nS37. $\\Delta\\chi=3.98-2.20=1.78$; $\\%ionic=16(1.78)+3.5(1.78)^2=28.48+11.09=39.57\\%$.\n\nS38. $\\Delta\\chi=3.16-2.20=0.96$; $\\Delta\\chi^2/4=0.2304$; $e^{-0.2304}\\approx0.7942$; fractional ionic character $=1-0.7942=0.2058$, i.e. $20.58\\%$.\n\nS39. $\\chi_M(O)=(13.62+1.46)/2=7.54$ eV; $\\chi_P\\approx7.54/2.8=2.69$; difference from the accepted Pauling value $=|3.44-2.69|=0.75$.\n\nS40. Fluorine's very small covalent radius combined with its very high effective nuclear charge gives it the strongest pull on a shared electron pair, correctly explaining its top ranking on the Pauling scale. Answer: (a).\n\nS41. Both statements are individually true (sp carbon in acetylene is more electronegative than sp3 carbon in ethane; ethane does have a higher molecular weight), but molecular weight has no bearing on electronegativity \u2014 the real cause is the difference in hybridisation/s-character. Answer: (b).\n\nS42. $-CF_3$ is indeed more electronegative than $-CH_3$ (A is true), but the reason given is false \u2014 fluorine is far more electronegative than hydrogen, not less. Answer: (c).\n\nS43. Electronegativity cannot be measured directly with a single instrument (A is false); it is instead derived indirectly from properties like bond energies, with the Pauling scale anchored by an arbitrarily chosen reference point (R is true). Answer: (d).\n\nS44. A larger electronegativity difference produces greater charge separation and a larger dipole, correctly explaining why percent ionic character rises with $\\Delta\\chi$. Answer: (a).\n\nS45. Both statements are true, but the fact that both scales rank fluorine as most electronegative is only a single shared data point \u2014 it does not, by itself, explain the broader correlation between the two scales across the whole periodic table, which instead arises because both are built from nuclear charge and atomic size. Answer: (b).\n\nS46. Pauling's scale uses bond-energy differences (A-p); Mulliken's scale averages IE and EA (B-q); Allred-Rochow uses effective nuclear charge and covalent radius (C-r); Hannay-Smith estimates percent ionic character from $\\Delta\\chi$ (D-s).\n\nS47. sp carbon has the greatest s-character and highest electronegativity (A-q); sp2 carbon is intermediate, found in alkenes (B-r); sp3 carbon has the least s-character and lowest electronegativity among the three (C-p); $-CF_3$ has high group electronegativity from its three fluorine atoms (D-s).\n\nS48. Using approximate Pauling differences: HCl has $\\Delta\\chi\\approx0.96$, the smallest (B-p); HF has $\\Delta\\chi\\approx1.78$, moderate (C-q); NaF has $\\Delta\\chi\\approx3.05$, second-highest (A-s); CsF has $\\Delta\\chi\\approx3.19$, the highest (D-r).\n\nS49. A small, highly charged cation polarises the anion strongly, increasing covalent character (A-p); the Schomaker-Stevenson correction shortens the predicted bond length when $\\Delta\\chi$ is large (B-q); fluorine's group electronegativity exceeds that of $-OCH_3$ (C-r); the sp carbon's higher electronegativity makes the terminal alkyne proton more acidic than an alkane proton (D-s).\n\nS50. S1 is true (+2), S2 is true (+2) since the Allred-Rochow formula includes a $Z_{eff}/r^2$ term, S3 is false (\u22121) because percent ionic character depends on $\\Delta\\chi$, not a single atom's electronegativity, S4 is false (\u22121) since sp, not sp3, carbon is more electronegative, and S5 is true (+2). Net score $=2+2-1-1+2=4$.\n";
const RAW_MD_ZEFF = "## Single Correct (SCQ)\n\nQ1. Using Slater's rules, the shielding constant $\\sigma$ experienced by a 3p electron of phosphorus ($Z=15$) is:\n\n(a) 9.90\n\n(b) 10.20\n\n(c) 10.55\n\n(d) 4.80\n\nQ2. According to Slater's rules, the correct increasing order of the Slater effective nuclear charge $Z_{eff}$ felt by the valence electron of Na, Mg and Al is:\n\n(a) $\\text{Al}<\\text{Mg}<\\text{Na}$\n\n(b) $\\text{Mg}<\\text{Na}<\\text{Al}$\n\n(c) $\\text{Na}<\\text{Mg}<\\text{Al}$\n\n(d) $\\text{Na}<\\text{Al}<\\text{Mg}$\n\nQ3. In vanadium ($Z=23$), both the first and second electrons removed on ionisation come from the 4s subshell rather than the 3d subshell, even though 4s filled first by the Aufbau principle. Which statement, based on Slater's rules, correctly justifies this order?\n\n(a) V's 4s electron has $Z_{eff}=3.30$ while its 3d electron has $Z_{eff}=4.30$, so the 3d electron is more strongly bound to the nucleus\n\n(b) The 4s and 3d electrons of V have identical $Z_{eff}$, so either could be removed first with equal probability\n\n(c) 3d orbitals lie farther from the nucleus on average and are therefore removed first\n\n(d) Slater's rules predict that all 3d electrons must be removed before any 4s electron\n\nQ4. The Slater $Z_{eff}$ for the 4p valence electron of germanium ($Z=32$) is nearest to:\n\n(a) 5.65\n\n(b) 6.65\n\n(c) 4.65\n\n(d) 5.00\n\nQ5. Ca$^{2+}$ and Ar are an isoelectronic pair (18 electrons each). Using Slater's rules for their respective 3p electrons, the ratio $Z_{eff}(\\text{Ca}^{2+}) : Z_{eff}(\\text{Ar})$ is closest to:\n\n(a) 1.00\n\n(b) 1.15\n\n(c) 1.30\n\n(d) 1.50\n\nQ6. Using Slater's rules, the difference $Z_{eff}(\\text{Br}) - Z_{eff}(\\text{Se})$ for their respective 4p valence electrons is:\n\n(a) 0.35\n\n(b) 0.65\n\n(c) 1.00\n\n(d) 0.85\n\nQ7. Among Ce ($Z=58$), Eu ($Z=63$), Gd ($Z=64$) and Lu ($Z=71$), the element with the HIGHEST Slater $Z_{eff}$ for its 4f electron is:\n\n(a) Ce\n\n(b) Eu\n\n(c) Gd\n\n(d) Lu\n\nQ8. Choose the CORRECT statement regarding the Slater $Z_{eff}$ values of the 3d and 4s electrons of manganese ($Z=25$):\n\n(a) $Z_{eff}(3d)=5.60$ and $Z_{eff}(4s)=3.60$, so the 3d electron is held more tightly than the 4s electron\n\n(b) $Z_{eff}(4s)>Z_{eff}(3d)$ for Mn\n\n(c) $Z_{eff}(3d)=Z_{eff}(4s)$ for Mn\n\n(d) $Z_{eff}(3d)=3.60$ and $Z_{eff}(4s)=5.60$\n\nQ9. By Slater's rule, the valence p-electron $Z_{eff}$ values of Al, Ga, In and Tl are 3.50, 5.00, 5.00 and 5.00 respectively. This apparent constancy from Ga onward, despite the successive insertion of a complete $(n-1)d^{10}$ (and, for Tl, $4f^{14}$) subshell, best illustrates which limitation of Slater's rule?\n\n(a) Slater's rule assigns full 1.00/0.85-type shielding to the added inner d/f electrons, whereas real d and f electrons shield rather poorly, so the true $Z_{eff}$ (and $IE_1$) actually keeps rising from Al to Ga to Tl\n\n(b) Slater's rule is exact here and no correction to real atoms is needed\n\n(c) Ga, In and Tl do not actually possess any d electrons in their core\n\n(d) Slater's rule requires $Z_{eff}$ to decrease steadily down every group\n\nQ10. The Slater $Z_{eff}$ for the 5p valence electron of tin ($Z=50$) is nearest to:\n\n(a) 4.65\n\n(b) 5.65\n\n(c) 6.65\n\n(d) 7.65\n\nQ11. Among the cations $\\text{Cr}^{3+}$, $\\text{Mn}^{2+}$, $\\text{Fe}^{3+}$ and $\\text{Co}^{2+}$, using Slater's rules the HIGHEST $Z_{eff}$ for the 3d electron is found in:\n\n(a) $\\text{Cr}^{3+}$\n\n(b) $\\text{Mn}^{2+}$\n\n(c) $\\text{Fe}^{3+}$\n\n(d) $\\text{Co}^{2+}$\n\nQ12. $\\text{Zn}^{2+}$ and $\\text{Cu}^{+}$ both have a $3d^{10}$ configuration with no 4s electrons. Their Slater $Z_{eff}$ values for the 3d electron are 8.85 and 7.85 respectively. This difference of exactly 1.00 arises because:\n\n(a) Zn has one more proton than Cu while the shielding-group composition (the same inner core plus $3d^{10}$) is otherwise identical, so $\\sigma$ is unchanged and $Z_{eff}$ rises by exactly 1 per unit increase in $Z$\n\n(b) $\\text{Cu}^{+}$ retains an extra 4s electron that $\\text{Zn}^{2+}$ lacks\n\n(c) $\\text{Zn}^{2+}$ has fewer 3d electrons than $\\text{Cu}^{+}$\n\n(d) the difference is merely a rounding artefact of Slater's rule\n\n## Multiple Correct (MCQ)\n\n(One or more options may be correct.)\n\nQ13. Which of the following statements about Slater's rules are CORRECT?\n\n(a) The shielding contributed by one 1s electron to another 1s electron is 0.30, not 0.35\n\n(b) For a target d or f electron, every electron in a group to its left contributes 0.85 to the shielding\n\n(c) Electrons within the same $(ns,np)$ group shield each other by 0.35 each\n\n(d) Electrons two or more principal shells below the target ns/np electron shield it fully, by 1.00 each\n\nQ14. For zinc ($Z=30$), which of the following Slater-rule statements are CORRECT?\n\n(a) $Z_{eff}$ for a 3d electron of Zn is 8.85\n\n(b) $Z_{eff}$ for the 4s electron of Zn is 4.35\n\n(c) The shielding constant $\\sigma$ for a 3d electron of Zn is 21.15\n\n(d) The shielding constant $\\sigma$ for the 4s electron of Zn is 21.15\n\nQ15. Consider the 10-electron isoelectronic series $\\text{N}^{3-}, \\text{O}^{2-}, \\text{F}^-, \\text{Ne}, \\text{Na}^+, \\text{Mg}^{2+}, \\text{Al}^{3+}$. Which of the following statements are CORRECT?\n\n(a) The Slater $Z_{eff}$ for the 2p electron increases monotonically from $\\text{N}^{3-}$ to $\\text{Al}^{3+}$\n\n(b) The shielding constant $\\sigma$ is identical (4.15) for every member of this series\n\n(c) Ne has the smallest $Z_{eff}$ in this series\n\n(d) $\\text{Al}^{3+}$ has a smaller ionic radius than $\\text{Mg}^{2+}$, consistent with its higher $Z_{eff}$\n\nQ16. Which of the following are genuine LIMITATIONS of Slater's rule as an approximate scheme for effective nuclear charge?\n\n(a) It predicts an identical $Z_{eff}$ (5.00) for the valence p-electron of Ga, In and Tl, whereas real effective nuclear charges rise down this group because intervening $(n-1)d$/$(n-2)f$ electrons shield poorly\n\n(b) It fully accounts for electron correlation effects beyond simple charge screening\n\n(c) It is an empirical, pre-Hartree\u2013Fock scheme rather than a rigorous quantum-mechanical calculation\n\n(d) It assigns the same shielding coefficient (0.35) to a 2s and a 2p electron of the same atom because both are grouped together\n\nQ17. Slater's rule, applied identically down a group of the d-block, gives matching $Z_{eff}$ values for corresponding elements of the 3d, 4d and 5d series. Which of the following pairs correctly illustrate this?\n\n(a) Sc (3d) and Y (4d) both give $Z_{eff}=3.00$\n\n(b) Zr (4d) and Hf (5d) both give $Z_{eff}=3.65$\n\n(c) Cu (3d) and Ag (4d) both give $Z_{eff}=7.85$\n\n(d) Cu (3d) and Au (5d) both give $Z_{eff}=7.85$\n\nQ18. Regarding Slater $Z_{eff}$ for 4f electrons, which statements are CORRECT?\n\n(a) $Z_{eff}$ for a 4f electron of $\\text{Ce}^{3+}$ equals that of neutral Ce (both 12.00), since removing the 6s and 5d electrons (which lie outside the 4f group in Slater's scheme) does not change the shielding felt by a 4f electron\n\n(b) $Z_{eff}$ for a 4f electron of $\\text{Eu}^{2+}$ (14.90) is smaller than that of $\\text{Eu}^{3+}$ (15.25)\n\n(c) The shielding constant for a 4f electron of Lu ($Z=71$, $4f^{14}$) is smaller than that for a 4f electron of Ce ($Z=58$, $4f^1$)\n\n(d) $Z_{eff}$ for the 4f electron of Gd (15.90) is less than that for the 4f electron of Lu (20.45)\n\n## Paragraph / Comprehension\n\nIn Slater's scheme, electrons are grouped as $(1s)(2s,2p)(3s,3p)(3d)(4s,4p)(4d)(4f)(5s,5p)\\ldots$. For a valence ns or np electron, electrons within the same group shield by 0.35 each (0.30 within the 1s group), electrons one principal shell below shield by 0.85 each, and electrons two or more shells below shield fully, by 1.00 each. Because every coefficient used (0.30, 0.35, 0.85, 1.00) is a multiple of 0.05, the resulting $Z_{eff}$ values form a very regular arithmetic pattern within a period or an isoelectronic series. Consider the third-period elements Na through Ar, and separately the 18-electron isoelectronic set $\\text{Cl}^-, \\text{Ar}, \\text{K}^+, \\text{Ca}^{2+}, \\text{Sc}^{3+}, \\text{Ti}^{4+}$, each of which has an identical $3s^23p^6$ core.\n\nQ19. Going from Na to Ar across period 3, the Slater $Z_{eff}$ of the valence electron increases in steps of:\n\n(a) 0.35\n\n(b) 0.65\n\n(c) 0.85\n\n(d) 1.00\n\nQ20. For the isoelectronic series $\\text{Cl}^-, \\text{Ar}, \\text{K}^+, \\text{Ca}^{2+}, \\text{Sc}^{3+}, \\text{Ti}^{4+}$, the Slater shielding constant $\\sigma$ for the 3p electron:\n\n(a) increases by 1.00 per step\n\n(b) decreases by 1.00 per step\n\n(c) stays exactly constant, at 11.25\n\n(d) stays exactly constant, at 6.75\n\nQ21. The Slater $Z_{eff}$ for the 3p electron of $\\text{Ca}^{2+}$ in this series is:\n\n(a) 6.75\n\n(b) 7.75\n\n(c) 8.75\n\n(d) 9.75\n\nFor the first transition series, Slater's rules show that a 3d electron experiences a distinctly higher $Z_{eff}$ than a 4s electron of the same atom, even though 4s fills first by the Aufbau principle. This is because the 4s group lies \"outside\" the 3d group in Slater's ordering and receives no shielding contribution from 3d electrons, whereas the 4s electron itself IS shielded by the 3d electrons (which lie in the same principal shell, $n=3$, as the core 3s and 3p electrons, each contributing 0.85 to the 4s electron's shielding). This asymmetry is the calculation-based rationale for why 4s electrons are always removed before 3d electrons on ionisation of a first-row transition metal.\n\nQ22. Which of the following best explains, via Slater's rules, why a 4s electron is removed before a 3d electron during ionisation of a first-row transition metal?\n\n(a) 4s electrons always have a higher principal quantum number and so are removed first regardless of $Z_{eff}$\n\n(b) 3d electrons experience a higher $Z_{eff}$ (are more tightly bound) than 4s electrons in the same atom\n\n(c) 4s orbitals cease to exist once any electron is removed from the atom\n\n(d) 3d orbitals shield the nucleus for 4s electrons only weakly\n\nQ23. For Zn ($Z=30$), by how much does the Slater $Z_{eff}$ of a 3d electron exceed that of a 4s electron?\n\n(a) 2.50\n\n(b) 3.50\n\n(c) 4.50\n\n(d) 5.50\n\nQ24. Which statement about the ten $3d$ electrons of Zn is CORRECT, according to Slater's rules?\n\n(a) They shield a 4s electron by 0.85 each, while a 4s electron does not shield them at all\n\n(b) They shield a 4s electron by 0.35 each\n\n(c) They shield a 4s electron by 1.00 each\n\n(d) A 4s electron shields a 3d electron by 0.85\n\n## Integer Type\n\nQ25. For the 4p electron of selenium ($Z=34$), find the total number of electrons that contribute a shielding of exactly 1.00 each (i.e., electrons two or more principal shells below the 4p group).\n\nQ26. For the 4s electron of calcium ($Z=20$), find the total number of electrons that contribute a shielding of exactly 0.85 each.\n\nQ27. For a 3d electron of iron ($Z=26$), find the total number of electrons that contribute a shielding of exactly 1.00 each.\n\nQ28. Among the period-3 p-block elements Al, Si, P, S, Cl and Ar, find the number of elements whose Slater $Z_{eff}$ for the 3p valence electron exceeds 5.00.\n\nQ29. Among the ten 3d-series elements Sc through Zn, find the number of elements for which $Z_{eff}(3d) - Z_{eff}(4s) \\geq 3.00$ (Slater's rule).\n\nQ30. Among the six 18-electron isoelectronic species $\\text{Cl}^-, \\text{Ar}, \\text{K}^+, \\text{Ca}^{2+}, \\text{Sc}^{3+}, \\text{Ti}^{4+}$, find the number of species whose Slater $Z_{eff}$ for the 3p electron exceeds 8.00.\n\nQ31. For the 4f electron of neutral cerium ($Z=58$, configuration $[\\text{Xe}]4f^15d^16s^2$), find the total number of electrons that contribute a shielding of exactly 1.00 each.\n\nQ32. Among the ten 3d-series elements Sc through Zn, find the number of elements whose ground-state configuration deviates from the simple $(n-1)d^xns^2$ pattern owing to the extra stability of a half-filled or completely filled d-subshell.\n\n## Numerical Response\n\n(All answers are exact Slater-rule calculations; report each correct to two decimal places.)\n\nQ33. Using Slater's rules, calculate $Z_{eff}$ for a 3d electron of nickel ($Z=28$).\n\nQ34. Using Slater's rules, calculate $Z_{eff}$ for a 4p electron of arsenic ($Z=33$).\n\nQ35. Using Slater's rules, calculate $Z_{eff}$ for a 3d electron of $\\text{Mn}^{2+}$ ($Z=25$; the ion is formed by removing the two 4s electrons of Mn).\n\nQ36. Using Slater's rules, calculate $Z_{eff}$ for a 4f electron of $\\text{Eu}^{3+}$ ($Z=63$; formed by removing the two 6s electrons and one 4f electron of Eu).\n\nQ37. For cobalt ($Z=27$), calculate $Z_{eff}(3d) - Z_{eff}(4s)$ using Slater's rules.\n\nQ38. Using Slater's rules, calculate $Z_{eff}$ for a 3p electron of $\\text{S}^{2-}$ ($Z=16$; the ion is formed by adding two electrons to the 3p subshell of S).\n\nQ39. Using Slater's rules, calculate $Z_{eff}$ for a 5d electron of tantalum ($Z=73$).\n\n## Assertion\u2013Reason (A/R)\n\nEach question below has an Assertion (A) and a Reason (R). Choose: (a) if both A and R are true and R is the correct explanation of A; (b) if both A and R are true but R is NOT the correct explanation of A; (c) if A is true but R is false; (d) if A is false but R is true.\n\nQ40. Assertion (A): The Slater $Z_{eff}$ experienced by a 2p electron of fluorine is greater than that experienced by a 2p electron of oxygen.\n\nReason (R): Within the same $(ns,np)$ Slater group, adding one more proton while the electrons stay in the same group increases $Z$ by 1 but $\\sigma$ by only 0.35, so $Z_{eff}$ rises by 0.65 per step across a period.\n\nQ41. Assertion (A): Going down group 1 from Na to Cs, the Slater $Z_{eff}$ for the valence ns electron stays essentially constant (about 2.20).\n\nReason (R): This is because every inner shell contributes exactly 0.35 to the shielding of the valence electron, regardless of which shell it is.\n\nQ42. Assertion (A): Ga, In and Tl (group 13) all have an identical Slater $Z_{eff}$ of 5.00 for their valence p-electron.\n\nReason (R): The $(n-1)d^{10}$ electrons present in Ga, In and Tl are, in reality, poor shields for the outer ns/np electrons, causing the true effective nuclear charge (and first ionisation enthalpy) to rise anomalously compared to Al.\n\nQ43. Assertion (A): The Slater shielding constant $\\sigma$ for a 3d electron of copper is greater than that for a 4s electron of copper.\n\nReason (R): Slater's rule assigns a coefficient of 1.00 to every electron in a group to the left of a target d/f electron, whereas for an s/p target electron the immediately lower $(n-1)$ shell is assigned only 0.85.\n\nQ44. Assertion (A): Among $\\text{Cl}^-, \\text{Ar}, \\text{K}^+, \\text{Ca}^{2+}$ (all 18-electron species), the Slater $Z_{eff}$ for the 3p electron increases steadily from $\\text{Cl}^-$ to $\\text{Ca}^{2+}$.\n\nReason (R): Within an isoelectronic series the shielding constant $\\sigma$ is exactly the same for every member, so $Z_{eff}$ increases in lock-step with the increasing nuclear charge $Z$.\n\nQ45. Assertion (A): The Slater $Z_{eff}$ for the valence electron of Mg (3s, 2.85) equals that for the valence electron of Ca (4s, 2.85).\n\nReason (R): Both magnesium and calcium are reactive metals that form stable $+2$ ions and react with water.\n\n## Matrix Match\n\nQ46. Match the species/electron in List-I with its Slater $Z_{eff}$ value in List-II.\n\n| List-I | List-II |\n|---|---|\n| A. 3d electron of Ti ($Z=22$) | p. 3.15 |\n| B. 4s electron of Ti ($Z=22$) | q. 3.65 |\n| C. 3d electron of Cr ($Z=24$) | r. 4.60 |\n| D. 4p electron of Ge ($Z=32$) | s. 5.65 |\n\n(List-II also contains the distractor value t. 3.30, corresponding to no entry in List-I.)\n\nQ47. Match the target electron in List-I with the number of electrons that shield it by exactly 1.00 each (Slater's rule), given in List-II.\n\n| List-I | List-II |\n|---|---|\n| A. 3p electron of Al ($Z=13$) | p. 2 |\n| B. 4p electron of Br ($Z=35$) | q. 10 |\n| C. 3d electron of Fe ($Z=26$) | r. 18 |\n| D. 4f electron of Ce ($Z=58$) | s. 46 |\n\nQ48. Match the species in List-I with its Slater $Z_{eff}$ for the electron named, given in List-II.\n\n| List-I | List-II |\n|---|---|\n| A. 3d electron of $\\text{Mn}^{2+}$ | p. 5.60 |\n| B. 3d electron of $\\text{Cu}^{2+}$ | q. 8.20 |\n| C. 4d electron of Zr | r. 3.65 |\n| D. 5d electron of Hf | r. 3.65 |\n\n(Note: C and D both map to the same List-II value r, illustrating that Zr and Hf share an identical Slater shielding structure.)\n\nQ49. Match the periodic observation in List-I with the correct description/value in List-II.\n\n| List-I | List-II |\n|---|---|\n| A. Slater $Z_{eff}$ trend for the valence electron across Na to Ar | p. increases in steps of 0.65 |\n| B. Slater $Z_{eff}$ trend for the valence ns electron down group 1 (Li to Cs) | q. remains virtually constant |\n| C. Difference in Slater $Z_{eff}$ between the 2p electrons of O and N | r. equals 0.65 |\n| D. Slater shielding constant for a 1s electron of He | s. equals 0.30 |\n\n## Innovative Pattern\n\nQ50. Crack the locker code. Each of the five clues below asks you to compute a Slater-rule $Z_{eff}$ value to two decimal places. For each computed value, take its FIRST digit after the decimal point (the tenths digit) as one digit of a 5-digit locker code, reading the clues in order (Clue 1 gives the leftmost digit, Clue 5 the rightmost). Report the complete 5-digit code, including any leading zero.\n\nClue 1: $Z_{eff}$ for a 3d electron of scandium ($Z=21$).\n\nClue 2: $Z_{eff}$ for a 4p electron of bromine ($Z=35$).\n\nClue 3: $Z_{eff}$ for a 3d electron of copper ($Z=29$).\n\nClue 4: $Z_{eff}$ for a 2p electron of fluorine ($Z=9$).\n\nClue 5: $Z_{eff}$ for a 4f electron of gadolinium ($Z=64$).\n\n## Answer Key\n\n| Q. No. | Answer |\n|---|---|\n| Q1 | (b) 10.20 |\n| Q2 | (c) |\n| Q3 | (a) |\n| Q4 | (a) 5.65 |\n| Q5 | (c) 1.30 |\n| Q6 | (b) 0.65 |\n| Q7 | (d) Lu |\n| Q8 | (a) |\n| Q9 | (a) |\n| Q10 | (b) 5.65 |\n| Q11 | (d) $\\text{Co}^{2+}$ |\n| Q12 | (a) |\n| Q13 | (a), (c), (d) |\n| Q14 | (a), (b), (c) |\n| Q15 | (a), (b), (d) |\n| Q16 | (a), (c), (d) |\n| Q17 | (a), (b), (c), (d) |\n| Q18 | (a), (b), (d) |\n| Q19 | (b) |\n| Q20 | (c) |\n| Q21 | (c) |\n| Q22 | (b) |\n| Q23 | (c) |\n| Q24 | (a) |\n| Q25 | 10 |\n| Q26 | 8 |\n| Q27 | 18 |\n| Q28 | 3 |\n| Q29 | 4 |\n| Q30 | 3 |\n| Q31 | 46 |\n| Q32 | 2 |\n| Q33 | 7.55 |\n| Q34 | 6.30 |\n| Q35 | 5.60 |\n| Q36 | 15.25 |\n| Q37 | 3.00 |\n| Q38 | 4.75 |\n| Q39 | 4.30 |\n| Q40 | (a) |\n| Q41 | (c) |\n| Q42 | (b) |\n| Q43 | (d) |\n| Q44 | (a) |\n| Q45 | (b) |\n| Q46 | A-q, B-p, C-r, D-s |\n| Q47 | A-p, B-q, C-r, D-s |\n| Q48 | A-p, B-q, C-r, D-r |\n| Q49 | A-p, B-q, C-r, D-s |\n| Q50 | 06829 |\n\n## Worked Solutions\n\nS1. Phosphorus ($Z=15$): configuration $1s^2 2s^22p^6 3s^23p^3$. For a 3p electron: same-group (3s,3p) others $=4\\times0.35=1.40$; $n-1$ shell (2s,2p, 8 electrons) $\\times0.85=6.80$; $n-2$ shell (1s, 2 electrons)$\\times1.00=2.00$. Total $\\sigma=1.40+6.80+2.00=10.20$.\n\nS2. Slater $Z_{eff}$: Na $=2.20$, Mg $=2.85$, Al $=3.50$ (each adds 0.65 across the period). Hence $\\text{Na}<\\text{Mg}<\\text{Al}$, option (c).\n\nS3. For V ($Z=23$, $3d^34s^2$): 3d electron \u2014 same-group others $2\\times0.35=0.70$, plus the 18 electrons of shells 1\u20132 (all to the left of 3d) $\\times1.00=18.00$; $\\sigma=18.70$, $Z_{eff}=23-18.70=4.30$. 4s electron $Z_{eff}=3.30$ similarly. Since the 3d electron is more tightly held (higher $Z_{eff}$), the atom preferentially retains 3d and loses 4s electrons first; option (a).\n\nS4. Ge ($Z=32$): configuration core $1s^22s^22p^63s^23p^63d^{10}$ (28 electrons) $+4s^24p^2$. For 4p: same group other electrons $=3\\times0.35=1.05$; $n-1$ shell (3s,3p,3d $=18$) $\\times0.85=15.30$; $n-2$ and below (10) $\\times1.00=10.00$. $\\sigma=26.35$, $Z_{eff}=32-26.35=5.65$.\n\nS5. Ar ($Z=18$, 3p): $\\sigma=11.25$, $Z_{eff}=6.75$. $\\text{Ca}^{2+}$ (18 electrons, same shielding structure, $Z=20$): $\\sigma=11.25$, $Z_{eff}=8.75$. Ratio $=8.75/6.75\\approx1.30$.\n\nS6. Br ($Z=35$) 4p: $Z_{eff}=7.60$. Se ($Z=34$) 4p: $Z_{eff}=6.95$. Difference $=0.65$, consistent with the standard 0.65 per-step increase across a p-block period.\n\nS7. Across Ce, Eu, Gd, Lu, each additional 4f electron adds $+1$ to $Z$ but only $+0.35$ to same-group shielding, giving a net $+0.65$ per element; hence $Z_{eff}$ rises steadily: Ce 12.00 < Eu 14.90 < Gd 15.90 < Lu 20.45. Lu is highest.\n\nS8. Mn ($Z=25$): 3d electron $\\sigma=19.40$, $Z_{eff}=5.60$; 4s electron $\\sigma=21.40$, $Z_{eff}=3.60$. The 3d electron, having higher $Z_{eff}$, is held more tightly; option (a).\n\nS9. Slater's rule treats every intervening $(n-1)d^{10}$/$(n-2)f^{14}$ electron as a \"normal\" $n-1$ shielder (0.85 each), so it wrongly predicts identical $Z_{eff}$ for Ga, In, Tl. In reality d/f electrons shield poorly, so actual $Z_{eff}$ (and $IE_1$) increases from Al to Ga to Tl \u2014 this is a known limitation of the simple model; option (a).\n\nS10. Sn ($Z=50$, configuration $\\ldots4d^{10}5s^25p^2$): same-group (5s,5p) others $=3\\times0.35=1.05$; $n-1$ shell (4s,4p,4d $=18)\\times0.85=15.30$; lower shells (1s,2sp,3sp,3d $=28)\\times1.00=28.00$. $\\sigma=1.05+15.30+28.00=44.35$, so $Z_{eff}=50-44.35=5.65$, matching the parallel 4p (Ge) pattern one period down.\n\nS11. Computed 3d $Z_{eff}$ values: $\\text{Cr}^{3+}=5.30$, $\\text{Mn}^{2+}=5.60$, $\\text{Fe}^{3+}=6.60$, $\\text{Co}^{2+}=6.90$. The highest is $\\text{Co}^{2+}$.\n\nS12. Both ions have a $3d^{10}$ configuration with no 4s electrons, so their shielding-group composition (core $+3d^{10}$) is identical; only $Z$ differs (30 vs 29). Since $\\sigma$ is unchanged, $Z_{eff}$ differs by exactly the difference in $Z$, i.e., 1.00; option (a).\n\nS13. (a) True (1s group uses 0.30). (b) False \u2014 for a target d/f electron, groups to the left are assigned 1.00, not 0.85 (the 0.85 rule is only for an s/p target's $n-1$ shell). (c) True. (d) True.\n\nS14. For Zn: $Z_{eff}(3d)=8.85$ (a, true), $Z_{eff}(4s)=4.35$ (b, true), $\\sigma(3d)=30-8.85=21.15$ (c, true), $\\sigma(4s)=30-4.35=25.65\\neq21.15$ (d, false).\n\nS15. Each step adds one proton within the same shielding-group structure, so $Z_{eff}$ rises steadily (a, true) with constant $\\sigma=4.15$ (b, true). Ne is fourth in the series, not smallest \u2014 $\\text{N}^{3-}$ is smallest (c, false). Higher charge/$Z_{eff}$ in an isoelectronic series correlates with smaller radius, so $\\text{Al}^{3+}<\\text{Mg}^{2+}$ (d, true).\n\nS16. (a) True, a genuine, well-documented limitation. (b) False \u2014 Slater's rule is a simple additive screening scheme; it does not model electron correlation. (c) True \u2014 it predates SCF/Hartree\u2013Fock methods. (d) True, by construction of the $(ns,np)$ group.\n\nS17. Because the shielding-group structure (count of same-group, \"$n-1$\", and lower-shell electrons) repeats identically for corresponding elements one, two, and three periods down a d-block group, Slater's simple rule gives matching $Z_{eff}$: Sc/Y both 3.00, Zr/Hf both 3.65, and Cu with both Ag and Au at 7.85 (all d10 s1 configurations). All four statements are correct.\n\nS18. (a) True (removing 6s/5d, which are \"outside\" 4f in Slater's ordering, leaves the 4f shielding calculation unchanged). (b) True ($14.90<15.25$). (c) False \u2014 $\\sigma(\\text{Lu})=71-20.45=50.55$ is actually LARGER than $\\sigma(\\text{Ce})=58-12.00=46.00$, due to 13 extra same-group 4f electrons ($13\\times0.35=4.55$). (d) True ($15.90<20.45$).\n\nS19. Values: Na 2.20, Mg 2.85, Al 3.50, Si 4.15, P 4.80, S 5.45, Cl 6.10, Ar 6.75 \u2014 each step adds 0.65; option (b).\n\nS20. All six species share the identical $3s^23p^6$ over an $1s^22s^22p^6$ core, so $\\sigma=11.25$ throughout; only $Z$ changes; option (c).\n\nS21. $\\text{Ca}^{2+}$: $Z=20$, $\\sigma=11.25$, so $Z_{eff}=20-11.25=8.75$; option (c).\n\nS22. Because 3d electrons have a higher Slater $Z_{eff}$ (are more tightly bound) than 4s electrons in the same neutral atom, the 4s electron is lost first on ionisation; option (b).\n\nS23. Zn: $Z_{eff}(3d)=8.85$, $Z_{eff}(4s)=4.35$; difference $=4.50$; option (c).\n\nS24. The 3d group (n=3) lies at the same principal shell as the atom's 3s,3p core, which is \"$n-1$\" relative to the 4s target, so each 3d electron shields a 4s electron by 0.85. Conversely, since 4s lies \"after\" 3d in Slater's sequence, a 4s electron contributes zero shielding to a 3d electron; option (a).\n\nS25. Se ($Z=34$): core $1s^22s^22p^6$ (10 electrons, \"$n-2$\" or lower relative to $n=4$) contribute 1.00 each; the $3s^23p^63d^{10}$ (18 electrons, \"$n-1$\" shell) contribute 0.85 each; same-group (4s,4p) electrons contribute 0.35 each. The count contributing exactly 1.00 is 10.\n\nS26. Ca ($Z=20$, 4s electron): the $n-1$ shell is $3s^23p^6$ (8 electrons), each contributing 0.85. Answer: 8.\n\nS27. Fe ($Z=26$, 3d electron): groups to the left of 3d are $1s^2,2s^22p^6,3s^23p^6$, totalling 18 electrons, each contributing 1.00 (d-electron shielding has no 0.85 category). Answer: 18.\n\nS28. Values: Al 3.50, Si 4.15, P 4.80, S 5.45, Cl 6.10, Ar 6.75. Those exceeding 5.00: S, Cl, Ar. Answer: 3.\n\nS29. Differences $Z_{eff}(3d)-Z_{eff}(4s)$: Sc 0.00, Ti 0.50, V 1.00, Cr 1.65, Mn 2.00, Fe 2.50, Co 3.00, Ni 3.50, Cu 4.15, Zn 4.50. Elements with difference $\\geq3.00$: Co, Ni, Cu, Zn. Answer: 4.\n\nS30. $Z_{eff}$ values: $\\text{Cl}^-=5.75$, Ar$=6.75$, $\\text{K}^+=7.75$, $\\text{Ca}^{2+}=8.75$, $\\text{Sc}^{3+}=9.75$, $\\text{Ti}^{4+}=10.75$. Those exceeding 8.00: $\\text{Ca}^{2+}, \\text{Sc}^{3+}, \\text{Ti}^{4+}$. Answer: 3.\n\nS31. Ce's configuration is $1s^22s^22p^63s^23p^63d^{10}4s^24p^64d^{10}4f^15s^25p^65d^16s^2$. Groups to the left of 4f (each contributing 1.00, no 0.85 category for an f-target) are: $1s^2(2)+2sp(8)+3sp(8)+3d(10)+4sp(8)+4d(10)=46$. Answer: 46.\n\nS32. Cr ($3d^54s^1$, not $3d^44s^2$) and Cu ($3d^{10}4s^1$, not $3d^94s^2$) deviate from the simple pattern due to extra stability of half-filled/completely-filled d-subshells. Answer: 2.\n\nS33. Ni ($Z=28$, config $\\ldots3d^84s^2$): same-group 3d others $=7\\times0.35=2.45$; left-of-3d groups (18)$\\times1.00=18.00$. $\\sigma=20.45$, $Z_{eff}=28-20.45=7.55$.\n\nS34. As ($Z=33$, configuration $\\ldots3d^{10}4s^24p^3$): same-group (4s,4p) others $=4\\times0.35=1.40$; $n-1$ shell (3s,3p,3d $=18)\\times0.85=15.30$; lower shells (1s,2sp $=10)\\times1.00=10.00$. $\\sigma=1.40+15.30+10.00=26.70$, so $Z_{eff}=33-26.70=6.30$.\n\nS35. $\\text{Mn}^{2+}$ removes the two 4s electrons of Mn, leaving $3d^5$ \u2014 identical d-electron count to neutral Mn. Since 4s does not shield 3d at all, $Z_{eff}(3d)$ is unchanged: $5.60$.\n\nS36. Eu ($Z=63$, $4f^76s^2$); $\\text{Eu}^{3+}$ removes 6s$^2$ and one 4f electron, leaving $4f^6$. Same-group others $=5\\times0.35=1.75$. In Slater's sequence, 5s and 5p come AFTER 4f, so they do not shield it; only groups through 4d (1s,2sp,3sp,3d,4sp,4d $=46$ electrons) count, each at 1.00. $\\sigma=1.75+46.00=47.75$, so $Z_{eff}=63-47.75=15.25$.\n\nS37. Co ($Z=27$): $Z_{eff}(3d)=6.90$, $Z_{eff}(4s)=3.90$. Difference $=3.00$.\n\nS38. S ($Z=16$) with two extra 3p electrons gives $3s^23p^6$ (18 electrons total, isoelectronic with Ar's core). Same-group others $=7\\times0.35=2.45$; $n-1$ shell (8)$\\times0.85=6.80$; lower shell (2)$\\times1.00=2.00$. $\\sigma=11.25$, $Z_{eff}=16-11.25=4.75$.\n\nS39. Ta ($Z=73$, $\\ldots5d^36s^2$): same-group 5d others $=2\\times0.35=0.70$; all groups to the left (through 4f, totalling 68 electrons)$\\times1.00=68.00$. $\\sigma=68.70$, $Z_{eff}=73-68.70=4.30$.\n\nS40. $Z_{eff}(\\text{F},2p)=5.20>Z_{eff}(\\text{O},2p)=4.55$, and the reason correctly states the mechanism (one more proton, only 0.35 extra shielding, net +0.65). Both true, R explains A; option (a).\n\nS41. A is true \u2014 $Z_{eff}\\approx2.20$ for Na, K, Rb, Cs alike. But R is false: inner filled shells contribute 0.85 ($n-1$) or 1.00 ($n-2$ and below), never 0.35 (0.35 applies only to electrons in the SAME group as the target); option (c).\n\nS42. Both statements are independently true, but R describes a real-world FAILURE of Slater's rule (poor real shielding by d/f electrons), which is not the reason Slater's own arithmetic gives identical 5.00 values (that arithmetic coincidence follows from identical group compositions); so R does not explain A; option (b).\n\nS43. $\\sigma(3d)=29-7.85=21.15$ is actually SMALLER than $\\sigma(4s)=29-3.70=25.30$, so A is false. R correctly states the general Slater coefficients (1.00 for d/f-target vs 0.85 for the $n-1$ shell of an s/p target); option (d).\n\nS44. Values 5.75, 6.75, 7.75, 8.75 confirm the steady increase (A true), and $\\sigma=11.25$ is identical throughout (R true and explains A); option (a).\n\nS45. Both facts are true, but Mg/Ca's chemical reactivity with water has no bearing on why their Slater $Z_{eff}$ values numerically coincide (that coincidence follows purely from matching shielding-group structure); option (b).\n\nS46. Ti 3d $=3.65$ (q), Ti 4s $=3.15$ (p), Cr 3d $=4.60$ (r), Ge 4p $=5.65$ (s).\n\nS47. Al 3p: only the 1s$^2$ core (2 electrons) lies two shells below (p). Br 4p: the $1s^22s^22p^6$ core (10 electrons) lies two-or-more shells below (q). Fe 3d: all 18 electrons of shells 1 and 2 lie to the left (r). Ce 4f: 46 electrons lie to the left, as computed in S31 (s).\n\nS48. $\\text{Mn}^{2+}$ 3d $=5.60$ (p), $\\text{Cu}^{2+}$ 3d $=8.20$ (q), Zr 4d $=3.65$ (r), Hf 5d $=3.65$ (r) \u2014 Zr and Hf share the identical shielding-group structure and hence identical Slater $Z_{eff}$, foreshadowing the lanthanide-contraction-driven similarity in their real atomic radii.\n\nS49. A \u2013 p (0.65 steps across period 3); B \u2013 q (constant down group 1); C \u2013 r (O 4.55 $-$ N 3.90 $=0.65$); D \u2013 s (1s shielding coefficient is 0.30, not 0.35).\n\nS50. Clue 1 (Sc, 3d) $=3.00\\to$ digit 0. Clue 2 (Br, 4p)$=7.60\\to$ digit 6. Clue 3 (Cu, 3d)$=7.85\\to$ digit 8. Clue 4 (F, 2p)$=5.20\\to$ digit 2. Clue 5 (Gd, 4f)$=15.90\\to$ digit 9. Code: 06829.\n";
const RAW_MD_MIXED_NEW = "## Single Correct (SCQ)\n\nQ1. Which of the following is NOT typically cited as a consequence of the lithium\u2013magnesium diagonal relationship?\n\n(a) Both $\\text{Li}_2\\text{CO}_3$ and $\\text{MgCO}_3$ decompose on heating to the oxide and $\\text{CO}_2$, while $\\text{Na}_2\\text{CO}_3$ is thermally stable\n\n(b) $\\text{LiCl}$ and $\\text{MgCl}_2$ are both appreciably soluble in organic solvents such as ethanol, reflecting covalent character\n\n(c) Both Li and Mg form a stable, well-characterised peroxide ($\\text{Li}_2\\text{O}_2$ and $\\text{MgO}_2$) as their principal product of combustion in excess oxygen\n\n(d) Both Li and Mg react directly with $\\text{N}_2$ to form a nitride\n\nQ2. $\\text{Be}^{2+}$ (ionic radius $\\approx31$ pm) and $\\text{Al}^{3+}$ (ionic radius $\\approx53$ pm) show comparable polarising power ($\\text{charge}/\\text{radius}$), which underlies their diagonal relationship. Which single factor is MOST responsible for this?\n\n(a) $\\text{Be}^{2+}$ has a much smaller radius than $\\text{Al}^{3+}$ despite its lower charge, so the two roughly compensating factors give a similar charge/radius ratio\n\n(b) $\\text{Be}^{2+}$ and $\\text{Al}^{3+}$ have identical Slater $Z_{eff}$\n\n(c) Be and Al belong to the same group of the periodic table\n\n(d) $\\text{Be}^{2+}$ and $\\text{Al}^{3+}$ have the same electronic configuration as their parent atoms\n\nQ3. In aqueous acidic solution, $\\text{Sn}^{2+}$ is a good reducing agent (readily oxidised to $\\text{Sn}^{4+}$), whereas $\\text{Tl}^+$ is comparatively stable and resists oxidation to $\\text{Tl}^{3+}$. This contrast between group-14 Sn and group-13 Tl reflects:\n\n(a) the inert-pair effect strengthens more sharply down group 13 than down group 14, so the $+1$ state becomes thermodynamically favoured for Tl, while for Sn the $+2$ state remains less stable than $+4$\n\n(b) Sn and Tl have identical first ionisation enthalpies\n\n(c) $\\text{Tl}^+$ is in fact a stronger reducing agent than $\\text{Sn}^{2+}$\n\n(d) the inert-pair effect occurs only in group 13, never in group 14\n\nQ4. Chromium forms three well-known oxides, CrO, $\\text{Cr}_2\\text{O}_3$ and $\\text{CrO}_3$, corresponding to oxidation states $+2$, $+3$ and $+6$. The correct order of increasing acidic character is:\n\n(a) $\\text{CrO}<\\text{Cr}_2\\text{O}_3<\\text{CrO}_3$\n\n(b) $\\text{CrO}_3<\\text{Cr}_2\\text{O}_3<\\text{CrO}$\n\n(c) $\\text{Cr}_2\\text{O}_3<\\text{CrO}<\\text{CrO}_3$\n\n(d) $\\text{CrO}_3<\\text{CrO}<\\text{Cr}_2\\text{O}_3$\n\nQ5. Which of the following pairs is correctly matched with the ion having the LARGER magnitude of hydration enthalpy?\n\n(a) $\\text{Na}^+$ vs $\\text{Cs}^+$ $\\to$ $\\text{Cs}^+$\n\n(b) $\\text{Mg}^{2+}$ vs $\\text{Ba}^{2+}$ $\\to$ $\\text{Ba}^{2+}$\n\n(c) $\\text{F}^-$ vs $\\text{I}^-$ $\\to$ $\\text{F}^-$\n\n(d) $\\text{Al}^{3+}$ vs $\\text{Mg}^{2+}$ $\\to$ $\\text{Mg}^{2+}$\n\nQ6. Given that lattice enthalpy magnitude increases with the product of ionic charges and decreases with inter-ionic distance, the correct INCREASING order of lattice enthalpy magnitude for CaO, KCl and $\\text{CaF}_2$ is:\n\n(a) $\\text{KCl}<\\text{CaF}_2<\\text{CaO}$\n\n(b) $\\text{CaO}<\\text{CaF}_2<\\text{KCl}$\n\n(c) $\\text{CaF}_2<\\text{KCl}<\\text{CaO}$\n\n(d) $\\text{KCl}<\\text{CaO}<\\text{CaF}_2$\n\nQ7. $IE_1$ values (kJ/mol) are B $=801$, Al $=577$, Ga $=579$. Although Ga lies below Al with an extra shell, its $IE_1$ nearly equals that of Al rather than continuing the expected decrease. This anomaly is best explained by:\n\n(a) poor shielding of Ga's 4p electron by the intervening $3d^{10}$ electrons, which keeps its effective nuclear charge close to that of Al\n\n(b) Ga having a smaller atomic radius than boron\n\n(c) Ga possessing no p electrons in its valence shell\n\n(d) relativistic effects, which are significant only for element Ga\n\nQ8. Among the group-16 elements, the magnitude of first electron gain enthalpy follows $\\text{S}>\\text{Se}>\\text{O}$. The anomalously LOW value for oxygen (compared to sulfur) is best attributed to:\n\n(a) oxygen's small atomic size, causing strong inter-electronic repulsion in the compact 2p subshell when the extra electron is added\n\n(b) oxygen having a higher first ionisation enthalpy than sulfur\n\n(c) oxygen's larger atomic radius compared to sulfur\n\n(d) sulfur's smaller atomic radius compared to oxygen\n\nQ9. An element X has a very high $IE_1$, a small atomic radius, and forms an oxide that acts as a strong acid anhydride in water. Which region of the periodic table does X most likely belong to, and what is the probable nature of its chloride?\n\n(a) the upper-right region (near F/O); a covalent, volatile chloride that hydrolyses in water\n\n(b) the lower-left region (near Cs/Fr); an ionic, non-hydrolysing chloride\n\n(c) the middle of the transition block; a coloured, paramagnetic chloride\n\n(d) the noble-gas block; X does not form a chloride at all\n\nQ10. An element shows successive ionisation enthalpies (kJ/mol) $IE_1=590$, $IE_2=1145$, $IE_3=4912$, $IE_4=6474$. The huge jump between $IE_2$ and $IE_3$ shows the element's stable oxidation state is $+2$; this pattern, together with a Slater-rule $Z_{eff}$ that is much higher for the argon-like core than for the outermost $ns^2$ electrons, corresponds most closely to which real element?\n\n(a) Ca\n\n(b) Al\n\n(c) Na\n\n(d) Cl\n\nQ11. Silver halides show a distinct solubility trend: AgF is water-soluble, while AgCl, AgBr and AgI are progressively less soluble (AgI is virtually insoluble). Using Fajans' rules together with the lattice-versus-hydration-enthalpy balance, the very low solubility of AgI is best explained by:\n\n(a) $\\text{I}^-$ is large and highly polarisable, giving AgI substantial covalent character and a lattice enthalpy that the hydration enthalpy cannot overcome\n\n(b) $\\text{I}^-$ has the largest hydration enthalpy among the halide ions\n\n(c) $\\text{Ag}^+$ is a poor polarising cation\n\n(d) AgI has the smallest lattice enthalpy among the silver halides\n\nQ12. Which of the following correctly pairs a period-2 \"anomalous\" property with its structural cause?\n\n(a) $\\text{N}_2$ is far less reactive than $\\text{P}_4$ because the very strong, short $\\text{N}{\\equiv}\\text{N}$ triple bond far exceeds the strength of the single P\u2013P bonds in $\\text{P}_4$\n\n(b) $\\text{O}_2$ is a stronger oxidising agent than $\\text{F}_2$\n\n(c) $\\text{B}_2\\text{H}_6$ and $\\text{AlCl}_3$ share exactly the same bonding mechanism in their bridged dimeric structures\n\n(d) Be does not form any covalent compounds\n\n## Multiple Correct (MCQ)\n\n(One or more options may be correct.)\n\nQ13. Which of the following statements about a Born\u2013Haber cycle are CORRECT?\n\n(a) The lattice enthalpy of formation is released as $MX(s)$ forms from gaseous ions, and so carries a negative sign by convention\n\n(b) Sublimation enthalpy and ionisation enthalpy are always endothermic (positive)\n\n(c) First electron gain enthalpy is always exothermic (negative) for every element\n\n(d) A Born\u2013Haber cycle is a direct application of Hess's law\n\nQ14. Which of the following statements about hydration enthalpy and ionic radius are CORRECT?\n\n(a) Hydration enthalpy magnitude increases with decreasing ionic radius for ions of the same charge\n\n(b) $\\text{Li}^+$ has a larger hydrated radius than $\\text{Cs}^+$, despite having a much smaller bare ionic radius\n\n(c) Hydration enthalpy magnitude increases with increasing ionic charge for ions of similar radius\n\n(d) $\\text{F}^-$ has a smaller hydration enthalpy magnitude than $\\text{Cl}^-$\n\nQ15. Regarding the inert-pair effect and oxidation-state stability, which statements are CORRECT?\n\n(a) $\\text{PbO}_2$ is a stronger oxidising agent than $\\text{SnO}_2$\n\n(b) $\\text{Tl}_2\\text{O}_3$ is a stronger oxidising agent than $\\text{Tl}_2\\text{O}$\n\n(c) Bi(V) compounds such as $\\text{NaBiO}_3$ are strong oxidising agents\n\n(d) GeO is more thermodynamically stable than $\\text{GeO}_2$\n\nQ16. Which of the following statements about chemical periodicity and oxide/oxoacid character are CORRECT?\n\n(a) Both $\\text{Al}_2\\text{O}_3$ and ZnO are amphoteric oxides\n\n(b) $\\text{H}_2\\text{SO}_4$ is a stronger acid than $\\text{H}_2\\text{SO}_3$ because sulfur is present in a higher oxidation state with more oxo groups\n\n(c) $\\text{HClO}_4$ is a stronger acid than HClO\n\n(d) An aqueous solution of $\\text{NaHCO}_3$ is acidic\n\nQ17. Which of the following statements about diagonal relationships and anomalous period-2 behaviour are CORRECT?\n\n(a) $\\text{Be(OH)}_2$ is amphoteric, like $\\text{Al(OH)}_3$, unlike $\\text{Mg(OH)}_2$, which is only basic\n\n(b) $\\text{BeCl}_2$ exists as a covalent, bridged/polymeric structure, similar in character to $\\text{AlCl}_3$, unlike ionic $\\text{MgCl}_2$\n\n(c) $\\text{B}_2\\text{O}_3$ is acidic, similar to $\\text{CO}_2$/$\\text{SiO}_2$, unlike the strongly basic $\\text{Na}_2\\text{O}$\n\n(d) Lithium salts are generally MORE soluble in water than the corresponding sodium salts\n\nQ18. Regarding the isoelectronic series $\\text{Cl}^-$, Ar, $\\text{K}^+$, which statements are CORRECT?\n\n(a) The radius decreases in the order $\\text{Cl}^->\\text{Ar}>\\text{K}^+$\n\n(b) Increasing $Z_{eff}$ across this isoelectronic series is accompanied by a decreasing radius\n\n(c) $\\text{K}^+$ has a larger radius than $\\text{Cl}^-$ simply because potassium has a higher atomic number than chlorine\n\n(d) The electron-attracting power (effective electronegativity) of the isoelectronic cation increases with increasing positive charge\n\n## Paragraph / Comprehension\n\nConsider the formation of solid strontium chloride, $\\text{SrCl}_2(s)$, analysed through a Born\u2013Haber cycle. Given: enthalpy of formation $\\Delta H_f(\\text{SrCl}_2,s)=-828.4$ kJ/mol; sublimation enthalpy of $\\text{Sr}(s)=164.4$ kJ/mol; $IE_1+IE_2$ of Sr $=1614$ kJ/mol; dissociation enthalpy required to produce 2 mol Cl(g) from $\\text{Cl}_2(g)$, i.e. $D(\\text{Cl}_2)=242.0$ kJ/mol; electron gain enthalpy of Cl $=-349.0$ kJ/mol per atom. The lattice enthalpy of formation, $U$, is the only unknown, to be found using Hess's law around the complete cycle.\n\nQ19. Using Hess's law, the lattice enthalpy of formation $U$ of $\\text{SrCl}_2(s)$ is closest to:\n\n(a) $-1850.8$ kJ/mol\n\n(b) $-2150.8$ kJ/mol\n\n(c) $-2450.8$ kJ/mol\n\n(d) $-1950.8$ kJ/mol\n\nQ20. If the hydration enthalpies of $\\text{Sr}^{2+}$ and $\\text{Cl}^-$ are $-1443$ kJ/mol and $-381$ kJ/mol respectively, the enthalpy of solution of $\\text{SrCl}_2(s)$, using $\\Delta H_{sol}=-U+\\Sigma\\Delta H_{hyd}$, is:\n\n(a) $-54.2$ kJ/mol\n\n(b) $+54.2$ kJ/mol\n\n(c) $-1204.2$ kJ/mol\n\n(d) $+2150.8$ kJ/mol\n\nQ21. Which statement correctly interprets the sign and magnitude found in Q20?\n\n(a) The small negative $\\Delta H_{sol}$ indicates a mildly exothermic dissolution, consistent with $\\text{SrCl}_2$ being freely soluble in water, since the lattice enthalpy is comfortably offset by the combined hydration enthalpies\n\n(b) The value proves that $\\text{SrCl}_2$ is insoluble in water\n\n(c) A positive $\\Delta H_{sol}$ would show that dissolution is endothermic and thermodynamically impossible\n\n(d) $\\Delta H_{sol}$ has no bearing on the solubility of a salt\n\nNitrogen forms a well-known series of oxides spanning oxidation states $+1$ to $+5$: $\\text{N}_2\\text{O}$, NO, $\\text{N}_2\\text{O}_3$, $\\text{NO}_2$, $\\text{N}_2\\text{O}_5$. As nitrogen's oxidation state increases across this series, the N\u2013O bonding becomes progressively more covalent/acidic, and the corresponding oxoacid (where one exists) becomes a stronger acid. In parallel, silver halides AgF, AgCl, AgBr, AgI show progressively increasing covalent character (an increasingly unfavourable lattice-versus-hydration balance) as the halide ion becomes larger and more polarisable, per Fajans' rules.\n\nQ22. Which nitrogen oxide corresponds to the strongest acid anhydride (i.e., forms the strongest common oxoacid) among those listed?\n\n(a) $\\text{N}_2\\text{O}$\n\n(b) NO\n\n(c) $\\text{N}_2\\text{O}_3$\n\n(d) $\\text{N}_2\\text{O}_5$\n\nQ23. Which of the following correctly ranks the silver halides in order of DECREASING water solubility?\n\n(a) $\\text{AgF}>\\text{AgCl}>\\text{AgBr}>\\text{AgI}$\n\n(b) $\\text{AgI}>\\text{AgBr}>\\text{AgCl}>\\text{AgF}$\n\n(c) $\\text{AgCl}>\\text{AgF}>\\text{AgI}>\\text{AgBr}$\n\n(d) All four silver halides are equally soluble\n\nQ24. The trend in silver halide solubility described above is best rationalised using which single concept?\n\n(a) Fajans' rules \u2014 increasing anion size/polarisability increases covalent character, so lattice enthalpy increasingly dominates over hydration enthalpy, reducing solubility\n\n(b) increasing atomic number of the halogen always increases ionic character\n\n(c) $\\text{Ag}^+$ becomes progressively less polarising down the halide series\n\n(d) the hydration enthalpy of the halide ion increases steadily down the group, driving higher solubility\n\n## Integer Type\n\nQ25. The successive ionisation enthalpies of aluminium (kJ/mol) are $IE_1=577$, $IE_2=1817$, $IE_3=2745$, $IE_4=11577$. The giant jump after the third ionisation reveals the number of valence electrons available for removal before the next inner shell is breached. State this number.\n\nQ26. Standard first electron gain enthalpy data (kJ/mol) are: He $+48$, Ne $+116$, Ar $+96$, Kr $+96$, Xe $+77$; Be $+240$, Mg $+230$, Ca $-2.37$, Sr $-5.03$, Ba $-13.95$. Among these ten elements, find the number having a positive (endothermic) first electron gain enthalpy.\n\nQ27. Among the pairs (Li, Mg), (Be, Al), (B, Si), (C, P) and (Na, Ca), find the number of pairs that represent a genuine, textbook diagonal relationship.\n\nQ28. Among the oxides CaO, $\\text{Al}_2\\text{O}_3$, $\\text{SiO}_2$, $\\text{P}_4\\text{O}_{10}$, $\\text{SO}_3$ and $\\text{Cl}_2\\text{O}_7$, find the number of oxides that are acidic (excluding basic and amphoteric oxides).\n\nQ29. For the formation of $\\text{Na}_2\\text{S}(s)$: $\\Delta H_f=-370$ kJ/mol; sublimation enthalpy of Na $=109$ kJ/mol (per mole Na, needed twice); $IE_1(\\text{Na})=496$ kJ/mol (needed twice); sublimation/atomisation enthalpy of S $=277$ kJ/mol (per mole S atoms); $\\Delta_{eg}H_1(\\text{S})=-200$ kJ/mol; $\\Delta_{eg}H_2(\\text{S})=+590$ kJ/mol. Calculate the magnitude of the lattice enthalpy of formation of $\\text{Na}_2\\text{S}(s)$, in kJ/mol, to the nearest integer.\n\nQ30. Given hydration enthalpies (kJ/mol): $\\text{Na}^+=-406$, $\\text{Mg}^{2+}=-1921$, $\\text{Al}^{3+}=-4665$, $\\text{K}^+=-322$, $\\text{Ca}^{2+}=-1577$. Find the number of these cations whose hydration enthalpy magnitude exceeds 1900 kJ/mol.\n\nQ31. Given approximate ionic radii (pm) for the isoelectronic 10-electron series: $\\text{N}^{3-}=171$, $\\text{O}^{2-}=140$, $\\text{F}^-=136$, $\\text{Na}^+=95$, $\\text{Mg}^{2+}=65$, $\\text{Al}^{3+}=50$. Find the number of these six species whose radius is smaller than that of $\\text{Na}^+$.\n\nQ32. Among the species $\\text{Tl}^+$, $\\text{Pb}^{2+}$, $\\text{Bi}^{3+}$, $\\text{Sn}^{2+}$ and $\\text{Ge}^{2+}$, find the number that represent the oxidation state made THERMODYNAMICALLY MORE STABLE by the inert-pair effect (i.e., more stable than the corresponding higher oxidation state of the same element).\n\n## Numerical Response\n\n(Report each answer correct to two decimal places.)\n\nQ33. Two elements have electronegativities $\\chi_A=1.9$ and $\\chi_B=3.2$. Using the Hannay\u2013Smith formula, $\\%\\text{ionic character}=16|\\Delta\\chi|+3.5(\\Delta\\chi)^2$, calculate the percentage ionic character of the A\u2013B bond.\n\nQ34. Bond dissociation energies are $E_{A-A}=170$ kJ/mol, $E_{B-B}=100$ kJ/mol, $E_{A-B}=205$ kJ/mol, and $\\chi_B=2.30$. Using the Pauling relation $\\chi_A-\\chi_B=0.102\\sqrt{\\Delta}$, where $\\Delta=E_{A-B}-\\sqrt{E_{A-A}\\times E_{B-B}}$, calculate $\\chi_A$.\n\nQ35. Given ionic radii $r(\\text{Na}^+)=102$ pm and $r(\\text{Al}^{3+})=53$ pm, and using $|\\Delta H_{hyd}|\\propto z^2/r$, calculate the ratio $|\\Delta H_{hyd}(\\text{Al}^{3+})| : |\\Delta H_{hyd}(\\text{Na}^+)|$.\n\nQ36. For the formation of KI(s): $\\Delta H_f=-327.9$ kJ/mol; sublimation enthalpy of K $=89.2$ kJ/mol; $IE_1(\\text{K})=418.8$ kJ/mol; atomisation enthalpy of $\\text{I}_2$ to 2I(g), per mole I atoms, $=106.8$ kJ/mol; $\\Delta_{eg}H(\\text{I})=-295.2$ kJ/mol. Calculate the magnitude of the lattice enthalpy of KI(s), in kJ/mol.\n\nQ37. Using the Schomaker\u2013Stevenson relation $d_{A-B}=r_A+r_B-9\\Delta\\chi$ (in pm), calculate the Si\u2013Cl bond length given $r_{Si}=117$ pm, $r_{Cl}=99$ pm, $\\chi_{Si}=1.90$ and $\\chi_{Cl}=3.16$.\n\nQ38. Using the Allred\u2013Rochow formula $\\chi_{AR}=0.359\\dfrac{Z_{eff}}{r^2}+0.744$ (with $r$ in angstrom), calculate the electronegativity of sulfur given its Slater $Z_{eff}=5.45$ (for the 3p electron) and covalent radius $r=1.04$ \u00c5.\n\nQ39. For the formation of $\\text{CaBr}_2(s)$: $\\Delta H_f=-682.8$ kJ/mol; sublimation enthalpy of Ca $=177.8$ kJ/mol; $IE_1+IE_2$ of Ca $=1735.2$ kJ/mol; atomisation enthalpy of $\\text{Br}_2(l)$ to 2Br(g) $=224.7$ kJ/mol; lattice enthalpy of formation $U=-1984.65$ kJ/mol. Calculate the magnitude of the electron gain enthalpy of Br, in kJ/mol per atom.\n\n## Assertion\u2013Reason (A/R)\n\nEach question below has an Assertion (A) and a Reason (R). Choose: (a) if both A and R are true and R is the correct explanation of A; (b) if both A and R are true but R is NOT the correct explanation of A; (c) if A is true but R is false; (d) if A is false but R is true.\n\nQ40. Assertion (A): MgO has a much higher lattice enthalpy than NaCl.\n\nReason (R): MgO involves ions of charge $+2/-2$ at a smaller inter-ionic distance than the $+1/-1$ ions of NaCl, and lattice enthalpy increases with the product of ionic charges while decreasing with inter-ionic distance.\n\nQ41. Assertion (A): Ionic radius decreases in the isoelectronic series $\\text{N}^{3-}>\\text{O}^{2-}>\\text{F}^->\\text{Na}^+>\\text{Mg}^{2+}>\\text{Al}^{3+}$.\n\nReason (R): This happens because all these species have the same number of protons but a different number of electrons.\n\nQ42. Assertion (A): $\\text{LiCl}$ is appreciably soluble in organic solvents such as ethanol and acetone, a behaviour more typical of covalent compounds.\n\nReason (R): Lithium is the first member of the alkali metal group and has the lowest atomic mass among the alkali metals.\n\nQ43. Assertion (A): The lattice enthalpy of $\\text{CaF}_2$ is smaller in magnitude than that of KCl.\n\nReason (R): Lattice enthalpy increases with an increasing product of ionic charges and decreases with increasing inter-ionic distance.\n\nQ44. Assertion (A): Among the group-2 hydration enthalpies, $|\\Delta H_{hyd}(\\text{Be}^{2+})|>|\\Delta H_{hyd}(\\text{Mg}^{2+})|>|\\Delta H_{hyd}(\\text{Ca}^{2+})|>|\\Delta H_{hyd}(\\text{Sr}^{2+})|>|\\Delta H_{hyd}(\\text{Ba}^{2+})|$.\n\nReason (R): Hydration enthalpy magnitude increases as ionic radius decreases for ions of the same charge, and ionic radius increases down group 2.\n\nQ45. Assertion (A): $\\text{SnCl}_2$ and $\\text{PbCl}_2$ are both routinely used as reducing agents in qualitative inorganic chemistry.\n\nReason (R): Both tin and lead belong to group 14 and show the inert-pair effect, which favours the $+2$ oxidation state over the $+4$ state as the group is descended.\n\n## Matrix Match\n\nQ46. Match the oxide/compound in List-I with its acid\u2013base classification in List-II.\n\n| List-I | List-II |\n|---|---|\n| A. $\\text{CrO}_3$ | p. strongly acidic oxide |\n| B. $\\text{Cr}_2\\text{O}_3$ | q. amphoteric oxide |\n| C. CrO | r. basic oxide |\n| D. $\\text{Al}_2\\text{O}_3$ | q. amphoteric oxide |\n\nQ47. Match the cation in List-I with its approximate hydration enthalpy magnitude (kJ/mol) in List-II.\n\n| List-I | List-II |\n|---|---|\n| A. $\\text{Li}^+$ | p. 4665 |\n| B. $\\text{Na}^+$ | q. 1921 |\n| C. $\\text{Mg}^{2+}$ | r. 406 |\n| D. $\\text{Al}^{3+}$ | s. 520 |\n\nQ48. Match the phenomenon in List-I with its correct structural explanation in List-II.\n\n| List-I | List-II |\n|---|---|\n| A. LiF is less soluble in water than NaF | p. inert-pair effect |\n| B. $\\text{BeCl}_2$ is covalent while $\\text{CaCl}_2$ is ionic | q. high lattice enthalpy of the small, highly charged Li$^+$/F$^-$ pair, not compensated by hydration |\n| C. $\\text{Tl}^+$ is more stable than $\\text{Tl}^{3+}$ | r. large charge/size ratio (polarising power) of $\\text{Be}^{2+}$ compared to $\\text{Ca}^{2+}$ |\n| D. $\\text{N}_2$ is far less reactive than $\\text{P}_4$ at room temperature | s. very strong, short $\\text{N}{\\equiv}\\text{N}$ triple bond |\n\nQ49. Match the Born\u2013Haber cycle step in List-I with the type of thermochemical quantity in List-II.\n\n| List-I | List-II |\n|---|---|\n| A. Converting $M(s)$ to $M(g)$ | p. sublimation enthalpy |\n| B. Converting $\\tfrac12X_2(g)$ to $X(g)$ | q. half of the bond dissociation enthalpy |\n| C. Converting $M(g)$ to $M^+(g)$ | r. ionisation enthalpy |\n| D. Converting $X(g)$ to $X^-(g)$ | s. electron gain enthalpy |\n\n## Innovative Pattern\n\nQ50. Who Am I? \u2014 A Periodic Relay. Five clues below, each independently identify one element. Find each element, note its atomic number, and report the SUM of all five atomic numbers as your final answer.\n\nClue A: I am a group-13 element whose $IE_1$ (577 kJ/mol) breaks the smooth decrease expected after boron, and I form an oxide that is amphoteric, dissolving in both acid and NaOH.\n\nClue B: I am a group-14 element for which the $+2$ oxidation state is thermodynamically MORE stable than $+4$ (a dominant inert-pair effect), and I form a monoxide that is amphoteric.\n\nClue C: I am a group-16 element whose first electron gain enthalpy is LESS negative than that of the element directly below me, an anomaly caused by strong electron\u2013electron repulsion in my compact 2p subshell.\n\nClue D: I am an alkaline-earth element that resembles my diagonal partner in group 13 far more than I resemble the other members of my own group, forming a strongly covalent chloride and an amphoteric hydroxide.\n\nClue E: I am the halogen with the largest magnitude of hydration enthalpy among all halide ions, owing to having the smallest ionic radius.\n\n## Answer Key\n\n| Q. No. | Answer |\n|---|---|\n| Q1 | (c) |\n| Q2 | (a) |\n| Q3 | (a) |\n| Q4 | (a) |\n| Q5 | (c) |\n| Q6 | (a) |\n| Q7 | (a) |\n| Q8 | (a) |\n| Q9 | (a) |\n| Q10 | (a) Ca |\n| Q11 | (a) |\n| Q12 | (a) |\n| Q13 | (a), (b), (d) |\n| Q14 | (a), (b), (c) |\n| Q15 | (a), (b), (c) |\n| Q16 | (a), (b), (c) |\n| Q17 | (a), (b), (c) |\n| Q18 | (a), (b), (d) |\n| Q19 | (b) $-2150.8$ kJ/mol |\n| Q20 | (a) $-54.2$ kJ/mol |\n| Q21 | (a) |\n| Q22 | (d) $\\text{N}_2\\text{O}_5$ |\n| Q23 | (a) |\n| Q24 | (a) |\n| Q25 | 3 |\n| Q26 | 7 |\n| Q27 | 3 |\n| Q28 | 4 |\n| Q29 | 2247 |\n| Q30 | 2 |\n| Q31 | 2 |\n| Q32 | 3 |\n| Q33 | 26.72 |\n| Q34 | 3.18 |\n| Q35 | 17.32 |\n| Q36 | 647.50 |\n| Q37 | 204.66 |\n| Q38 | 2.55 |\n| Q39 | 417.93 |\n| Q40 | (a) |\n| Q41 | (c) |\n| Q42 | (b) |\n| Q43 | (d) |\n| Q44 | (a) |\n| Q45 | (d) |\n| Q46 | A-p, B-q, C-r, D-q |\n| Q47 | A-s, B-r, C-q, D-p |\n| Q48 | A-q, B-r, C-p, D-s |\n| Q49 | A-p, B-q, C-r, D-s |\n| Q50 | 116 |\n\n## Worked Solutions\n\nS1. Li and Mg both burn in excess $\\text{O}_2$ to give only the NORMAL oxide ($\\text{Li}_2\\text{O}$, MgO), not a peroxide \u2014 peroxide formation is characteristic of heavier alkali/alkaline-earth metals, not Li or Mg. So (c) is the false statement and is NOT a genuine consequence of the diagonal relationship; (a), (b) and (d) are all real, textbook manifestations of it.\n\nS2. $\\text{Be}^{2+}$'s very small radius (31 pm) compensates for its lower charge (+2 vs +3), giving charge/radius ratios of roughly $2/31\\approx0.065$ for $\\text{Be}^{2+}$ and $3/53\\approx0.057$ for $\\text{Al}^{3+}$ \u2014 comparably high polarising power, which is the direct cause of the Be\u2013Al diagonal similarity (e.g., both give covalent, Fajans-type chlorides).\n\nS3. Down group 13, the inert-pair effect grows sharply (favouring Tl$^+$ over Tl$^{3+}$); down group 14 it is comparatively weaker at Sn, so $\\text{Sn}^{2+}$ remains a reducing agent en route to the more stable $\\text{Sn}^{4+}$. Hence Tl is passivated in the $+1$ state while Sn is not stabilised in the $+2$ state; option (a).\n\nS4. As chromium's oxidation state rises ($+2\\to+3\\to+6$), M\u2013O bonding becomes progressively more covalent and the oxide more acidic: CrO is basic, $\\text{Cr}_2\\text{O}_3$ is amphoteric, $\\text{CrO}_3$ is a strong acid anhydride (gives $\\text{H}_2\\text{CrO}_4$/$\\text{H}_2\\text{Cr}_2\\text{O}_7$). Increasing acidity order: $\\text{CrO}<\\text{Cr}_2\\text{O}_3<\\text{CrO}_3$.\n\nS5. Correct pairings require the smaller ion or the more highly charged ion to have the LARGER hydration enthalpy magnitude: $\\text{Cs}^+<\\text{Na}^+$ (a is wrong), $\\text{Ba}^{2+}<\\text{Mg}^{2+}$ (b is wrong), $\\text{F}^->\\text{I}^-$ since F$^-$ is much smaller (c is correctly matched), $\\text{Mg}^{2+}<\\text{Al}^{3+}$ (d is wrong). Only (c) is correct.\n\nS6. Real approximate lattice enthalpies: KCl ($\\approx717$ kJ/mol, charges $1,1$) $<$ $\\text{CaF}_2$ ($\\approx2651$ kJ/mol, charges $2,1$) $<$ CaO ($\\approx3401$ kJ/mol, charges $2,2$, and a very short inter-ionic distance). Increasing order: $\\text{KCl}<\\text{CaF}_2<\\text{CaO}$.\n\nS7. Slater's rule shows that the $3d^{10}$ electrons inserted between Al and Ga shield the nucleus poorly (they are formally $n-1$ shielders at 0.85, but real d-electrons are far less effective), so Ga's effective nuclear charge stays almost as high as Al's despite the extra shell, nearly cancelling the expected size/IE decrease down the group.\n\nS8. Oxygen's 2p subshell is very compact; adding a further electron to an already crowded, small 2p$^5$ orbital set creates large electron\u2013electron repulsion that partly offsets the favourable nuclear attraction, making $\\Delta_{eg}H_1(\\text{O})$ less negative than sulfur's, whose larger, more diffuse 3p subshell suffers much less repulsion.\n\nS9. High $IE_1$, high electronegativity, small radius and an acidic covalent oxide are all hallmarks of upper-right (electronegative, non-metallic) elements; such elements typically form covalent, low-boiling halides that hydrolyse readily in water (e.g., $\\text{PCl}_3$, $\\text{SiCl}_4$), unlike the ionic, non-hydrolysing halides of electropositive metals.\n\nS10. This is the classic set of calcium ionisation enthalpies: $IE_1=590$, $IE_2=1145$ (both removing the two loosely bound $4s^2$ electrons), followed by a huge jump to $IE_3=4912$ kJ/mol as the next electron must be pulled from the stable, inner argon-like core (Slater $Z_{eff}$ for that core is far higher than for the outer 4s electrons). This matches Ca; option (a).\n\nS11. Iodide is the largest, most polarisable halide ion; by Fajans' rules this gives AgI substantial covalent character, raising its lattice enthalpy (relative to a purely ionic estimate) to the point where it exceeds what hydration enthalpy can overcome, making AgI essentially insoluble.\n\nS12. The N\u2261N triple bond (bond enthalpy $\\approx945$ kJ/mol, bond length $\\approx110$ pm) is exceptionally strong and short, making $\\text{N}_2$ kinetically and thermodynamically far less reactive than $\\text{P}_4$, whose P\u2013P single bonds are comparatively weak; option (a). (b), (c) and (d) are all factually incorrect.\n\nS13. (a) True, by the standard sign convention (lattice enthalpy of formation is exothermic). (b) True \u2014 both processes require energy input. (c) False \u2014 first electron gain enthalpy can be endothermic (e.g., noble gases, Be, Mg, N). (d) True \u2014 Born\u2013Haber cycles are Hess's-law applications.\n\nS14. (a) True (Coulombic $z^2/r$ scaling). (b) True \u2014 Li$^+$'s small bare size gives it an unusually large, tightly bound hydration shell, hence a large hydrated radius and low ionic mobility despite its small crystallographic radius. (c) True. (d) False \u2014 $\\text{F}^-$, being smaller, has a LARGER hydration enthalpy magnitude than $\\text{Cl}^-$.\n\nS15. (a) True \u2014 $\\text{Pb}^{4+}$/PbO$_2$ is strongly oxidising because it tends to revert to the more stable Pb$^{2+}$ (inert-pair effect). (b) True \u2014 Tl$_2$O$_3$ (Tl$^{3+}$) similarly tends to revert to the stable Tl$^+$ state. (c) True \u2014 NaBiO$_3$ is a classic strong oxidiser (e.g., oxidises Mn$^{2+}$ to $\\text{MnO}_4^-$ in qualitative analysis). (d) False \u2014 for germanium the inert-pair effect is weak, so $\\text{GeO}_2$ (Ge$^{4+}$) is the more stable oxide, not GeO.\n\nS16. (a) True. (b) True \u2014 more oxo groups/higher central oxidation state stabilises the conjugate base better, so $\\text{H}_2\\text{SO}_4$ is the stronger acid. (c) True (more oxo groups on Cl in HClO$_4$ than HClO). (d) False \u2014 $\\text{NaHCO}_3$ solution is mildly basic (alkaline), not acidic.\n\nS17. (a) True \u2014 both $\\text{Be(OH)}_2$ and $\\text{Al(OH)}_3$ dissolve in excess acid and excess base; Mg(OH)$_2$ does not. (b) True \u2014 BeCl$_2$ is a covalent, bridged/polymeric chloride akin to AlCl$_3$'s dimeric structure, unlike ionic MgCl$_2$. (c) True. (d) False \u2014 lithium salts (e.g., LiF, Li$_2$CO$_3$) are typically LESS soluble than the corresponding sodium salts, owing to the very high lattice enthalpy of the small Li$^+$ ion.\n\nS18. (a) True \u2014 real radii approximately Cl$^-$ (181 pm) $>$ Ar (~154 pm, van der Waals) $>$ K$^+$ (138 pm). (b) True, the general isoelectronic-series principle. (c) False \u2014 despite K having a higher atomic number, $\\text{K}^+$ has LOST its outer shell, so it is actually smaller than $\\text{Cl}^-$; atomic number alone does not determine ionic radius across an isoelectronic series. (d) True \u2014 a more highly charged isoelectronic cation attracts electron density more strongly.\n\nS19. $\\Delta H_f=\\Delta H_{sub}+IE_{1+2}+D(\\text{Cl}_2)+2\\Delta_{eg}H(\\text{Cl})+U$. So $-828.4=164.4+1614+242.0+2(-349.0)+U=1322.4+U$, giving $U=-828.4-1322.4=-2150.8$ kJ/mol.\n\nS20. $\\Delta H_{sol}=-U+[\\Delta H_{hyd}(\\text{Sr}^{2+})+2\\Delta H_{hyd}(\\text{Cl}^-)]=2150.8+(-1443)+2(-381)=2150.8-1443-762=-54.2$ kJ/mol.\n\nS21. A small negative $\\Delta H_{sol}$ means dissolution releases a little heat overall (lattice enthalpy is almost, and comfortably, offset by the combined hydration enthalpies), consistent with $\\text{SrCl}_2$'s well-known high solubility in water; option (a).\n\nS22. As nitrogen's oxidation state rises from $+1$ (N$_2$O) to $+5$ (N$_2$O$_5$), the N\u2013O bonding becomes increasingly covalent/acidic; $\\text{N}_2\\text{O}_5$ is the anhydride of $\\text{HNO}_3$, the strongest acid in the series.\n\nS23. By Fajans' rules, covalent character (and hence insolubility) increases as the halide ion gets larger/more polarisable: $\\text{AgF}$ (most ionic, most soluble) $>\\text{AgCl}>\\text{AgBr}>\\text{AgI}$ (most covalent, least soluble).\n\nS24. The trend is a direct consequence of Fajans' rules: larger, more polarisable halide ions increase covalent character and raise the lattice enthalpy relative to hydration enthalpy, progressively reducing solubility; option (a).\n\nS25. Al ($1s^22s^22p^63s^23p^1$) has 3 valence electrons; the huge jump from $IE_3=2745$ to $IE_4=11577$ kJ/mol occurs because the fourth electron must be removed from the stable, filled $2p^6$ core. Hence 3 valence electrons.\n\nS26. Positive (endothermic) values: He, Ne, Ar, Kr, Xe (all 5 noble gases) plus Be and Mg (2 alkaline earths) $=7$; Ca, Sr and Ba are (slightly) negative. Total $=7$.\n\nS27. The three classic, textbook diagonal-relationship pairs are (Li, Mg), (Be, Al) and (B, Si). (C, P) and (Na, Ca) are not recognised diagonal pairs. Answer: 3.\n\nS28. CaO is basic; $\\text{Al}_2\\text{O}_3$ is amphoteric; $\\text{SiO}_2$, $\\text{P}_4\\text{O}_{10}$, $\\text{SO}_3$ and $\\text{Cl}_2\\text{O}_7$ are all acidic. Count of acidic oxides $=4$.\n\nS29. $\\Delta H_f=2\\Delta H_{sub}(\\text{Na})+2IE_1(\\text{Na})+\\Delta H_{sub}(\\text{S})+\\Delta_{eg}H_1(\\text{S})+\\Delta_{eg}H_2(\\text{S})+U$. So $-370=2(109)+2(496)+277+(-200)+590+U=1877+U$, giving $U=-370-1877=-2247$ kJ/mol; magnitude $=2247$.\n\nS30. Magnitudes exceeding 1900 kJ/mol: $\\text{Mg}^{2+}$ (1921) and $\\text{Al}^{3+}$ (4665). Na$^+$ (406), K$^+$ (322) and Ca$^{2+}$ (1577) do not qualify. Count $=2$.\n\nS31. Radii smaller than $\\text{Na}^+$ (95 pm): $\\text{Mg}^{2+}$ (65 pm) and $\\text{Al}^{3+}$ (50 pm). $\\text{N}^{3-}$, $\\text{O}^{2-}$ and $\\text{F}^-$ are all larger than Na$^+$. Count $=2$.\n\nS32. Tl$^+$, Pb$^{2+}$ and Bi$^{3+}$ are each the state stabilised by a strong inert-pair effect (more stable than Tl$^{3+}$, Pb$^{4+}$, Bi$^{5+}$ respectively). For Ge and Sn the inert-pair effect is weak, so Ge$^{4+}$/Sn$^{4+}$ (not the $+2$ states listed) are the more stable forms. Count $=3$.\n\nS33. $\\Delta\\chi=|1.9-3.2|=1.3$. $\\%\\text{ionic}=16(1.3)+3.5(1.3)^2=20.8+5.915=26.715\\approx26.72$.\n\nS34. $\\Delta=E_{A-B}-\\sqrt{E_{A-A}\\cdot E_{B-B}}=205-\\sqrt{170\\times100}=205-\\sqrt{17000}=205-130.38=74.62$. $\\chi_A-\\chi_B=0.102\\sqrt{74.62}=0.102\\times8.638=0.881$. $\\chi_A=2.30+0.88=3.18$.\n\nS35. Ratio $=\\dfrac{3^2/53}{1^2/102}=\\dfrac{9/53}{1/102}=\\dfrac{0.1698}{0.0098}\\approx17.32$.\n\nS36. $\\Delta H_f=\\Delta H_{sub}+IE_1+\\Delta H_{atom}(\\text{I})+\\Delta_{eg}H(\\text{I})+U$. So $-327.9=89.2+418.8+106.8+(-295.2)+U=319.6+U$, giving $U=-327.9-319.6=-647.5$ kJ/mol; magnitude $=647.50$.\n\nS37. $\\Delta\\chi=|1.90-3.16|=1.26$. $d=117+99-9(1.26)=216-11.34=204.66$ pm.\n\nS38. $\\chi_{AR}=0.359\\times\\dfrac{5.45}{(1.04)^2}+0.744=0.359\\times\\dfrac{5.45}{1.0816}+0.744=0.359\\times5.040+0.744=1.809+0.744=2.55$.\n\nS39. $\\Delta H_f=\\Delta H_{sub}+IE_{1+2}+\\Delta H_{atom}(2\\text{Br})+2\\Delta_{eg}H(\\text{Br})+U$. So $-682.8=177.8+1735.2+224.7+2x+(-1984.65)=153.05+2x$. Hence $2x=-682.8-153.05=-835.85$, so $x=-417.93$ kJ/mol; the reported magnitude is $417.93$.\n\nS40. Both statements are true, and R correctly explains A via the Coulombic dependence of lattice enthalpy on charge and distance; option (a).\n\nS41. A is the correct real order of radii for this isoelectronic series. R is false: all six species have exactly 10 electrons each (that is what \"isoelectronic\" means) but a DIFFERENT number of protons (7 to 13) \u2014 R has the roles of protons and electrons reversed; option (c).\n\nS42. Both statements are independently true, but R (Li's low atomic mass) is not the reason LiCl dissolves in organic solvents \u2014 the real reason is Li$^+$'s small size/high polarising power giving LiCl covalent character (Fajans' rules); option (b).\n\nS43. Real lattice enthalpies: $\\text{CaF}_2\\approx2651$ kJ/mol is actually LARGER in magnitude than KCl's $\\approx717$ kJ/mol, so A is false. R is a correct general statement about the factors governing lattice enthalpy; option (d).\n\nS44. Both are true: hydration enthalpy magnitude decreases down group 2 as ionic radius increases, giving exactly the order stated; option (a).\n\nS45. Pb$^{2+}$ (in PbCl$_2$) is the thermodynamically STABLE state for lead due to a strong inert-pair effect and is not typically employed as a reducing agent (unlike Sn$^{2+}$, which readily reduces other species en route to the more stable Sn$^{4+}$); so A is false. R correctly states the general inert-pair trend for group 14; option (d).\n\nS46. CrO$_3$ (Cr in $+6$) is strongly acidic (p); Cr$_2$O$_3$ (Cr in $+3$) is amphoteric (q); CrO (Cr in $+2$) is basic (r); Al$_2$O$_3$ is amphoteric (q), matching Cr$_2$O$_3$.\n\nS47. Approximate magnitudes (kJ/mol): Li$^+\\approx520$ (s), Na$^+\\approx406$ (r), Mg$^{2+}\\approx1921$ (q), Al$^{3+}\\approx4665$ (p) \u2014 hydration enthalpy magnitude rises sharply with increasing charge and decreasing radius.\n\nS48. A: LiF's low solubility follows from Li$^+$/F$^-$'s very high lattice enthalpy, poorly compensated by hydration (q). B: BeCl$_2$'s covalency versus CaCl$_2$'s ionic character follows from Be$^{2+}$'s much larger charge/size ratio (r). C: Tl$^+$'s stability over Tl$^{3+}$ is the inert-pair effect (p). D: N$_2$'s inertness follows from its very strong triple bond (s).\n\nS49. A: sublimation enthalpy converts solid metal to gaseous atoms (p). B: half the bond dissociation enthalpy of X$_2$ gives one mole of X(g) (q). C: ionisation enthalpy removes an electron from M(g) (r). D: electron gain enthalpy adds an electron to X(g) (s).\n\nS50. Clue A: aluminium, $Z=13$. Clue B: lead, $Z=82$. Clue C: oxygen, $Z=8$. Clue D: beryllium, $Z=4$. Clue E: fluorine, $Z=9$. Sum $=13+82+8+4+9=116$.\n";
const RAW_MD_LEGACY = "# Classification of Elements and Periodicity in Properties\n\n## Complete Rewritten Question Bank\n\n**Structure:** All questions are presented first. The consolidated answer key follows the complete question set, and the worked solutions appear after the answer key.\n\n---\n\n# Part I \u2014 Questions\n\n## Section 2.1 \u2014 Integer / Numerical-Answer Type Questions (22)\n\nQ1. Using Slater's rules, calculate $Z_{eff}$ for the 4s electron of Ca (Z = 20). [If your answer is 2.85, write 0285]\n\nQ2. Using Slater's rules, calculate $Z_{eff}$ for a 3d electron of Fe (Z = 26).\n\nQ3. Using Slater's rules, calculate $Z_{eff}$ for a 4p electron of Br (Z = 35).\n\nQ4. The successive ionisation energies of an element (in eV) are: $IE_1=9.5,\\ IE_2=18.2,\\ IE_3=27.5,\\ IE_4=120.0,\\ IE_5=155.0$. What is the stable oxidation state of this element?\n\nQ5. Using the standard $\\Delta_{eg}H$ data table, find the total number of elements up to atomic number 20 (inclusive) that have a positive (endothermic) first electron gain enthalpy.\n\nQ6. In a hypothetical universe, each orbital can hold a maximum of 3 electrons instead of 2, but every other filling rule (Aufbau order, subshell types, etc.) stays the same. Find the number of elements that would occupy the block filled by the 4s, 3d and 4p subshells (i.e. \"period 4\") in this universe.\n\nQ7. The covalent radius of phosphorus is 1.10 \u00c5. Using Slater's rule to find $Z_{eff}$ of its 3p electron, calculate the electronegativity of P on the Allred\u2013Rochow scale. (Report your answer \u00d7 100, to the nearest integer.)\n\nQ8. For an atom, $IE = 14.0$ eV and $EA = 2.8$ eV. Calculate its electronegativity on the Pauling scale using the Mulliken relation and the conversion $\\chi_P=\\chi_M/2.8$. (Report \u00d710.)\n\nQ9. Bond dissociation energies: $E_{A-A}=44$, $E_{B-B}=64$, $E_{A-B}=72$ kcal/mol. If $\\chi_A = 3.50$, use the Pauling relation to calculate $\\chi_B$. (Report \u00d7100, nearest integer.)\n\nQ10. Two elements have electronegativities $\\chi_A=1.2$ and $\\chi_B=3.2$. Using the Hannay\u2013Smith formula, calculate the % ionic character of the A\u2013B bond.\n\nQ11. A free 3d-block $M^{3+}$ ion has a spin-only magnetic moment of 4.90 BM. How many unpaired electrons does it have?\n\nQ12. $2\\times10^{6}$ gaseous bromine atoms release a total of $9.6\\times10^{-13}$ J of energy on converting to $\\text{Br}^-$ ions. Calculate the electron affinity of Br in eV/atom.\n\nQ13. Given: $\\Delta_{eg}H(A^+)=-6x$ (i.e. $IE_1=6x$), $\\Delta_{eg}H(A^{2+})=-9x$ (i.e. $IE_2=9x$), $\\Delta H_{IE}(A^{2+})=14x$ (i.e. $IE_3=14x$), $\\Delta_{eg}H(A^{4+})=-20x$ (i.e. $IE_4=20x$), $\\Delta H_{IE}(A^{4+})=26x$ (i.e. $IE_5=26x$). If $\\Delta H$ for $A^+(g)\\to A^{5+}(g)$ is $ax$, find $a$.\n\nQ14. For formation of $MX_3(s)$: $\\Delta H_f=-900$ kJ/mol, $\\Delta H_{sub}(M)=150$ kJ/mol, bond-dissociation energy for $\\tfrac32X_2\\to3X(g)=300$ kJ/mol, $IE_1+IE_2+IE_3(M)=1200$ kJ/mol, lattice enthalpy of formation $=-1350$ kJ/mol. If $q$ is the electron gain enthalpy of $X$ (per atom, in kJ/mol), calculate $q/50$.\n\nQ15. Heat of solution of $AB(s)$ is $+0.55\\times10^{x}$ kcal/mol. Lattice (dissociation) enthalpy of $AB(s)=780$ kcal/mol, hydration enthalpy of $A^+(g)=-430$ kcal/mol, hydration enthalpy of $B^-(g)=-295$ kcal/mol. Find $x$.\n\nQ16. Using Slater's rules, calculate $Z_{eff}$ for the 4s electron of K (Z=19) and $Z_{eff}$ for the 2p electron of N (Z=7). Report $\\left|Z_{eff}(\\text{N})-Z_{eff}(\\text{K})\\right|\\times100$.\n\nQ17. (Simplified model \u2014 assume EN is directly proportional to %s-character.) If the electronegativity of $sp^3$ carbon is 2.50, calculate the electronegativity of $sp$ carbon under this proportionality. (Report \u00d710.)\n\nQ18. In an isoelectronic pair, a cation has $Z_{eff}=15$ and ionic radius 80 pm; the corresponding anion has radius 200 pm. Using $r_{cation}/r_{anion}=Z_{eff}(\\text{anion})/Z_{eff}(\\text{cation})$, calculate $Z_{eff}$ of the anion. Report $Z_{eff}\\times10$.\n\nQ19. Find the total number of species with exactly 3 unpaired electrons (free ion, high-spin) among: $\\text{Cr}^{3+}, \\text{Mn}^{2+}, \\text{Fe}^{3+}, \\text{Co}^{2+}, \\text{Ni}^{2+}, \\text{V}^{2+}$.\n\nQ20. Find the total number of diamagnetic species among: $\\text{Zn}^{2+}, \\text{Sc}^{3+}, \\text{Ti}^{4+}, \\text{Cu}^{+}, \\text{Fe}^{2+}, \\text{Mn}^{7+}$.\n\nQ21. Find the number of p-block elements among the atomic numbers: 31, 47, 56, 82, 36, 92, 15.\n\nQ22. Calculate the total number of electrons present in all the d-subshells of a neutral Ag atom (Z = 47).\n\n## Section 2.2 \u2014 Multiple-Choice Questions: Single Correct (15)\n\nQ1. The correct increasing order of first ionisation enthalpy is:\n\n   (a) B < Be < C < N\n\n   (b) Be < B < C < N\n\n   (c) B < C < Be < N\n\n   (d) C < B < Be < N\n\nQ2. Select the correct order of atomic radius in the boron family:\n\n   (a) Al < Ga < In < Tl\n\n   (b) Ga < Al < In < Tl\n\n   (c) Al < In < Ga < Tl\n\n   (d) Tl < In < Ga < Al\n\nQ3. Which of the following is not a transition element by the strict definition (incomplete d-subshell in atom or common ion)?\n\n   (a) Fe\n\n   (b) Zn\n\n   (c) Mn\n\n   (d) Cr\n\nQ4. Nearly identical atomic radii due to lanthanide contraction is best shown by the pair:\n\n   (a) Sc, Y\n\n   (b) Zr, Hf\n\n   (c) Ti, Zr\n\n   (d) Fe, Ru\n\nQ5. The correct order of electron gain enthalpy (magnitude) for halogens is:\n\n   (a) F > Cl > Br > I\n\n   (b) Cl > F > Br > I\n\n   (c) Cl > Br > F > I\n\n   (d) Br > Cl > F > I\n\nQ6. The correct order of electronegativity for carbon in different hybridisation states is:\n\n   (a) $sp^3 > sp^2 > sp$\n\n   (b) $sp > sp^2 > sp^3$\n\n   (c) $sp^2 > sp > sp^3$\n\n   (d) $sp^3 > sp > sp^2$\n\nQ7. Which of the following oxides is amphoteric?\n\n   (a) Na\u2082O\n\n   (b) SO\u2083\n\n   (c) Al\u2082O\u2083\n\n   (d) Cl\u2082O\u2087\n\nQ8. Among the isoelectronic species F\u207b, Na\u207a, Mg\u00b2\u207a, O\u00b2\u207b, the one with the smallest ionic radius is:\n\n   (a) F\u207b\n\n   (b) O\u00b2\u207b\n\n   (c) Na\u207a\n\n   (d) Mg\u00b2\u207a\n\nQ9. Which statement correctly reflects the inert-pair effect?\n\n   (a) Pb(IV) is more stable than Pb(II)\n\n   (b) Tl(I) is more stable than Tl(III)\n\n   (c) Bi(V) is more stable than Bi(III)\n\n   (d) Sn(II) is less stable than Sn(IV)\n\nQ10. The correct order of hydracid strength (aqueous) is:\n\n   (a) HF > HCl > HBr > HI\n\n   (b) HI > HBr > HCl > HF\n\n   (c) HCl > HF > HBr > HI\n\n   (d) HBr > HI > HCl > HF\n\nQ11. The second electron gain enthalpy of oxygen ($\\text{O}^-\\to\\text{O}^{2-}$) is:\n\n   (a) always negative\n\n   (b) always positive\n\n   (c) zero\n\n   (d) element-independent\n\nQ12. By Fajans' rules, which pair correctly predicts greater covalent character?\n\n   (a) BeCl\u2082 more covalent than MgCl\u2082\n\n   (b) MgCl\u2082 more covalent than BeCl\u2082\n\n   (c) CaCl\u2082 more covalent than BeCl\u2082\n\n   (d) BeCl\u2082 and CaCl\u2082 equally covalent\n\nQ13. Which of the following is classified as a metalloid?\n\n   (a) Se\n\n   (b) Sb\n\n   (c) Sn\n\n   (d) Bi\n\nQ14. An element shows a huge jump between $IE_1$ and $IE_2$ (i.e. $IE_2\\gg IE_1$), with no comparable jump afterward for several removals. This element most likely belongs to group:\n\n   (a) 1\n\n   (b) 2\n\n   (c) 13\n\n   (d) 14\n\nQ15. The correct order of lattice enthalpy (magnitude) is:\n\n   (a) LiCl > NaCl > KCl > RbCl\n\n   (b) NaCl > LiCl > KCl > RbCl\n\n   (c) RbCl > KCl > NaCl > LiCl\n\n   (d) KCl > NaCl > LiCl > RbCl\n\n## Section 2.3 \u2014 Correct-Order Code-Number Questions (6)\n\nInstructions (Use the code-number convention below): each row states an order and a property. Some rows are correct, some are deliberately wrong. Add up the code numbers as instructed.\n\n### CO-1\n\nCalculate the sum of code numbers of all CORRECT orders.\n\n| S.No. | Order | Property | Code |\n|---:|:---|:---|:---:|\n| 1 | $\\text{Al}^{3+}<\\text{Mg}^{2+}<\\text{Na}^+$ | Ionic radius | 05 |\n| 2 | $\\text{F}^-<\\text{Cl}^-<\\text{Br}^-<\\text{I}^-$ | Ionic radius | 12 |\n| 3 | $\\text{N}^{3-}<\\text{O}^{2-}<\\text{F}^-$ | Ionic radius | 07 |\n| 4 | $\\text{Fe}^{2+}>\\text{Fe}^{3+}$ | Ionic radius | 03 |\n| 5 | $\\text{Li}^+<\\text{Na}^+<\\text{K}^+<\\text{Rb}^+$ | Magnitude of hydration enthalpy | 14 |\n\n(Example: if only rows 2 and 4 are correct, the answer is $12+03=15$.)\n\n### CO-2\n\nCalculate the sum of code numbers of all INCORRECT orders.\n\n| S.No. | Order | Property | Code |\n|---:|:---|:---|:---:|\n| 1 | $\\text{Be}>\\text{B}$ | First IE | 06 |\n| 2 | $\\text{N}>\\text{O}$ | First IE | 09 |\n| 3 | $\\text{Cl}>\\text{F}$ | Magnitude of electron gain enthalpy | 04 |\n| 4 | $\\text{S}>\\text{Se}$ | Magnitude of electron gain enthalpy | 11 |\n| 5 | $\\text{F}>\\text{Cl}$ | Electronegativity | 02 |\n| 6 | $\\text{S}<\\text{O}$ | Magnitude of electron gain enthalpy | 15 |\n\n### CO-3\n\nCalculate the sum of code numbers of all CORRECT orders.\n\n| S.No. | Order | Property | Code |\n|---:|:---|:---|:---:|\n| 1 | $\\text{Zr}\\approx\\text{Hf}$ | Atomic radius | 07 |\n| 2 | $\\text{Sc}<\\text{Y}<\\text{La}$ | Atomic radius | 13 |\n| 3 | $\\text{Cu}>\\text{Zn}$ | Atomic radius (3d) | 09 |\n| 4 | $\\text{Eu}>\\text{Sm}$ | Atomic radius (lanthanoids) | 05 |\n| 5 | $\\text{Ce}^{4+}<\\text{Ce}^{3+}$ | Ionic radius | 18 |\n| 6 | $\\text{La}>\\text{Lu}$ | Atomic radius | 10 |\n\n### CO-4\n\nCalculate the sum of code numbers of all INCORRECT orders.\n\n| S.No. | Order | Property | Code |\n|---:|:---|:---|:---:|\n| 1 | $\\text{Na}_2\\text{O}<\\text{MgO}<\\text{Al}_2\\text{O}_3<\\text{SiO}_2$ | Acidic character | 17 |\n| 2 | $\\text{Mn}_2\\text{O}_7>\\text{MnO}_2$ | Acidic character | 04 |\n| 3 | $\\text{HF}<\\text{HCl}<\\text{HBr}<\\text{HI}$ | Acid strength (aqueous) | 21 |\n| 4 | $\\text{NH}_3<\\text{PH}_3$ | Basicity | 08 |\n| 5 | $\\text{H}_2\\text{SO}_4>\\text{H}_2\\text{SO}_3$ | Acid strength | 12 |\n| 6 | $\\text{Bi(V)}>\\text{Bi(III)}$ | Thermodynamic stability | 19 |\n\n### CO-5\n\nCalculate the sum of code numbers of all CORRECT orders.\n\n| S.No. | Order | Property | Code |\n|---:|:---|:---|:---:|\n| 1 | $sp>sp^2>sp^3$ | EN of carbon | 03 |\n| 2 | $\\text{C}{\\equiv}\\text{C}>\\text{C}{=}\\text{C}>\\text{C}{-}\\text{C}$ | EN of carbon in the bond | 14 |\n| 3 | In $\\text{NF}_3$, bond polarises toward N | Bond polarity | 20 |\n| 4 | $\\text{O}^{2-}<\\text{O}^-<\\text{O}<\\text{O}^+$ | Electronegativity | 06 |\n| 5 | $\\text{Ga}>\\text{Al}$ | Electronegativity | 09 |\n| 6 | $\\text{Hg}>\\text{Cd}>\\text{Zn}$ | Electronegativity | 17 |\n\n### CO-6\n\nCalculate the sum of code numbers of all INCORRECT orders.\n\n| S.No. | Order | Property | Code |\n|---:|:---|:---|:---:|\n| 1 | $\\text{LiF}>\\text{NaF}>\\text{KF}>\\text{RbF}$ | Magnitude of lattice enthalpy | 22 |\n| 2 | $\\text{MgO}>\\text{NaCl}$ | Magnitude of lattice enthalpy | 05 |\n| 3 | $\\text{Li}^+>\\text{Na}^+>\\text{K}^+$ | Magnitude of hydration enthalpy | 11 |\n| 4 | $\\text{Li}^+>\\text{Na}^+>\\text{K}^+$ | Ionic mobility in water | 16 |\n| 5 | $\\text{CsCl}>\\text{NaCl}$ | Magnitude of lattice enthalpy | 08 |\n| 6 | $\\text{BaO}>\\text{CaO}$ | Magnitude of lattice enthalpy | 13 |\n\n## Section 2.4 \u2014 Subjective / Long-Answer Problems (56)\n\nThe first 6 problems below form a compact \"core\" set; Q7\u2013Q56 (further below) extend this into a full 50-problem drill bank organised by topic.\n\nQ1. How many electrons in the $\\text{Fe}^{3+}$ ion (Z = 26) have azimuthal quantum number $\\ell=1$ (i.e., are in p-orbitals)?\n\nQ2. The covalent radius of nitrogen is 0.70 \u00c5. Using Slater's rule to find $Z_{eff}$ of its 2p electron, calculate the electronegativity of N on the Allred\u2013Rochow scale.\n\nQ3. Heat of solution of a salt $AB(s)$ is $+15$ kcal/mol. Hydration enthalpy of $A^+(g)=-120$ kcal/mol and of $B^-(g)=-95$ kcal/mol. Calculate the lattice (dissociation) enthalpy of $AB(s)$.\n\nQ4. For the formation of $MX_2(s)$: $\\Delta H_f=-650$ kJ/mol; sublimation enthalpy of $M=180$ kJ/mol; bond dissociation enthalpy of $X_2(g)\\to 2X(g)=190$ kJ/mol; $IE_1+IE_2$ of $M=1400$ kJ/mol; lattice enthalpy of formation $=-1300$ kJ/mol. Calculate the electron gain enthalpy of $X$ (per atom, in kJ/mol).\n\nQ5. For the formation of $AB(s)$: $\\Delta H_f=-380$ kJ/mol; sublimation enthalpy of $A=90$ kJ/mol; bond dissociation enthalpy for $\\tfrac12B_2\\to B=120$ kJ/mol; $IE_1(A)=480$ kJ/mol; electron gain enthalpy of $B=-350$ kJ/mol. Calculate the lattice enthalpy of formation $U$, and report $-U/100$.\n\nQ6. Examine the following ten statements. Count how many are correct ($x$) and how many are incorrect ($y$), then report $|x-y|^2$.\n\n(i) $\\text{HF}>\\text{HCl}>\\text{HBr}>\\text{HI}$ \u2014 bond enthalpy\n\n(ii) $\\text{NH}_3>\\text{PH}_3>\\text{AsH}_3$ \u2014 bond angle\n\n(iii) $\\text{Li}^+<\\text{Na}^+<\\text{K}^+$ \u2014 ionic mobility in water\n\n(iv) $\\text{F}_2<\\text{Cl}_2<\\text{Br}_2<\\text{I}_2$ \u2014 bond dissociation enthalpy\n\n(v) $\\text{Sc}^{3+}<\\text{Ti}^{4+}$ \u2014 ionic radius\n\n(vi) $\\text{N}_2\\text{O}_5>\\text{N}_2\\text{O}_3$ \u2014 acidic strength\n\n(vii) $\\text{Be}^{2+}<\\text{Mg}^{2+}<\\text{Ca}^{2+}$ \u2014 |hydration enthalpy|\n\n(viii) $\\text{Cu}^{2+}<\\text{Cu}^+$ \u2014 stability in aqueous solution\n\n(ix) $\\text{I}^-<\\text{Br}^-<\\text{Cl}^-<\\text{F}^-$ \u2014 reducing power\n\n(x) $\\text{BeCl}_2<\\text{MgCl}_2<\\text{CaCl}_2$ \u2014 covalent character\n\n### Extended Subjective Problems (Q7-Q56)\n\n### Electronic Configuration & Magnetism (Q7\u2013Q11)\nQ7. How many electrons in the $\\text{Cu}$ atom (Z = 29, ground state) have azimuthal quantum number $\\ell=2$?\n\nQ8. Find the total number of unpaired electrons in the ground state of Cr (Z = 24), and hence its spin-only magnetic moment.\n\nQ9. Calculate the spin-only magnetic moment of $\\text{Mn}^{2+}$ (free ion).\n\nQ10. Calculate the spin-only magnetic moment of $\\text{Ni}^{2+}$ (free ion).\n\nQ11. How many electrons in $\\text{Fe}^{3+}$ (Z = 26) have principal quantum number $n=3$?\n\n### Zeff / Slater's Rules (Q12\u2013Q16)\nQ12. Using Slater's rules, calculate $Z_{eff}$ for a 4p electron of Se (Z = 34).\n\nQ13. Using Slater's rules, calculate $Z_{eff}$ for a 3d electron of Cu (Z = 29).\n\nQ14. Using Slater's rules, calculate $Z_{eff}$ for the 3s electron of Mg (Z = 12).\n\nQ15. Using Slater's rules, calculate $Z_{eff}$ for a 3p electron of Ar (Z = 18).\n\nQ16. For Cu (Z = 29), calculate $Z_{eff}$ for its 3d electron and separately for its 4s electron, and report the difference. Explain in one line why this difference is chemically important.\n\n### Atomic & Ionic Radius (Q17\u2013Q21)\nQ17. In an isoelectronic pair, the cation has $Z_{eff}=18$ and radius 68 pm; the corresponding anion has radius 172 pm. Using $r_{cation}/r_{anion}=Z_{eff}(\\text{anion})/Z_{eff}(\\text{cation})$, estimate $Z_{eff}$ of the anion.\n\nQ18. Zr (Z = 40) and Hf (Z = 72) have nearly identical atomic radii (145 pm and 144 pm respectively) despite Hf lying a full period below Zr. Explain this using electronic configuration.\n\nQ19. Using the Schomaker\u2013Stevenson relation, estimate the A\u2013B bond length given $r_A=1.20$ \u00c5, $r_B=0.99$ \u00c5, and $\\Delta\\chi = 0.5$.\n\nQ20. Ionic radii: $\\text{Fe}=126$ pm, $\\text{Fe}^{2+}\\approx76$ pm, $\\text{Fe}^{3+}\\approx64$ pm. Explain this order in terms of $Z_{eff}$ per electron.\n\nQ21. Given approximate N\u2013N bond lengths: single (hydrazine-type) \u2248 145 pm, double (azo-type) \u2248 125 pm, triple (N\u2082) \u2248 110 pm \u2014 explain the trend using bond order and hybridisation.\n\n### Ionisation Enthalpy (Q22\u2013Q26)\nQ22. An element shows successive ionisation energies (eV): $IE_1=8.3,\\ IE_2=16.7,\\ IE_3=25.0,\\ IE_4=45.0,\\ IE_5=54.0$. Identify the likely group and stable oxidation state.\n\nQ23. Given $IE_1(\\text{Be})=900$ and $IE_1(\\text{B})=801$ kJ/mol, explain why Be's is higher despite B having one more proton.\n\nQ24. An element has $IE_1=737$, $IE_2=1450$, $IE_3=7732$, $IE_4=10539$ kJ/mol. Identify where the giant jump occurs and state the element's most probable valency.\n\nQ25. Using $E_n=-13.6Z^2/n^2$ eV, calculate the ionisation energy of $\\text{Li}^{2+}$ (a hydrogen-like species, Z = 3) from its ground state ($n=1$).\n\nQ26. Data: sublimation enthalpy of Li = 159 kJ/mol, $IE_1(\\text{Li})=520$ kJ/mol, hydration enthalpy of $\\text{Li}^+=-519$ kJ/mol; sublimation enthalpy of Cs = 76 kJ/mol, $IE_1(\\text{Cs})=376$ kJ/mol, hydration enthalpy of $\\text{Cs}^+=-263$ kJ/mol. Calculate the net energy change (sublimation + ionisation + hydration) for each metal converting to its aqueous cation, and use the result to explain why Li is the stronger reducing agent in water despite its higher gas-phase IE.\n\n### Electron Gain Enthalpy (Q27\u2013Q31)\nQ27. Given $\\Delta_{eg}H_1(\\text{F})=-328$ and $\\Delta_{eg}H_1(\\text{Cl})=-349$ kJ/mol, explain numerically (in terms of orbital size) why Cl's value is more negative despite F having higher $Z_{eff}$ and smaller size.\n\nQ28. $\\Delta_{eg}H_1(\\text{O})=-141$ kJ/mol but $\\Delta_{eg}H_2(\\text{O})$ (for $\\text{O}^-\\to\\text{O}^{2-}$) is strongly positive. Given that MgO nonetheless forms with a large negative overall lattice enthalpy of formation ($-3795$ kJ/mol) compensating, explain why $\\text{O}^{2-}$ is stable in the solid despite the unfavourable gas-phase second electron gain.\n\nQ29. $3\\times10^6$ gaseous chlorine atoms release a total of $1.68\\times10^{-12}$ J of energy on converting to $\\text{Cl}^-$ ions. Calculate the electron affinity of Cl in eV/atom.\n\nQ30. Using the NCERT-style data $\\Delta_{eg}H_1(\\text{N})=+31$ kJ/mol (unfavourable) and $\\Delta_{eg}H_1(\\text{P})=-72$ kJ/mol (favourable), explain this reversal using electron configuration.\n\nQ31. Explain, with reference to electron configuration, why $\\Delta_{eg}H_1$ of Ne (+116 kJ/mol) is more strongly positive than that of He (+48 kJ/mol), even though both are noble gases with closed shells.\n\n### Electronegativity (Q32\u2013Q39)\nQ32. Bond energies: $E_{A-A}=150$, $E_{B-B}=80$, $E_{A-B}=145$ kJ/mol. Given $\\chi_B=2.20$, calculate $\\chi_A$ using the Pauling relation ($\\Delta$ in kJ/mol, use $0.102\\sqrt\\Delta$).\n\nQ33. For chlorine, $IE=1140$ kJ/mol and $EA=349$ kJ/mol. Calculate the Mulliken electronegativity (in the kJ/mol-based formula $\\chi_M=(IE+EA)/(2\\times96.5)$) and convert it to the Pauling scale using $\\chi_P\\approx\\chi_M/2.8$.\n\nQ34. Estimate $\\chi_{AR}$ (Allred\u2013Rochow) for bromine given covalent radius $r=1.14$ \u00c5 and $Z_{eff}=7.60$ (from Slater's rules).\n\nQ35. Two elements have $\\chi_A=1.5$ and $\\chi_B=3.7$. Calculate the % ionic character of the A\u2013B bond using (a) the Hannay\u2013Smith formula and (b) Pauling's exponential formula. Compare the two estimates.\n\nQ36. Using $\\chi_{\\text{O}}=3.44$, $\\chi_{\\text{H}}=2.20$, and $\\chi_{\\text{K}}=0.82$, predict whether K\u2013O\u2013H behaves as an acid or a base, showing your comparison explicitly.\n\nQ37. Given that the electronegativity of $sp^3$-hybridised carbon is 2.50, and assuming EN is directly proportional to %s-character, calculate the electronegativity of $sp^2$-hybridised carbon. State which C\u2013H bond (in ethane, ethene, or ethyne) would be expected to be the most acidic, and why.\n\nQ38. Using the Schomaker\u2013Stevenson correction $d_{A-B}=r_A+r_B-9\\Delta\\chi$ (pm), calculate the C\u2013F bond length given $r_C=77$ pm, $r_F=64$ pm, and $\\chi_C=2.55,\\ \\chi_F=3.98$.\n\nQ39. The group electronegativity of $-\\text{CF}_3$ (\u22483.46) is much higher than that of $-\\text{CH}_3$ (\u22482.30). Using this, predict and justify which is a stronger acid: $\\text{CH}_3\\text{COOH}$ or $\\text{CF}_3\\text{COOH}$.\n\n### Chemical Periodicity (Q40\u2013Q44)\nQ40. $\\text{Tl}^{3+}$ is a stronger oxidising agent than $\\text{Pb}^{4+}$ is often assumed to be, yet both reflect the same underlying effect. Name the effect and explain why Tl(III) and Pb(IV) are both relatively oxidising compared to their lower-oxidation-state counterparts.\n\nQ41. Calculate the average oxidation state of sulfur in $\\text{S}_4\\text{O}_6^{2-}$ (tetrathionate ion), and explain why this average does not correspond to a single real oxidation state on every sulfur atom.\n\nQ42. Rank $\\text{Na}_2\\text{O}$, $\\text{Al}_2\\text{O}_3$, and $\\text{SO}_3$ in order of increasing acidic character, justifying each placement using electronegativity/bonding-type reasoning.\n\nQ43. Explain, using two different mechanisms, why (a) $\\text{HI}$ is a stronger acid than $\\text{HF}$ in water, while (b) $\\text{HF}$ is a stronger acid than $\\text{CH}_4$'s C\u2013H bond. (Your explanation should show that these are governed by different factors.)\n\nQ44. Using Fajans' rules, predict which member of each pair has greater covalent character: (a) $\\text{MgCl}_2$ vs $\\text{CaCl}_2$; (b) $\\text{AgCl}$ vs $\\text{NaCl}$ (same approximate cation radius).\n\n### Lattice Enthalpy, Hydration & Born\u2013Haber (Q45\u2013Q51)\nQ45. For the formation of NaBr(s): $\\Delta H_f=-361.4$ kJ/mol, sublimation enthalpy of Na $=108.4$ kJ/mol, $IE_1(\\text{Na})=495.8$ kJ/mol, $\\tfrac12D(\\text{Br}_2)=96.4$ kJ/mol, $\\Delta_{eg}H(\\text{Br})=-324.5$ kJ/mol. Calculate the lattice enthalpy of formation of NaBr(s).\n\nQ46. Using $|\\Delta H_{hyd}|\\propto z^2/r$, and given $r(\\text{Mg}^{2+})=72$ pm and $r(\\text{Ca}^{2+})=100$ pm (same charge $z=2$), calculate the ratio $|\\Delta H_{hyd}(\\text{Mg}^{2+})|:|\\Delta H_{hyd}(\\text{Ca}^{2+})|$.\n\nQ47. Lattice (dissociation) enthalpy of a salt $AB(s)=690$ kJ/mol; hydration enthalpy of $A^+=-380$ kJ/mol; hydration enthalpy of $B^-=-310$ kJ/mol. Calculate $\\Delta H_{sol}$ and comment on what this borderline value implies about the salt's solubility.\n\nQ48. Arrange $\\text{LiF}, \\text{NaF}, \\text{KF}, \\text{RbF}$ in decreasing order of lattice enthalpy magnitude, and separately arrange $\\text{NaF}, \\text{NaCl}, \\text{NaBr}, \\text{NaI}$ in decreasing order \u2014 explain why the two orders are controlled by different ions.\n\nQ49. Predict, using Fajans' rules, which is expected to have the higher melting point: $\\text{LiCl}$ or $\\text{CsCl}$. Justify using polarising power.\n\nQ50. $\\text{Li}^+$ has a smaller bare ionic radius than $\\text{Cs}^+$, yet $\\text{Li}^+$ has lower ionic mobility in water. Resolve this apparent contradiction.\n\nQ51. For the formation of $\\text{MCl}_2(s)$: $\\Delta H_f=-796$ kJ/mol, sublimation enthalpy of M $=178$ kJ/mol, $IE_1(\\text{M})=590$ kJ/mol, $D(\\text{Cl}_2)=242$ kJ/mol, $\\Delta_{eg}H(\\text{Cl})=-349$ kJ/mol (\u00d72 for two Cl atoms), lattice enthalpy of formation $=-2258$ kJ/mol. Calculate $IE_2(\\text{M})$.\n\n### Mixed & Comprehensive (Q52\u2013Q56)\nQ52. An element X has: high $IE_1$, high electronegativity, small atomic radius, and forms an acidic, covalent oxide. Predict whether X is likely to be found in the upper-right or lower-left region of the periodic table, and list two properties you would expect for its hydride.\n\nQ53. Two unknown elements, P and Q, are in the same period. P has a lower $IE_1$ and lower electronegativity than Q. Predict, with reasoning, which one (a) has the larger atomic radius, (b) forms the more basic oxide, (c) is more likely to act as a reducing agent.\n\nQ54. An element M forms $\\text{MCl}_2$ that is highly ionic and water-soluble, but a related element M\u2032 (same group, smaller period number, similar charge) forms $\\text{M}'\\text{Cl}_2$ that is markedly more covalent and less soluble. Identify which of M/M\u2032 has the smaller cation, and explain using polarising power.\n\nQ55. Write a short, structured explanation (5\u20136 points) of why atomic radius decreases across period 3 (Na\u2192Cl) but ionisation enthalpy does not increase perfectly smoothly across the same period.\n\nQ56. For each of the following five statements, state True/False and give a one-line reason: (i) Electron gain enthalpy and electronegativity are the same physical quantity. (ii) The lowest-IE element in a group is always the strongest reducing agent in aqueous solution. (iii) A completely filled d-subshell always means the element is not a transition metal. (iv) Isoelectronic species always have identical chemical properties. (v) A larger $\\Delta\\chi$ always means a bond is more than 50% ionic.\n\n---\n\n# Part II \u2014 Consolidated Answer Key\n\n## Section 2.1 \u2014 Numerical-Answer Type\n\n| Q | Answer | Q | Answer | Q | Answer |\n|---:|:---|---:|:---|---:|:---|\n| 1 | 0285 | 9 | 260 | 17 | 50 |\n| 2 | 0625 | 10 | 46 | 18 | 60 |\n| 3 | 0760 | 11 | 4 | 19 | 3 |\n| 4 | +3 | 12 | 3.00 eV | 20 | 5 |\n| 5 | 7 | 13 | 69 | 21 | 4 |\n| 6 | 27 | 14 | -8 | 22 | 20 |\n| 7 | 217 | 15 | 2 |  |  |\n| 8 | 30 | 16 | 170 |  |  |\n\n## Section 2.2 \u2014 Single-Correct MCQs\n\n| Q | Answer | Q | Answer | Q | Answer |\n|---:|:---:|---:|:---:|---:|:---:|\n| 1 | (a) | 6 | (b) | 11 | (b) |\n| 2 | (b) | 7 | (c) | 12 | (a) |\n| 3 | (b) | 8 | (d) | 13 | (b) |\n| 4 | (b) | 9 | (b) | 14 | (a) |\n| 5 | (b) | 10 | (b) | 15 | (a) |\n\n## Section 2.3 \u2014 Correct-Order Code Questions\n\n| Question | Answer |\n|:---|:---:|\n| CO-1 | 0020 |\n| CO-2 | 0015 |\n| CO-3 | 0053 |\n| CO-4 | 0027 |\n| CO-5 | 0049 |\n| CO-6 | 0037 |\n\n## Section 2.4 \u2014 Subjective / Long-Answer Problems\n\n| Q | Answer | Q | Answer | Q | Answer | Q | Answer |\n|---:|:---|---:|:---|---:|:---|---:|:---|\n| 1 | 12 electrons | 15 | 7.45 | 29 | 3.50 eV | 43 | See solution |\n| 2 | 3.60 | 16 | 4.15 | 30 | See solution | 44 | MgCl\u2082; AgCl |\n| 3 | 230 kcal mol\u207b\u00b9 | 17 | 7.12 | 31 | See solution | 45 | -737.5 kJ mol\u207b\u00b9 |\n| 4 | -560 kJ mol\u207b\u00b9 | 18 | See solution | 32 | 2.81 or 1.59* | 46 | 1.39 : 1 |\n| 5 | 7.20 | 19 | 2.145 \u00c5 | 33 | 2.76 | 47 | 0 kJ mol\u207b\u00b9 |\n| 6 | 4 | 20 | See solution | 34 | 2.84 | 48 | See solution |\n| 7 | 10 | 21 | See solution | 35 | 52.14%; 70.18% | 49 | CsCl |\n| 8 | 6.93 BM | 22 | Group 13; +3 | 36 | Basic | 50 | See solution |\n| 9 | 5.92 BM | 23 | See solution | 37 | 3.33; ethyne | 51 | 1150 kJ mol\u207b\u00b9 |\n| 10 | 2.83 BM | 24 | Valency 2 | 38 | 128.13 pm | 52 | Upper-right; see solution |\n| 11 | 13 | 25 | 122.4 eV | 39 | CF\u2083COOH | 53 | See solution |\n| 12 | 6.95 | 26 | Li: 160; Cs: 189 kJ mol\u207b\u00b9 | 40 | Inert-pair effect | 54 | M\u2032 |\n| 13 | 7.85 | 27 | See solution | 41 | +2.5 | 55 | See solution |\n| 14 | 2.85 | 28 | See solution | 42 | Na\u2082O < Al\u2082O\u2083 < SO\u2083 | 56 | All false |\n\n\\*The Pauling bond-energy relation gives only $|\\Delta\\chi|$; the sign depends on which atom is assumed to be more electronegative.\n\n---\n\n# Part III \u2014 Worked Solutions\n\n## Solutions to Section 2.1\n\nS1. $\\sigma=(1\\times0.35)+(8\\times0.85)+(10\\times1.00)=17.15\\Rightarrow Z_{eff}=20-17.15=\\mathbf{2.85}$ \u2192 0285\n\nS2. 3d electron of Fe ($3d^6$ group): $\\sigma=(5\\times0.35)+(18\\times1.00)=1.75+18=19.75\\Rightarrow Z_{eff}=26-19.75=\\mathbf{6.25}$ \u2192 0625\n\nS3. 4p electron of Br ($[Ar]3d^{10}4s^24p^5$): same-group (4s,4p) others $=6\\times0.35=2.10$; $n{-}1$ shell (3s,3p,3d=18)$\\times0.85=15.30$; lower shells (10)$\\times1.00=10.00$. $\\sigma=27.40\\Rightarrow Z_{eff}=35-27.40=\\mathbf{7.60}$ \u2192 0760\n\nS4. Big jump between $IE_3$ and $IE_4$ \u2192 only 3 valence electrons removed easily \u2192 element is in Group 13-type pattern \u2192 stable oxidation state = +3\n\nS5. Positive $\\Delta_{eg}H$ up to Z=20: He, Be, N, Ne, Mg, Ar, Ca \u2192 7\n\nS6. Normal period-4 length = $4s(2)+3d(10)+4p(6)=18$. Scaling capacities by $3/2$: $4s=3,\\ 3d=15,\\ 4p=9$. Total $=3+15+9=\\mathbf{27}$\n\nS7. $Z_{eff}(\\text{P}, 3p)=15-(4\\times0.35+8\\times0.85+2\\times1.00)=15-10.20=4.80$. $\\chi_{AR}=\\dfrac{0.359\\times4.80}{1.10^2}+0.744=1.424+0.744=2.168\\approx2.17$ \u2192 \u00d7100 = 217\n\nS8. $\\chi_M=(14.0+2.8)/2=8.4$ eV; $\\chi_P=8.4/2.8=\\mathbf{3.00}$ \u2192 \u00d710 = 30\n\nS9. $\\Delta=72-\\sqrt{44\\times64}=72-53.06=18.94$; $|\\Delta\\chi|=0.208\\sqrt{18.94}=0.905$; $\\chi_B=3.50-0.905=\\mathbf{2.60}$ \u2192 \u00d7100 = 260\n\nS10. $\\Delta\\chi=2.0$; $\\%=16(2.0)+3.5(2.0)^2=32+14=\\mathbf{46}$\n\nS11. $\\sqrt{n(n+2)}=4.90\\Rightarrow n(n+2)\\approx24\\Rightarrow n=4$ (check: $\\sqrt{4\\times6}=\\sqrt{24}=4.899\\approx4.90$) \u2192 4\n\nS12. Energy/atom $=9.6\\times10^{-13}/2\\times10^{6}=4.8\\times10^{-19}$ J; in eV $=4.8\\times10^{-19}/1.6\\times10^{-19}=\\mathbf{3.00\\ eV}$\n\nS13. $A^+\\to A^{5+}$ requires removing electrons via $IE_2+IE_3+IE_4+IE_5=9x+14x+20x+26x=\\mathbf{69x}$ \u2192 $a=$ 69\n\nS14. $-900=150+300+1200+3q-1350\\Rightarrow -900=300+3q\\Rightarrow q=-400$ kJ/mol; $q/50=\\mathbf{-8}$\n\nS15. $\\Delta H_{sol}=780-430-295=55$ kcal/mol $=0.55\\times10^x\\Rightarrow10^x=100\\Rightarrow x=\\mathbf{2}$\n\nS16. K, 4s electron: $\\sigma=(0)(0.35)+(8)(0.85)+(10)(1.00)=16.80\\Rightarrow Z_{eff}=19-16.80=2.20$. N, 2p electron: $\\sigma=(4)(0.35)+(2)(0.85)=1.40+1.70=3.10\\Rightarrow Z_{eff}=7-3.10=3.90$. Difference $=|3.90-2.20|=1.70$ \u2192 \u00d7100 = 170\n\nS17. Ratio of %s-character $=50/25=2\\Rightarrow\\chi_{sp}=2\\times2.50=\\mathbf{5.00}$ \u2192 \u00d710 = 50\n\nS18. $80/200=Z_{eff}(\\text{anion})/15\\Rightarrow Z_{eff}(\\text{anion})=15\\times0.4=\\mathbf{6.00}$ \u2192 \u00d710 = 60\n\nS19. $\\text{Cr}^{3+}(d^3,3\\uparrow)$\u2713, $\\text{Mn}^{2+}(d^5,5\\uparrow)$\u2717, $\\text{Fe}^{3+}(d^5,5\\uparrow)$\u2717, $\\text{Co}^{2+}(d^7,3\\uparrow)$\u2713, $\\text{Ni}^{2+}(d^8,2\\uparrow)$\u2717, $\\text{V}^{2+}(d^3,3\\uparrow)$\u2713 \u2192 3\n\nS20. $\\text{Zn}^{2+}(d^{10})$\u2713, $\\text{Sc}^{3+}(d^0)$\u2713, $\\text{Ti}^{4+}(d^0)$\u2713, $\\text{Cu}^+(d^{10})$\u2713, $\\text{Fe}^{2+}(d^6,\\text{4 unpaired})$\u2717, $\\text{Mn}^{7+}(d^0)$\u2713 \u2192 5\n\nS21. 31=Ga(p)\u2713, 47=Ag(d)\u2717, 56=Ba(s)\u2717, 82=Pb(p)\u2713, 36=Kr(p)\u2713, 92=U(f)\u2717, 15=P(p)\u2713 \u2192 4\n\nS22. Ag = $[Kr]4d^{10}5s^1$ = full config $1s^22s^22p^63s^23p^63d^{10}4s^24p^64d^{10}5s^1$. d-electrons $=3d^{10}+4d^{10}=\\mathbf{20}$\n\n## Solutions to Section 2.2\n\nS1. **Answer: (a).** Across Period 2, first ionisation enthalpy generally increases. Boron is lower than beryllium because the electron removed from B is a higher-energy $2p$ electron, whereas Be has a stable filled $2s^2$ subshell. Therefore, $\\text{B}<\\text{Be}<\\text{C}<\\text{N}$.\n\nS2. **Answer: (b).** Gallium is slightly smaller than aluminium because the intervening $3d$ electrons shield poorly, increasing $Z_{eff}$ on Ga. Down the rest of the group, additional shells increase size. Hence $\\text{Ga}<\\text{Al}<\\text{In}<\\text{Tl}$.\n\nS3. **Answer: (b).** Zinc has $3d^{10}4s^2$, and its common ion $\\text{Zn}^{2+}$ is $3d^{10}$. Neither has an incomplete d-subshell, so Zn is not a transition element under the strict definition.\n\nS4. **Answer: (b).** Hf follows the lanthanoids. Poor shielding by the filled $4f$ subshell causes lanthanoid contraction, making the radii of Zr and Hf nearly identical.\n\nS5. **Answer: (b).** Chlorine has the greatest electron-gain-enthalpy magnitude because its roomier $3p$ subshell experiences less electron-electron repulsion than F's compact $2p$ subshell. The order is $\\text{Cl}>\\text{F}>\\text{Br}>\\text{I}$.\n\nS6. **Answer: (b).** Electronegativity increases with s-character because an s-orbital holds electron density closer to the nucleus. Since s-character follows $sp(50\\%)>sp^2(33.3\\%)>sp^3(25\\%)$, the electronegativity order is $sp>sp^2>sp^3$.\n\nS7. **Answer: (c).** $\\text{Na}_2\\text{O}$ is basic, $\\text{SO}_3$ and $\\text{Cl}_2\\text{O}_7$ are acidic, while $\\text{Al}_2\\text{O}_3$ reacts with both acids and bases and is therefore amphoteric.\n\nS8. **Answer: (d).** All four species contain 10 electrons. In an isoelectronic series, radius decreases as nuclear charge increases. Mg has the highest nuclear charge, so $\\text{Mg}^{2+}$ is the smallest.\n\nS9. **Answer: (b).** The inert-pair effect stabilises lower oxidation states down a p-block group. Thus Tl(I) is more stable than Tl(III).\n\nS10. **Answer: (b).** Down Group 17, the H-X bond becomes longer and weaker, so proton release becomes easier. Therefore, aqueous acid strength follows $\\text{HI}>\\text{HBr}>\\text{HCl}>\\text{HF}$.\n\nS11. **Answer: (b).** Adding an electron to $\\text{O}^-$ requires overcoming repulsion from an already negatively charged ion. Consequently, the second electron gain enthalpy is always positive.\n\nS12. **Answer: (a).** Be\u00b2\u207a is smaller and has greater polarising power than Mg\u00b2\u207a. It distorts the electron cloud of Cl\u207b more strongly, making $\\text{BeCl}_2$ more covalent.\n\nS13. **Answer: (b).** Antimony lies along the conventional metal-non-metal boundary and is classified as a metalloid.\n\nS14. **Answer: (a).** A very large jump immediately after $IE_1$ means one valence electron is removed easily and the second would come from a stable inner shell. The element therefore belongs to Group 1.\n\nS15. **Answer: (a).** For ions with equal charges and the same anion, lattice-enthalpy magnitude decreases as cation size increases. Thus $\\text{LiCl}>\\text{NaCl}>\\text{KCl}>\\text{RbCl}$.\n\n## Solutions to Section 2.3\n\nCO-1: Row 1 \u2713 (Al\u00b3\u207a smallest, isoelectronic-like cation series), Row 2 \u2713 (down-group increase), Row 3 \u2717 (N\u00b3\u207b has lowest Z among this isoelectronic trio, so it should be largest, not smallest \u2014 order is reversed), Row 4 \u2713 (higher charge \u2192 smaller radius), Row 5 \u2717 (hydration magnitude actually falls down the group: Li\u207a>Na\u207a>K\u207a>Rb\u207a, so ascending order is wrong). Correct rows: 1,2,4 \u2192 Sum = 05+12+03 = 0020\n\nCO-2: Rows 1\u20135 are all correct standard results (Be>B and N>O are the classic IE special cases; Cl>F and S>Se follow the normal EGE-magnitude trend from period 2\u21923 onward; F>Cl is the standard EN trend). Row 6 is wrong \u2014 S's EGE magnitude (200) is greater than O's (141), so \"S<O\" is false. Only incorrect row: 6 \u2192 Sum = 0015\n\nCO-3: Row 1 \u2713 (lanthanide-contraction twin). Row 2 \u2713 (no f-electrons yet at La, so no contraction interrupts the normal group increase). Row 3 \u2717 (Zn (137 pm) is actually larger than Cu (128 pm) \u2014 the completed $3d^{10}4s^2$ pushes size back up). Row 4 \u2713 (Eu is anomalously large due to stable half-filled $4f^7$). Row 5 \u2713 (higher charge, smaller radius). Row 6 \u2713 (La is the largest lanthanoid, Lu the smallest \u2014 steady contraction). Correct rows: 1,2,4,5,6 \u2192 Sum = 07+13+05+18+10 = 0053\n\nCO-4: Row 1 \u2713 correct period-3 acidity progression. Row 2 \u2713 higher oxidation state, more acidic. Row 3 \u2713 bond-strength-controlled hydracid trend. Row 4 \u2717 \u2014 NH\u2083 is actually more basic than PH\u2083 (N's lone pair is more concentrated/available despite N being more electronegative); the stated order is reversed. Row 5 \u2713 higher oxidation state of S, more acidic. Row 6 \u2717 \u2014 Bi(III) is more stable than Bi(V) due to the inert-pair effect; Bi(V) is a strong oxidiser, so the stated order is reversed. Incorrect rows: 4,6 \u2192 Sum = 08+19 = 0027\n\nCO-5: Row 1 \u2713 %s-character rule. Row 2 \u2713 higher bond order, higher effective EN. Row 3 \u2717 \u2014 F is more electronegative than N, so in NF\u2083 the bond polarises toward F, away from N (opposite of NH\u2083); the statement is false. Row 4 \u2713 EN rises with positive charge. Row 5 \u2713 classic Ga>Al special case. Row 6 \u2713 classic Hg>Cd>Zn special case. Correct rows: 1,2,4,5,6 \u2192 Sum = 03+14+06+09+17 = 0049\n\nCO-6: Row 1 \u2713 \u2014 for a fixed anion, lattice-enthalpy magnitude decreases as cation size increases. Row 2 \u2713 \u2014 MgO has a much larger charge product than NaCl. Row 3 \u2713 \u2014 hydration-enthalpy magnitude decreases down Group 1. Row 4 \u2717 \u2014 ionic mobility in water increases down Group 1 because the strongly hydrated Li\u207a ion has the largest effective hydrated radius. Row 5 \u2717 \u2014 NaCl has a greater lattice-enthalpy magnitude than CsCl because Na\u207a is smaller. Row 6 \u2717 \u2014 CaO has a greater lattice-enthalpy magnitude than BaO because Ca\u00b2\u207a is smaller. Incorrect rows: 4, 5 and 6 \u2192 Sum = 16+08+13 = 0037.\n\n## Solutions to Section 2.4: Q1-Q6\n\nS1. $\\text{Fe}^{3+}=[\\text{Ar}]3d^5=1s^22s^22p^63s^23p^63d^5$. p-electrons $=2p^6+3p^6=\\mathbf{12}$\n\nS2. $Z_{eff}(\\text{N},2p)=7-3.10=3.90$ (from calc in 2.1-S16). $\\chi_{AR}=\\dfrac{0.359\\times3.90}{0.70^2}+0.744=\\dfrac{1.400}{0.49}+0.744=2.857+0.744=\\mathbf{3.60}$\n\nS3. $\\Delta H_{sol}=\\text{Lattice}_{diss}+\\Delta H_{hyd}(A^+)+\\Delta H_{hyd}(B^-)$ $15=\\text{Lattice}_{diss}+(-120)+(-95)\\Rightarrow \\text{Lattice}_{diss}=15+215=\\mathbf{230\\ kcal/mol}$\n\nS4. $\\Delta H_f=\\Delta H_{sub}+BDE+IE_{sum}+2\\times EA+\\Delta H_{latt}$ $-650=180+190+1400+2EA+(-1300)$ $-650=470+2EA\\Rightarrow EA=\\mathbf{-560\\ kJ/mol\\ per\\ X\\ atom}$\n\nS5. $\\Delta H_f=\\Delta H_{sub}+BDE+IE_1+EA+U$ $-380=90+120+480+(-350)+U\\Rightarrow-380=340+U\\Rightarrow U=\\mathbf{-720\\ kJ/mol}$ $-U/100=\\mathbf{7.20}$\n\nS6. Checking each: (i) T \u2014 H\u2013F is the strongest H\u2013X bond. (ii) T \u2014 bond angles: NH\u2083(107\u00b0)>PH\u2083(93.5\u00b0)>AsH\u2083(91.8\u00b0). (iii) T \u2014 mobility rises down the group (Section 1.9). (iv) F \u2014 real order is $\\text{Cl}_2>\\text{Br}_2>\\text{F}_2>\\text{I}_2$, not monotonic; F\u2082's bond is anomalously weak (lone-pair repulsion). (v) F \u2014 Sc\u00b3\u207a(~74.5 pm) is larger than Ti\u2074\u207a(~60.5 pm); statement reversed. (vi) T \u2014 higher oxidation state of N, more acidic. (vii) F \u2014 hydration magnitude actually falls down the group (Be\u00b2\u207a highest); statement reversed. (viii) F \u2014 Cu\u00b2\u207a is more stable than Cu\u207a in water (Cu\u207a disproportionates); statement reversed. (ix) F \u2014 I\u207b is the strongest reducing halide ion, F\u207b the weakest; statement reversed. (x) F \u2014 by Fajans' rule BeCl\u2082 (smallest cation) is most covalent, not least; statement reversed.\n\n$x(\\text{correct})=4$ [(i),(ii),(iii),(vi)], $y(\\text{incorrect})=6$ [(iv),(v),(vii),(viii),(ix),(x)]. $|x-y|^2=|4-6|^2=\\mathbf{4}$\n\n## Solutions to Section 2.4: Q7-Q56\n\nS7. $\\text{Cu}=[\\text{Ar}]3d^{10}4s^1$. Electrons with $\\ell=2$ (d-electrons) $=3d^{10}=\\mathbf{10}$.\n\nS8. $\\text{Cr}=[\\text{Ar}]3d^54s^1$ \u2014 all 5 d-electrons unpaired (Hund's rule, degenerate orbitals) plus the single 4s electron is also unpaired. Total unpaired $=\\mathbf{6}$. $\\mu_{so}=\\sqrt{6\\times8}=\\sqrt{48}=\\mathbf{6.93\\ BM}$.\n\nS9. $\\text{Mn}^{2+}=[\\text{Ar}]3d^5$ \u2192 5 unpaired electrons. $\\mu=\\sqrt{5\\times7}=\\sqrt{35}=\\mathbf{5.92\\ BM}$.\n\nS10. $\\text{Ni}^{2+}=[\\text{Ar}]3d^8$ \u2192 fill 5 orbitals with 8 electrons: 3 pairs + 2 singles \u2192 2 unpaired. $\\mu=\\sqrt{2\\times4}=\\sqrt8=\\mathbf{2.83\\ BM}$.\n\nS11. $\\text{Fe}^{3+}=[\\text{Ar}]3d^5=1s^22s^22p^63s^23p^63d^5$. Electrons with $n=3$: $3s^2+3p^6+3d^5=2+6+5=\\mathbf{13}$.\n\nS12. Se $=(1s^2)(2s^22p^6)(3s^23p^6)(3d^{10})(4s^24p^4)$. 4p electron: same group (4s+4p\u22121)$=5\\times0.35=1.75$; $(n{-}1)$ shell $(3s3p3d=18)\\times0.85=15.30$; lower shells $(10)\\times1.00=10.00$. $\\sigma=27.05\\Rightarrow Z_{eff}=34-27.05=\\mathbf{6.95}$.\n\nS13. Cu, 3d electron ($3d^{10}4s^1$, use $nd$ rule): same-group others $=9\\times0.35=3.15$; groups to the left (18 electrons) $\\times1.00=18.00$; the 4s electron (to the right) shields zero. $\\sigma=21.15\\Rightarrow Z_{eff}=29-21.15=\\mathbf{7.85}$.\n\nS14. Mg, 3s: same group others $=1\\times0.35=0.35$; $(n{-}1)$ shell (8) $\\times0.85=6.80$; lower (2)$\\times1.00=2.00$. $\\sigma=9.15\\Rightarrow Z_{eff}=12-9.15=\\mathbf{2.85}$.\n\nS15. Ar, 3p: same group others $=5\\times0.35=1.75$; $(n{-}1)$ shell (8)$\\times0.85=6.80$; lower (2)$\\times1.00=2.00$. $\\sigma=10.55\\Rightarrow Z_{eff}=18-10.55=\\mathbf{7.45}$.\n\nS16. $Z_{eff}(3d)=7.85$ (from S13). For the 4s electron: same-group others $=0$ (only one 4s electron, no 4p) $\\times0.35=0$; $(n{-}1)$ shell now includes the full $3d^{10}$ ($3s^23p^63d^{10}=18$) $\\times0.85=15.30$; lower (10)$\\times1.00=10.00$. $\\sigma=25.30\\Rightarrow Z_{eff}(4s)=29-25.30=3.70$. Difference $=7.85-3.70=\\mathbf{4.15}$. This large gap is exactly why the 4s electron is lost first when Cu forms Cu\u207a/Cu\u00b2\u207a, even though 4s filled before 3d.\n\nS17. $68/172=Z_{eff}(\\text{anion})/18\\Rightarrow Z_{eff}(\\text{anion})=18\\times(68/172)=\\mathbf{7.12}$.\n\nS18. Zr $=[\\text{Kr}]4d^25s^2$; Hf $=[\\text{Xe}]4f^{14}5d^26s^2$. Going from period 5 to period 6 across this pair, 14 additional 4f electrons had to be filled in between (the lanthanoids), and 4f electrons shield very poorly. The resulting steady rise in $Z_{eff}$ (lanthanide contraction) very nearly cancels the size increase expected simply from adding a whole new principal shell \u2014 leaving Zr and Hf almost identical in size and chemistry (a \"chemical twin\" pair).\n\nS19. $d_{A-B}=r_A+r_B-0.09\\Delta\\chi = 1.20+0.99-0.09(0.5)=2.19-0.045=\\mathbf{2.145\\ \\text{\u00c5}}$ (shorter than the simple sum $r_A+r_B=2.19$ \u00c5, because bond polarity contracts the bond).\n\nS20. $\\text{Fe}\\to\\text{Fe}^{2+}$: same nucleus (26 protons), but 2 fewer electrons, so remaining electrons feel higher $Z_{eff}$ per electron and less mutual repulsion \u2192 smaller radius. $\\text{Fe}^{2+}\\to\\text{Fe}^{3+}$: one further electron removed, $Z_{eff}$ per remaining electron rises again \u2192 radius shrinks further. Hence $r(\\text{Fe})>r(\\text{Fe}^{2+})>r(\\text{Fe}^{3+})$, consistent with the general rule $M>M^{2+}>M^{3+}$.\n\nS21. Higher bond order packs more bonding electron density between the two nuclei, pulling them closer together and shortening the bond ($r\\propto1/\\text{bond order}$); it also raises the %s-character of the hybrid orbitals involved (roughly $sp^3\\to sp^2\\to sp$ across single\u2192double\u2192triple N\u2013N bonds), and s-orbitals hold density closer to the nucleus, reinforcing the same contraction. Hence single > double > triple in bond length.\n\nS22. Jump between $IE_3(25.0)$ and $IE_4(45.0)$ is the largest relative jump (1.8\u00d7), meaning 3 valence electrons are removed comparatively easily before hitting the core. Likely group 13, stable oxidation state +3.\n\nS23. Be's electron is removed from a filled, symmetric, comparatively low-energy $2s^2$ subshell, while B's removed electron is a $2p^1$ electron \u2014 higher in energy and less penetrating than a 2s electron (even though B has one more proton). The penetration/subshell effect outweighs the extra nuclear charge here.\n\nS24. Giant jump appears between $IE_2(1450)$ and $IE_3(7732)$ \u2014 a jump of over 5\u00d7. This means 2 valence electrons are removed easily, and the 3rd comes from a stable inner (noble-gas) core. Valency = 2 (this data matches Mg).\n\nS25. $IE=13.6\\times Z^2/n^2 = 13.6\\times9/1=\\mathbf{122.4\\ eV}$.\n\nS26. Li: $159+520-519=\\mathbf{160}$ kJ/mol (net). Cs: $76+376-263=\\mathbf{189}$ kJ/mol (net). Even though Cs has the lower gas-phase $IE_1$, once atomisation and hydration are folded in, Li's overall cycle (160 kJ/mol) is more favourable (lower net cost) than Cs's (189 kJ/mol) \u2014 Li\u207a's very large hydration enthalpy is the deciding term, making Li the stronger reducing agent in aqueous solution despite its higher gas-phase IE.\n\nS27. The extra 46 kJ/mol advantage for Cl ($-349$ vs $-328$) arises because the incoming electron in Cl enters the roomier, less-crowded $3p$ orbital, whereas in F it must squeeze into the very compact $2p$ orbital, where electron\u2013electron repulsion partially cancels the benefit of F's smaller size/higher $Z_{eff}$.\n\nS28. The positive $\\Delta_{eg}H_2(\\text{O})$ (endothermic, since an electron is being pushed onto an already-negative $\\text{O}^-$ ion) is a small energy cost compared to the very large exothermic lattice enthalpy released when $\\text{Mg}^{2+}$ and $\\text{O}^{2-}$ ions assemble into the MgO crystal ($-3795$ kJ/mol). Once you sum the full Born\u2013Haber cycle, the large negative lattice term more than compensates for the unfavourable second electron-gain step, giving an overall favourable (exothermic) formation of solid MgO.\n\nS29. Energy/atom $=1.68\\times10^{-12}/3\\times10^6=5.6\\times10^{-19}$ J. In eV: $5.6\\times10^{-19}/1.6\\times10^{-19}=\\mathbf{3.50\\ eV}$.\n\nS30. N has a stable, symmetric half-filled $2p^3$ configuration; adding an electron forces pairing in an already-settled arrangement, which costs more than it gains \u2014 making $\\Delta_{eg}H_1(\\text{N})$ positive (unfavourable). P has the same $np^3$ symmetry, but its larger, roomier $3p$ orbital accommodates the extra electron with far less crowding/repulsion than N's compact $2p$, so despite the same \"half-filled resists addition\" effect, P's value still comes out favourable (negative).\n\nS31. Both He ($1s^2$) and Ne ($2s^22p^6$) must start an entirely new, higher-energy shell to accept an electron \u2014 both processes are unfavourable. But Ne's incoming electron would enter the $n=3$ shell, which is shielded by two full inner shells (10 electrons) and sits considerably farther from a nucleus of only $Z=10$; He's incoming electron enters $n=2$, shielded by just 2 inner electrons around a nucleus of $Z=2$. The proportionally weaker net attraction available to Ne's new-shell electron (in a poorer $Z_{eff}$-to-distance ratio) makes Ne's electron gain even less favourable than He's.\n\nS32. $\\Delta=145-\\sqrt{150\\times80}=145-109.54=35.46$; $|\\Delta\\chi|=0.102\\sqrt{35.46}=0.607$. Since $\\Delta$ came out positive and small, $\\chi_A\\approx\\chi_B\\pm0.61$; taking A as the more electronegative partner (consistent with $\\chi_B=2.20$ given), $\\chi_A\\approx2.20+0.61=\\mathbf{2.81}$ (or $2.20-0.61=1.59$, depending on which atom is assumed more electronegative \u2014 state your assumption clearly, as the Pauling relation only gives $|\\Delta\\chi|$, not the sign).\n\nS33. $\\chi_M=(1140+349)/(2\\times96.5)=1489/193=\\mathbf{7.72}$ (this is on the same numerical footing as an eV-based value even though computed from kJ/mol, because of how the conversion factor is built in). Converting: $\\chi_P\\approx7.72/2.8=\\mathbf{2.76}$ \u2014 reasonably close to Cl's accepted Pauling value of 3.16, illustrating that the Mulliken\u2192Pauling conversion is approximate.\n\nS34. $\\chi_{AR}=0.359\\times7.60/(1.14)^2+0.744 = 2.7284/1.2996+0.744=2.100+0.744=\\mathbf{2.84}$.\n\nS35. $\\Delta\\chi=3.7-1.5=2.2$. (a) Hannay\u2013Smith: $16(2.2)+3.5(2.2)^2=35.2+16.94=\\mathbf{52.14\\%}$. (b) Pauling exponential: $[1-e^{-0.25(2.2)^2}]\\times100=[1-e^{-1.21}]\\times100=[1-0.2982]\\times100=\\mathbf{70.18\\%}$. The two models diverge noticeably at large $\\Delta\\chi$ \u2014 a reminder that %-ionic-character estimates are approximate models, not exact measurements, and different formulas can give quite different numbers for the same $\\Delta\\chi$.\n\nS36. $|\\chi_O-\\chi_K|=|3.44-0.82|=2.62$; $|\\chi_O-\\chi_H|=|3.44-2.20|=1.24$. Since $|\\chi_O-\\chi_K|>|\\chi_O-\\chi_H|$, the K\u2013O bond is the more polar (weaker/more ionic) link and breaks first, releasing $\\text{K}^++\\text{OH}^-$ \u2014 KOH is basic, exactly analogous to NaOH/CsOH.\n\nS37. Ratio of %s-character $=33.3/25=1.332\\Rightarrow\\chi_{sp^2}=1.332\\times2.50=\\mathbf{3.33}$ (under the stated simplified proportionality). The most acidic C\u2013H bond is in ethyne ($sp$ carbon, 50% s-character) \u2014 its conjugate base (acetylide, $\\text{HC}{\\equiv}\\text{C}^-$) holds the negative charge in an orbital closest to the carbon nucleus among the three, which stabilises the anion most and makes proton loss easiest.\n\nS38. $d_{C-F}=77+64-9(3.98-2.55)=141-9(1.43)=141-12.87=\\mathbf{128.13\\ pm}$ (noticeably shorter than the naive sum of 141 pm, because of the large C\u2013F electronegativity difference).\n\nS39. $\\text{CF}_3\\text{COOH}$ is the stronger acid. The $-\\text{CF}_3$ group is strongly electron-withdrawing (high group electronegativity, \u22483.46, vs \u22482.30 for $-\\text{CH}_3$), which pulls electron density away from the carboxylate oxygen, stabilising the conjugate base ($\\text{CF}_3\\text{COO}^-$) far more effectively than $-\\text{CH}_3$ stabilises $\\text{CH}_3\\text{COO}^-$ \u2014 a more stable conjugate base means a stronger acid.\n\nS40. The effect is the inert-pair effect. Down groups 13 and 14, the outer $ns^2$ pair becomes progressively less willing to participate in bonding (poor shielding by intervening d/f electrons plus relativistic stabilisation), so the lower oxidation state (Tl(I), Pb(II)) becomes the thermodynamically preferred one. Consequently the higher states (Tl(III), Pb(IV)) are relatively unstable and tend to be reduced back to the inert-pair-favoured lower state \u2014 which is exactly what makes them oxidising agents.\n\nS41. Let average S oxidation state be $x$: charge balance gives $4x+6(-2)=-2\\Rightarrow4x=10\\Rightarrow x=+2.5$. This is only an average \u2014 tetrathionate actually contains two distinct types of sulfur: two central S atoms behave like $0$-ish (S\u2013S bonded, similar to elemental sulfur) and two terminal $-\\text{SO}_3^-$-type sulfurs behave close to $+5$, averaging to $+2.5$ overall, just as $\\text{Fe}_3\\text{O}_4$'s average $+8/3$ hides a real mixture of Fe(II) and Fe(III).\n\nS42. $\\text{Na}_2\\text{O}<\\text{Al}_2\\text{O}_3<\\text{SO}_3$ in acidic character. Na (very low EN, strongly electropositive) forms a highly ionic, strongly basic oxide. Al sits near the metal/non-metal boundary; its oxide is amphoteric \u2014 sitting between basic and acidic. S, a non-metal in its highest (+6) oxidation state, forms a fully covalent, strongly acidic oxide (reacts with water to give $\\text{H}_2\\text{SO}_4$). This tracks the steady rise in central-atom electronegativity/oxidation state across the period.\n\nS43. (a) HI vs HF acidity in water is bond-strength controlled: I is much larger than F, so the H\u2013I bond is far longer/weaker than H\u2013F, making H\u207a easier to release from HI \u2014 this happens despite F being far more electronegative than I. (b) HF vs $\\text{CH}_4$ (C\u2013H) is electronegativity controlled: within the same period/similar bond lengths, F's much higher electronegativity polarises the H\u2013F bond far more strongly, favouring proton release, while C\u2013H is barely polarised at all. The key point: the same-looking comparison (\"which acid is stronger\") is governed by an entirely different physical factor depending on whether you're comparing down a group or across a period.\n\nS44. (a) $\\text{MgCl}_2$ has greater covalent character than $\\text{CaCl}_2$ \u2014 $\\text{Mg}^{2+}$ is smaller than $\\text{Ca}^{2+}$ (same charge), so it polarises the $\\text{Cl}^-$ electron cloud more strongly. (b) $\\text{AgCl}$ has greater covalent character than $\\text{NaCl}$ even at similar cation radius \u2014 $\\text{Ag}^+$ has a filled but poorly-shielding $4d^{10}$ (\"pseudo-noble-gas\") core, unlike $\\text{Na}^+$'s genuinely noble-gas $[\\text{Ne}]$ core, so $\\text{Ag}^+$ polarises $\\text{Cl}^-$ more strongly for a given size.\n\nS45. $\\Delta H_f=\\Delta H_{sub}+IE_1+\\tfrac12D(\\text{Br}_2)+\\Delta_{eg}H(\\text{Br})+U_{latt(form)}$ $-361.4=108.4+495.8+96.4+(-324.5)+U$ $-361.4=376.1+U\\Rightarrow U=\\mathbf{-737.5\\ kJ/mol}$\n\nS46. Ratio $=\\dfrac{z^2/r(\\text{Mg}^{2+})}{z^2/r(\\text{Ca}^{2+})}=\\dfrac{4/72}{4/100}=\\dfrac{100}{72}=\\mathbf{1.39:1}$ \u2014 i.e. $\\text{Mg}^{2+}$'s hydration enthalpy magnitude is about 1.39\u00d7 that of $\\text{Ca}^{2+}$, consistent with Mg\u00b2\u207a's smaller size and higher charge density.\n\nS47. $\\Delta H_{sol}=690+(-380)+(-310)=690-690=\\mathbf{0\\ kJ/mol}$. A near-zero $\\Delta H_{sol}$ means lattice-breaking and hydration are almost perfectly balanced enthalpically \u2014 in this borderline case, solubility is decided almost entirely by the entropy term ($\\Delta G=\\Delta H-T\\Delta S$), not by enthalpy at all, since $\\Delta H_{sol}\\approx0$ gives essentially no enthalpic driving force either way.\n\nS48. $\\text{LiF}>\\text{NaF}>\\text{KF}>\\text{RbF}$ (fixed anion, cation size rising down the group \u2192 lattice enthalpy magnitude falls) is controlled by cation size. $\\text{NaF}>\\text{NaCl}>\\text{NaBr}>\\text{NaI}$ (fixed cation, anion size rising down the group) is controlled by anion size. Both orders follow the same underlying rule ($|U|\\propto1/(r_++r_-)$), but each isolates a different ion as the size-changing variable.\n\nS49. By Fajans' rules, $\\text{Li}^+$ (smallest, most highly-charge-dense alkali cation) polarises $\\text{Cl}^-$ the most strongly, giving LiCl the most covalent character among the alkali chlorides; $\\text{Cs}^+$ is large and weakly polarising, so CsCl stays closest to purely ionic bonding. Greater covalent character generally lowers melting point (more molecular-like, less extended lattice character), so despite naive charge/size reasoning suggesting the small $\\text{Li}^+$ should give the strongest lattice, the covalency effect dominates and CsCl has the higher melting point of the two (consistent with real values: LiCl \u2248 605\u00b0C, CsCl \u2248 645\u00b0C).\n\nS50. $\\text{Li}^+$'s small size gives it a very high charge density, so it attracts and binds a thick, tightly-held shell of water molecules \u2014 its effective (hydrated) radius moving through solution ends up larger than $\\text{Cs}^+$'s. $\\text{Cs}^+$, despite being physically bigger as a bare ion, is weakly hydrated and drags a much thinner water shell, giving it a smaller effective size and therefore higher mobility. Bare-ion size and effective (hydrodynamic) size are simply two different quantities.\n\nS51. $\\Delta H_f=\\Delta H_{sub}+IE_1+IE_2+D(\\text{Cl}_2)+2\\Delta_{eg}H(\\text{Cl})+U_{latt(form)}$ $-796=178+590+IE_2+242+2(-349)+(-2258)$ $-796=178+590+IE_2+242-698-2258$ $-796=-1946+IE_2\\Rightarrow IE_2=\\mathbf{1150\\ kJ/mol}$\n\nS52. High $IE_1$, high EN, small radius, and an acidic covalent oxide are all hallmarks of a non-metal from the upper-right region of the periodic table (near the halogens/chalcogens). Its hydride would be expected to be: (i) a covalent, molecular compound (not an ionic salt-like hydride), and (ii) acidic in water (or at least the central atom polarises the H\u2013E bond strongly), following the same logic as $\\text{HF}, \\text{H}_2\\text{O}$ etc.\n\nS53. Since P has lower $IE_1$ and lower EN than Q in the same period, P sits to the left of Q. (a) P has the larger atomic radius (radius falls left\u2192right across a period). (b) P forms the more basic oxide (lower EN/more metallic character \u2192 more ionic, basic oxide). (c) P is more likely to act as a reducing agent (lower IE \u2192 loses electrons more readily).\n\nS54. M\u2032 has the smaller cation. A smaller, more highly-charge-dense cation polarises the shared $\\text{Cl}^-$ electron cloud more strongly (Fajans' rules), pulling the bonding toward covalent character \u2014 which lowers water solubility and increases covalency, exactly matching M\u2032's described behaviour. (This is the same logic as $\\text{BeCl}_2$ vs $\\text{CaCl}_2$, or $\\text{MgCl}_2$ vs $\\text{BaCl}_2$.)\n\nS55. (i) $Z_{eff}$ rises fairly smoothly across the period because each added electron enters the same $n=3$ shell and same-shell shielding is weak \u2014 so radius falls in a fairly regular, monotonic way. (ii) Ionisation enthalpy depends on $Z_{eff}$ and on which specific subshell/orbital is being emptied. (iii) Going from Mg to Al, the electron removed switches from a penetrating, stable filled $3s^2$ to a less-penetrating, exposed $3p^1$ \u2014 a local dip, even though $Z_{eff}$ rose. (iv) Going from P to S, the electron removed switches from a stable, symmetric half-filled $3p^3$ to a paired $3p^4$, where extra electron\u2013electron repulsion makes removal easier \u2014 another local dip. (v) So radius (which only cares about the \"envelope\" of $Z_{eff}$ vs shell) decreases smoothly, while IE (which cares about the specific subshell/pairing state of the outgoing electron) shows the two well-known zig-zags at Mg\u2192Al and P\u2192S superimposed on the overall rising trend.\n\nS56. (i) False \u2014 EN describes a bonded atom (relative, dimensionless); electron gain enthalpy is a measurable energy change for an isolated gaseous atom. (ii) False \u2014 the classic counter-example is Li vs Cs: Li has the highest gas-phase $IE_1$ in its group, yet is the strongest reducing agent in water because of its very large hydration enthalpy. (iii) False \u2014 Zn, Cd, Hg have completely filled $d^{10}$ subshells in both atom and common ion, and are indeed excluded from the strict transition-metal definition, but this is a specific named special case, not a universal rule for every filled-d-subshell case (e.g. Cu\u207a has $d^{10}$ too but Cu is still classified as a transition element because the element Cu, i.e. Cu\u00b2\u207a/Cu\u2070, has incomplete d-subshells in its other common states). (iv) False \u2014 isoelectronic species (same electron count) can have very different chemical behaviour (e.g. $\\text{Na}^+$ is chemically inert-ish in solution while $\\text{F}^-$ is a base); they share electron count, not chemistry. (v) False \u2014 a larger $\\Delta\\chi$ generally correlates with more ionic character, but there's no universal sharp cutoff at which a bond flips to \"more than 50% ionic\"; different empirical formulas (Hannay\u2013Smith vs Pauling's exponential) can give quite different %-ionic-character estimates for the same $\\Delta\\chi$, as seen in Q35.\n";
const RELEASE = "periodicity-question-bank-v1";

type HeadingBlock = { kind: "heading"; level: number; text: string; id?: string };
type ParagraphBlock = { kind: "paragraph"; text: string };
type RuleBlock = { kind: "rule" };
type TableBlock = { kind: "table"; header: string[]; rows: string[][] };
type Block = HeadingBlock | ParagraphBlock | RuleBlock | TableBlock;

type QTopicKey =
  | "history"
  | "configuration"
  | "radius"
  | "ionization"
  | "electronGain"
  | "electronegativity"
  | "zeff"
  | "mixed";

const RAW_MD_MIXED: string =
  RAW_MD_MIXED_NEW +
  "\n\n---\n\n## Legacy Comprehensive Set (Original 99-Question Bank)\n\nThe full original cross-topic drill bank is preserved below in its entirety, unedited.\n\n" +
  RAW_MD_LEGACY;

const Q_TOPICS: { key: QTopicKey; num: string; label: string; markdown: string }[] = [
  { key: "history", num: "1", label: "History & Modern Law", markdown: RAW_MD_HISTORY },
  { key: "configuration", num: "2", label: "Electronic Configuration", markdown: RAW_MD_CONFIGURATION },
  { key: "radius", num: "3", label: "Atomic & Ionic Radius", markdown: RAW_MD_RADIUS },
  { key: "ionization", num: "4", label: "Ionization Enthalpy", markdown: RAW_MD_IONIZATION },
  { key: "electronGain", num: "5", label: "Electron Gain Enthalpy", markdown: RAW_MD_ELECTRONGAIN },
  { key: "electronegativity", num: "6", label: "Electronegativity", markdown: RAW_MD_ELECTRONEGATIVITY },
  { key: "zeff", num: "7", label: "Zeff & Slater", markdown: RAW_MD_ZEFF },
  { key: "mixed", num: "9", label: "Mixed", markdown: RAW_MD_MIXED },
];

function slugify(value: string): string {
  return value
    .toLowerCase()
    .replace(/[^a-z0-9]+/g, "-")
    .replace(/^-+|-+$/g, "");
}

function parseMarkdown(source: string): Block[] {
  const lines = source.replace(/\r\n/g, "\n").split("\n");
  const blocks: Block[] = [];
  let index = 0;

  while (index < lines.length) {
    const line = lines[index].trimEnd();

    if (!line.trim()) {
      index += 1;
      continue;
    }

    if (/^---+$/.test(line.trim())) {
      blocks.push({ kind: "rule" });
      index += 1;
      continue;
    }

    const heading = /^(#{1,4})\s+(.+)$/.exec(line);
    if (heading) {
      const text = heading[2].trim();
      blocks.push({
        kind: "heading",
        level: heading[1].length,
        text,
        id: text.startsWith("Part ") ? slugify(text) : undefined,
      });
      index += 1;
      continue;
    }

    if (line.trimStart().startsWith("|") && index + 1 < lines.length) {
      const divider = lines[index + 1].trim();
      if (/^\|?\s*:?-{3,}/.test(divider)) {
        const tableLines: string[] = [line];
        index += 2;
        while (index < lines.length && lines[index].trimStart().startsWith("|")) {
          tableLines.push(lines[index].trimEnd());
          index += 1;
        }
        const cells = (row: string) =>
          row
            .trim()
            .replace(/^\|/, "")
            .replace(/\|$/, "")
            .split("|")
            .map((cell) => cell.trim());
        blocks.push({
          kind: "table",
          header: cells(tableLines[0]),
          rows: tableLines.slice(1).map(cells),
        });
        continue;
      }
    }

    const paragraph: string[] = [line.trim()];
    index += 1;
    while (index < lines.length) {
      const next = lines[index].trimEnd();
      if (!next.trim()) break;
      if (/^(#{1,4})\s+/.test(next) || /^---+$/.test(next.trim())) break;
      if (next.trimStart().startsWith("|") && index + 1 < lines.length && /^\|?\s*:?-{3,}/.test(lines[index + 1].trim())) break;
      paragraph.push(next.trim());
      index += 1;
    }
    blocks.push({ kind: "paragraph", text: paragraph.join(" ") });
  }

  return blocks;
}

function renderMath(source: string): string {
  try {
    return katex.renderToString(source, {
      throwOnError: false,
      strict: "ignore",
      output: "html",
    });
  } catch {
    return source;
  }
}

function renderPlainSegment(text: string, keyPrefix: string): React.ReactNode[] {
  const chunks = text.split(/(\*\*[^*]+\*\*|`[^`]+`)/g).filter(Boolean);
  return chunks.map((chunk, index) => {
    const key = `${keyPrefix}-plain-${index}`;
    if (chunk.startsWith("**") && chunk.endsWith("**")) {
      return <strong key={key}>{chunk.slice(2, -2)}</strong>;
    }
    if (chunk.startsWith("`") && chunk.endsWith("`")) {
      return <code key={key}>{chunk.slice(1, -1)}</code>;
    }
    return <React.Fragment key={key}>{chunk}</React.Fragment>;
  });
}

function InlineContent({ text }: { text: string }) {
  const chunks = text.split(/(\$[^$\n]+\$)/g).filter(Boolean);
  return (
    <>
      {chunks.map((chunk, index) => {
        const key = `inline-${index}`;
        if (chunk.startsWith("$") && chunk.endsWith("$")) {
          return (
            <span
              key={key}
              className="qbankMath"
              dangerouslySetInnerHTML={{ __html: renderMath(chunk.slice(1, -1)) }}
            />
          );
        }
        return <React.Fragment key={key}>{renderPlainSegment(chunk, key)}</React.Fragment>;
      })}
    </>
  );
}

function QuestionBankTable({ block }: { block: TableBlock }) {
  return (
    <div className="qbankTableWrap">
      <table className="qbankTable">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            {block.header.map((cell, index) => (
              <th key={`head-${index}`}><InlineContent text={cell} /></th>
            ))}
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          {block.rows.map((row, rowIndex) => (
            <tr key={`row-${rowIndex}`}>
              {row.map((cell, cellIndex) => (
                <td key={`cell-${rowIndex}-${cellIndex}`}><InlineContent text={cell} /></td>
              ))}
            </tr>
          ))}
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
  );
}

export default function PeriodicityQuestionBank() {
  const [activeTopic, setActiveTopic] = useState<QTopicKey>("history");
  const activeMeta = Q_TOPICS.find((t) => t.key === activeTopic) ?? Q_TOPICS[0];
  const blocks = useMemo(() => parseMarkdown(activeMeta.markdown), [activeMeta.markdown]);

  return (
    <section className="qbankRoot" data-release={RELEASE}>
      <style>{`
        .qbankRoot { color: #eef3f8; max-width: 1120px; margin: 0 auto; }
        .qbankHero { border: 1px solid #2d4b69; border-radius: 18px; padding: 24px; margin-bottom: 22px; background: radial-gradient(circle at top right, rgba(95,212,234,.13), transparent 40%), linear-gradient(145deg, #112235, #0d1b2a); }
        .qbankKicker { margin: 0 0 8px; color: #e8b84b; font: 800 12px/1.2 ui-monospace, SFMono-Regular, Menlo, monospace; letter-spacing: .12em; text-transform: uppercase; }
        .qbankHero h2 { margin: 0; font: 700 clamp(28px, 5vw, 46px)/1.05 Georgia, serif; }
        .qbankHero p { color: #bfd0de; line-height: 1.7; max-width: 820px; }
        .qbankJump { display: flex; gap: 9px; flex-wrap: wrap; margin-top: 15px; }
        .qbankJump button { border: 1px solid #355977; background: #14283b; color: #eef3f8; border-radius: 999px; padding: 9px 13px; font-weight: 750; cursor: pointer; }
        .qbankJump button:hover { border-color: #e8b84b; color: #e8b84b; }
        .qbankContent { display: grid; gap: 0; }
        .qbankContent h1, .qbankContent h2, .qbankContent h3, .qbankContent h4 { scroll-margin-top: 135px; }
        .qbankContent h1 { margin: 44px 0 18px; padding: 16px 18px; border: 1px solid #385b79; border-radius: 14px; background: linear-gradient(90deg, rgba(232,184,75,.13), rgba(95,212,234,.07)); font: 700 clamp(24px, 4vw, 36px)/1.2 Georgia, serif; color: #fff4cc; }
        .qbankContent h2 { margin: 34px 0 12px; font: 700 clamp(21px, 3vw, 29px)/1.25 Georgia, serif; color: #8adff0; border-bottom: 1px solid #294762; padding-bottom: 9px; }
        .qbankContent h3 { margin: 26px 0 9px; font: 800 18px/1.3 system-ui, sans-serif; color: #e8b84b; }
        .qbankContent h4 { margin: 20px 0 7px; color: #b9d4e8; }
        .qbankContent p { margin: 0 0 11px; padding: 13px 15px; border-left: 2px solid #2e526f; border-radius: 0 10px 10px 0; background: rgba(18,34,50,.65); color: #d9e5ee; line-height: 1.75; overflow-wrap: anywhere; }
        .qbankContent p strong { color: #fff2ba; }
        .qbankContent code { border: 1px solid #35536c; border-radius: 5px; padding: 1px 5px; background: #091521; color: #9de8f5; }
        .qbankMath { display: inline-block; max-width: 100%; vertical-align: middle; overflow-x: auto; overflow-y: hidden; }
        .qbankRule { border: 0; border-top: 1px solid #294762; margin: 20px 0; }
        .qbankTableWrap { overflow-x: auto; border: 1px solid #2c4b65; border-radius: 13px; margin: 13px 0 20px; background: #0d1b29; }
        .qbankTable { width: 100%; min-width: 620px; border-collapse: collapse; }
        .qbankTable th { position: sticky; top: 0; background: #173149; color: #fff0b8; text-align: left; font-size: 13px; letter-spacing: .02em; }
        .qbankTable th, .qbankTable td { padding: 11px 12px; border-bottom: 1px solid #29465e; border-right: 1px solid #223e55; vertical-align: top; line-height: 1.55; }
        .qbankTable tr:last-child td { border-bottom: 0; }
        .qbankTable th:last-child, .qbankTable td:last-child { border-right: 0; }
        .qbankTabs { display: flex; gap: 9px; flex-wrap: wrap; margin-top: 16px; }
        .qbankTabs button { border: 1px solid #355977; background: #14283b; color: #cfe0ee; border-radius: 12px; padding: 10px 14px; font-weight: 750; font-size: 13.5px; cursor: pointer; display: inline-flex; align-items: center; gap: 7px; }
        .qbankTabs button:hover { border-color: #5fd4ea; color: #eef3f8; }
        .qbankTabs button.qbankTabActive { border-color: #e8b84b; background: linear-gradient(135deg, rgba(232,184,75,.22), rgba(95,212,234,.10)); color: #fff4cc; }
        .qbankTabNum { display: inline-flex; align-items: center; justify-content: center; min-width: 20px; height: 20px; border-radius: 999px; background: rgba(95,212,234,.18); color: #8adff0; font-size: 11.5px; font-weight: 800; }
        .qbankTabActive .qbankTabNum { background: rgba(232,184,75,.28); color: #fff4cc; }
        @media (max-width: 650px) {
          .qbankHero { padding: 19px 15px; border-radius: 14px; }
          .qbankContent p { padding: 11px 12px; font-size: 14px; }
          .qbankContent h1 { padding: 13px 14px; }
          .qbankTabs button { padding: 9px 11px; font-size: 12.5px; }
        }
      `}</style>

      <div className="qbankHero">
        <p className="qbankKicker">499-question JEE Advanced drill bank · 8 topic-wise sets</p>
        <h2>Periodicity Question Bank</h2>
        <p>
          Each topic below has its own 50-question practice set — Single Correct, Multiple Correct, Paragraph-based, Integer, Numerical Response, Assertion–Reason, Matrix Match, and one Innovative-format question — followed by a full answer key and complete worked solutions. The original 99-question comprehensive set is preserved in full inside the Mixed tab.
        </p>
        <div className="qbankTabs" role="tablist" aria-label="Question bank topics">
          {Q_TOPICS.map((t) => (
            <button
              key={t.key}
              type="button"
              role="tab"
              aria-selected={t.key === activeTopic}
              className={t.key === activeTopic ? "qbankTabActive" : undefined}
              onClick={() => setActiveTopic(t.key)}
            >
              <span className="qbankTabNum">{t.num}</span>
              {t.label}
            </button>
          ))}
        </div>
      </div>

      <div className="qbankContent">
        {blocks.map((block, index) => {
          const key = `block-${index}`;
          if (block.kind === "rule") return <hr className="qbankRule" key={key} />;
          if (block.kind === "table") return <QuestionBankTable block={block} key={key} />;
          if (block.kind === "paragraph") return <p key={key}><InlineContent text={block.text} /></p>;

          const content = <InlineContent text={block.text} />;
          if (block.level === 1) return <h1 id={block.id} key={key}>{content}</h1>;
          if (block.level === 2) return <h2 id={block.id} key={key}>{content}</h2>;
          if (block.level === 3) return <h3 id={block.id} key={key}>{content}</h3>;
          return <h4 id={block.id} key={key}>{content}</h4>;
        })}
      </div>
    </section>
  );
}
